<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     06-11 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Focuses On Economics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, back in his home territory for the
weekend, says he hopes to help forge an economic alliance among
farmers and industrial workers.
   ``We want to bring people beyond racism, beyond sexism and
beyond anti-Semitism,'' said Jackson, in brief statements to
reporters late Friday as he arrived in Chicago from a campaign
swing in California.
   Jackson said he would unveil his new plans today in a speech at
the headquarters of Operation Push, the civil rights group he
founded.
   The candidate said his latest 40-day campaign plan would focus
on economic proposals.
   ``We'll focus on ways to protect workers, farmers, the aged and
the poor against the ravages of Reagonomics,'' he said.
   Jackson was asked about polls indicating he would hurt
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis as a running mate against the
Republican ticket headed by George Bush.
   ``If we are within four points of Bush before the race begins,
we have the capacity to win,'' Jackson replied.
   Jackson came in second place to Dukakis in delegate and popular
vote count in the Democratic primaries, but a survey published in
The Washington Post suggested he would hurt the ticket among groups
whose support the Democrats need to win in the fall.
   And another poll, conducted for USA Today and Cable News
Network, indicated a Dukakis-led ticket with Jesse Jackson as the
running mate would lose to George Bush, 47 percent to 40 percent.
Otherwise, Dukakis would win, 45 percent to 39 percent, the survey
suggested.
   Dukakis has said only that Jackson deserves to be considered,
not that he has any special claim on the job.
   Confusion over Jackson's position on the matter has been
heightened in recent days by a Cable News Network report that
quoted him as saying he wants to be vice president.
   ``Let's leave it at consideration,'' Jackson said Friday in
California when asked to clarify the matter.
   Jackson has said he deserves to be offered a spot on the ticket,
but the ABC News-Post survey found that two-thirds of Democratic
voters believe the nominee has the right to ``choose anyone he
wants'' as a running mate. Only three in 10 said the second spot on
the ticket should automatically go to the second-place finisher in
the primaries, the poll said.
   The ABC-Post poll said Jackson was the vice presidential choice
of 36 percent of all registered Democrats. However, nearly
one-quarter of those surveyed said they would be less likely to
vote for Dukakis if Jackson were on the ticket. Only 12 percent
said they would be more likely to vote Democratic with Jackson in
the No. 2 spot, the poll said.
   Earlier Friday, Jackson said in California that he has better
credentials than anyone else in politics to be the Democratic vice
presidential nominee.
   While others may be qualified, Jackson said, none has shown
ability to win 7 million votes as he did in the primary season or
has his combination of regional and political strengths to balance
a ticket headed by Dukakis.
   ``We meet virtually every stated qualification for serious
consideration on the ticket,'' he said. ``No one else at this point
that's active in politics has shown the breadth of support I have
shown at the voting polls; no one else has shown the ability to
impact on the country's tone and the party's priorities.
   ``They may have state credentials. They've not shown themselves
to have national vote-getting potential,'' Jackson told reporters
who accompanied him to a two-day working vacation at the posh La
Costa health spa north of San Diego.
   Jackson left La Costa Friday afternoon to head to return to
Chicago, where he planned to meet with civil rights leaders and
continue plans for the convention.
   Although visibly tired and talking very softly after his long
flight, Jackson brought a touch of California casualness to the
chilly Chicago night.
   The often soberly dressed candidate was wearing blue jeans,
leather sandals and a black jacket bearing the emblem of the
International Longshoremen's and Warehousemen's Union. He also wore
a silver pin in the form of a stevedore's pick _ a symbol of the
union.
</TEXT>
