<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Politics-Quotes     06-11 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Politics-Quotes,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quotes From the Presidential Campaign Trail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some comments Friday from the
presidential campaign trail:
   
   JESSE JACKSON, saying he has the best credentials of anyone in
politics to be the vice presidential nominee: ``We meet virtually
every stated qualification for serious consideration on the ticket.
No one else at this point that's active in politics has shown the
breadth of support I have shown at the voting polls; no one else
has shown the ability to impact on the country's tone and the
party's priorities.''
   
   MICHAEL DUKAKIS, asked whether he plans to respond to George
Bush's attacks that he's an elitist by bringing up Bush's own
background, which includes Yale University: ``I really am not
interested. I don't think the American people are interested. I
think that's a losing strategy.''
   
   GEORGE BUSH, saying he finds it curious that Dukakis has accused
him of dirty politics after he attacked Dukakis' domestic and
foreign policies: ``You're looking at a guy who's been getting hit
for six months, guilt by association, and all kinds of personal
attacks. What happens now, they raise the mudslinging thing. This
is going to be a fun campaign.''
   
   REP. WILLIAM GRAY III of Pennsylvania, drafting committee
chairman, hoping to craft a party platform that suits both Dukakis
and Jackson: ``As we go through the discussion of issues _ drugs,
education, civil rights, health care ... hopefully they'll realize
that their differences are not that great and begin to come to a
consensus of their own.''
   
   PAUL KIRK, Democratic Party chief, pushing his dream of a short
and readable platform: ``I don't think we'll end up with the Yellow
Pages, an ad for every organized group.''
</TEXT>
