<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Nuclear     06-11 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Nuclear,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Allows Norwegian Inspection Of Heavy Water</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel and Norway have agreed that Norwegian
experts can inspect a shipment of Norwegian heavy water, a chemical
used in the production of nuclear weapons.
   Foreign Trade Minister Kurt Mosbakk told Parliament on Friday
that an agreement on the inspection was negotiated by Israel and
Norway in Oslo earlier this week, the national news agency NTB
reported.
   The news agency said Mosbakk told parliament that about half of
the 20 tons of heavy water sold to Israel in 1959 had vanished
through waste and evaporation.
   Norwegian experts would be allowed to inspect the remaining
half, NTB said.
   When Norway sold Israel the water almost 30 years ago the
contract stipulated that Norway had the right to inspect the water
and that it could be used for peaceful purposes only.
   Norway did not raise the question of inspection until Israeli
nuclear technician Mordechai Vanunu told a British newspaper that
Israel had used heavy water to produce plutonium for use in nuclear
weapons. Vanunu is serving an 18-year prison term in Israel for
treason.
   In three previous rounds of negotiations about the inspection
issue, Israel rejected a Norwegian proposal to transfer its
inspection right to the Vienna-based International Atom Energy
Agency.
   Since Norway started production of heavy water in the late
1930s, about 450 tons have been exported, mostly for scientific
research. Ten countries, including Israel, received amounts large
enough for use in nuclear reactors.
   Two nuclear powers, France and Britain, received heavy water
from Norway on the condition that they did no re-export it. Seven
other import countries have signed the nuclear non-proliferation
treaty, which allows on-site inspection. Israel has not signed the
treaty.
</TEXT>
