<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 0343EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama     06-11 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama Spurns U.S. Ban On Its Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama shrugged off Washington's move
to ban from the United States Panamanian officials supporting Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega and warned that Panama could bar U.S.
officials also.
   The ban, announced Friday in Washington, was the latest in a
series of steps the United States has taken in recent months to
show displeasure with Panama's leader.
   President Reagan's order bars from the United States top
Panamanian government and military officials known to back Noriega,
the country's military commander and the power behind its civilian
government.
   A State Department official said the order would probably affect
several hundred Panamanians.
   Boris Moreno, director of Panama's National Information Service,
responded to the order Friday by saying, ``We could not care less
about any lists made up by the Reagan administration.
   ``The United States is free to make as many lists as it wants of
Panamanians it does not want to admit there, just as we can make
our lists of U.S. citizens we do not want in Panama,'' he said.
   The Reagan administration has imposed sweeping economic
sanctions against Panama in an effort to force the ouster of
Noriega, who was indicted in February by a federal grand jury in
Florida on drug-trafficking charges.
   Romulo Escobar Bethancourt, president of the pro-government
Democratic Revolutionary Party, said Friday that the United States
scuttled an offer by Colombia to provide $70 million in aid to help
Panama through the financial crunch caused by the sanctions.
   He said the Panamanian government first negotiated with Japan
and Taiwan and when those discussions broke down, it turned to
Colombia, which agreed to provide the money if it would be returned
when U.S.-Panamanian relations improved.
   ``Then the U.S. insulted Colombia and blocked the negotiations
by saying the Colombian money came from drug trafficking,'' Escobar
Bethancourt said.
   About $50 million in Panamanian government assets has been
frozen in U.S. banks. Panama uses the U.S. dollar as its currency.
   In announcing the ban on Panamanian government officials, Reagan
said Noriega and his hand-picked president, Manuel Solis Palma,
``are preventing the legitimate government of President Eric Arturo
Delvalle from restoring order and democracy in that country.''
   Delvalle was deposed by the National Assembly in February the
day after he tried to fire Noriega.
   After he was ousted, his family took refuge in the U.S.
ambassador's residence, and Delvalle apparently spends much time
there. He often meets there with English-speaking journalists, who
are asked not to disclose the location.
   At other times, according to sources speaking on condition of
anonymity, Delvalle stays in safe homes provided by the U.S.
government at its military installations in Panama.
   ``If they want him (Delvalle) to re-establish democracy, as they
say, let him come out of his little Pentagon in the U.S. bases
here,'' Moreno said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
