<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 0345EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Bribery     06-11 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Bribery,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Prime Minister's Office Official Arrested For Taking Bribes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese authorities have arrested a former public
relations officer with the Prime Minister's Office for allegedly
accepting bribes from an advertising company, authorities said
today.
   Officials from the Tokyo prosecutor's office on Friday arrested
Shigeru Suzuki, 59, a former councilor in charge of government
public relations, for accepting bribes in return for extending
favors, said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Also arrested were two men who allegedly offered the bribes to
Suzuki: Saburo Toyama, 67, chairman of an Osaka-based advertising
company, and Tsutomu Nishida, 56, head of its Tokyo branch.
   The Asahi Shimbun, a nationally circulated daily, reported today
that investigators found the two had entertained Suzuki with
dinners in Tokyo and golf outings costing a total of $7,200.
   The entertainment led to increased orders for television
advertisements, the report said.
   The prosecutor's office refused to confirm or deny the report.
   Another former Prime Minister's Office official was arrested in
May for allegedly accepting about $18,400 in bribes from
advertising agents.
</TEXT>
