<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Malaysia-US,0158</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Leader Denies Asking United States to Drop Tariff
Preferences</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A labor leader today denied asking
AFL-CIO officials to press Washington to drop preferential tariffs
to protest the government's alleged human rights violations.
   Vethamuthu David, head of the Malaysian Trade Unions Congress,
said his union is ``fully convinced that labor and human rights
problems in our country can be solved within the Malaysian
context.''
   Government officials attacked David, who also belongs to an
opposition party, after reports last week that he had asked AFL-CIO
officials for help. They said his reported requests to the AFL-CIO
could hurt the Southeast Asian nation's economy.
   David was arrested and held without trial in October under the
Internal Security Act for allegedly fanning racial tensions. He was
released June 3.
   The government has used the act to arrest more than 100 people,
including opposition leaders, in the past year.
