<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Joseph     06-11 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Joseph,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>83-Year-old White Anti-Apartheid Activist Seriously Ill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Helen Joseph, one of the first
white South Africans ever banned by the government for
anti-apartheid activities, is in serious condition at a hospital.
   Mrs. Joseph, 83, had been reported ``critical and sinking fast''
by a family friend Thursday. The Johannesburg General Hospital said
Friday she was in serious condition, but the family had asked that
no further details be released.
   For the past three decades it has been illegal to quote Mrs.
Joseph in South Africa.
   In 1957, Mrs. Joseph received the first of several banning
orders, which for 16 of the next 25 years prohibited her from
leaving Johannesburg, attending political meetings, writing for
publication and communicating with other banned people.
   In 1962, she became the first South African placed under house
arrest, which required her to stay in her cottage north of
Johannesburg from dawn to dusk, report to police daily and visit
with no more than one person at a time.
   Born in England in 1905, Helen Fennell came to South Africa from
India in 1931, and, as a social worker, began participating in
anti-apartheid campaigns at the age of 48.
   She helped found the Federation of South African Women, which in
1956 staged one of the biggest protests in the country's history _
a march by 20,000 black women on the government buildings in
Pretoria.
</TEXT>
