<1ST_LINE>r a PM-InventorsCongress     06-11 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Inventors Congress,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inventors Gather To Market Their Gadgets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REDWOOD FALLS, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Necessity may be the mother of
invention but the possiblity of making a million dollars seems to
help.
   An attorney who helped organize the 31st annual Minnesota
Inventors Congress says some gadget makers come with dollar signs
in their eyes.
   ``Some are quite naive,'' said William Braddock, a Minneapolis
patent attorney. ``They will come and say `I've got this invention.
It works. Where do I go to get my million dollars?' It's often that
simplistic. We try to put them on the right road.''
   David Ludvigson, of Sioux Falls, S.D., said a harrowing
experience led to his invention.
   ``I was almost killed off by a kid on a skateboard one night, so
I went home and invented the `thrasher flasher,''' said Ludvigson,
a camera repairman and participant in the three-day Inventors
Congress, which began Friday.
   His thrasher flasher is essentially a headlight for a
skateboard. It's a low-intensity strobe light attached to the
board's wheel axle.
   Like many of the 88 exhibitors and 108 inventors at the
congress, Ludvigson is hoping someone will spot the flasher and
decide to market it.
   People come to the congress, which has been held annually in
Redwood Falls since 1958, not only to get exposure and to market
their ideas, but also to find direction.
   Others come to get the public's reaction to their inventions,
said Andrew Amoroso, a business development specialist from the
U.S. Small Business Administration.
   ``They want to know, `Is there any market for my products? I
have shown it to my family, and they all think it is a good idea,
but what about John Q. Public? What is he going to think about
it?''' Amoroso said.
   Some people, such as brothers Darrell, Vernon and Richard Fox of
Langdon, N.D., are compulsive inventors and design products after
seeing a need for it.
   They invented an aluminum can crusher, an electrical contraption
that hangs on the rim of garbage cans and crushes cans.
   ``We saw that whole cans were really causing space problems,''
Darrell Fox said.
</TEXT>
