<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Administration Proposes Tougher Stance Against Coal
Wildcatters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration has asked Congress
to make it a felony to strip mine coal without a permit.
   Legislation proposed Friday by the Office of Surface Mining
Reclamation and Enforcement which calls for a maximum prison term
of five years for people convicted of mining without a permit is
seen as the administration's attempt to get tough with coal
wildcatters.
   `The civil procedures are so ponderous, it's difficult to keep
up with the wildcatters,'' said office spokesman Alan Cole.
   Strip mining without a permit is now a civil offense with a top
penalty of $22,500, but the bill also would allow a judge to impose
a fine of up to $250,000 against a convicted individual and a fine
of up to $500,000 against a convicted organization.
</TEXT>
