<HEAD>Agreement Reached With Trucking Companies In Midwest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Teamsters union and an employer group
representing some 50 small and regional trucking companies in the
Middle West has reached agreement on a new three-year contract.
   The contract, announced Friday, with the Motor Carrier Labor
Advisory Council of Chicago covers some 35,000 drivers and terminal
workers and parallels an agreement signed earlier by the union and
the industry's main bargaining arm, Trucking Management Inc.
   Under the terms of both contracts, drivers get a 35 cents per
hour wage increase in each of three years, the first retroactive to
April 1 when the old pacts expired. The basic wage rate under the
old agreement was $14.71 an hour.
   ``The monetary terms are the same,'' said Chip Roth, a Teamster
spokesman. ``I think you could describe the non-monetary
differences as inconsequential.''
