<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UNESCO-Press     06-11 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UNESCO-Press,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNESCO Plays Down Controversial Communications Order</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY DUNPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UNESCO officials have backed away from a proposal
to create a global communications order that some Western nations
viewed as a threat to the freedom of the press.
   The U.S. observer to UNESCO cautiously praised the
recommendations, released by the group's executive board Friday.
   The new communications strategy played down establishing a new
world information and communication order. The concept lay at the
heart of a decade-old debate at the 158-nation U.N. Educational,
Scientific and Cultural Organization and helped convince the United
States and Britain to withdraw.
   The board's recommendations go to UNESCO Director General
Federico Mayor, who is trying to persuade those two nations to
rejoin.
   The report's communications section admitted that journalists
had widely interpreted UNESCO's efforts to establish a new world
order as aimed at ``undermining freedom of information.''
   ``This resulted in a misunderstanding that was used to sully the
organization's image,'' it said.
   The section said UNESCO should ``explore the possibilities of a
new strategy ... that will dispel the misunderstanding.''
   It said the strategy should emphasize ``development of critical
acumen among (media) users, the ability for individuals and
communities to react to any kind of manipulation (by the media) and
to become familiair with the means available to users to defend
their right of reply.''
   The section also said UNESCO should seek to ``ensure a free and
wider and more balanced flow of information.''
   In the past, Western governments and media groups have tried to
replace the words ``more balanced'' with ``unrestricted.''
   These governments and Western media groups expressed concern
that the proposed new world communications order could lead to
codes of conduct and licensing of journalists.
   U.S. observer Richard T. Miller said the latest recommendations,
approved by consensus without a vote, contained ``scope for
positive change.''
   ``However, I am distressed at the tone'' in the communications
section, which ``tries to set up an adversary relationship between
the media and its audience.''
   The board's recommendations, presented at the end of its spring
meeting, are intended to guide Mayor in preparation of UNESCO's
plan of activities for the l990s.
   At the board's opening meeting three weeks ago, Mayor, a Spanish
scientist who took office in November, proposed that UNESCO's 14
major programs be reduced to five. He suggested that the
organization should do fewer things but do them better and with
more follow-up.
   The board has recommended cutting programs to seven. It added
one dealing with peace, human rights and elimination of
discrimination, and another that covers development studies.
   A group of 77 Third World countries and the Soviet bloc
criticized Mayor for dropping these programs from his plan for the
1990s.
   Along with communications, the peace and human rights proposals
have provoked controversial debates in the past.
   Mayor will use the document prepared by the board to draft an
outline of the plan for the 1990s for the fall meeting of the board.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
