<2ND_LINE>PM-Cambodia-US,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cambodia To Release American Prisoner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pro-Vietnamese government in Phnom
Penh will release an American who was captured 13 months ago after
illegaly crossing into Cambodia, the official Cambodian news agency
SPK said today.
   The agency said Sterling Brian Bono, 35, was seized on May 2,
1987 after he crossed the Thai border into the western Cambodian
province of Battambang.
   SPK did not say when Bono, of Las Animas, Colo., would leave
Cambodia.
   Some reports have said that Bono, a Vietnam war army veteran,
crossed into Cambodia to look for some 80 Americans still listed as
missing in action from the Indochina conflict. But others said Bono
hoped to locate and help Vietnamese he had known during the war who
he thought might have fled to the Thai-Cambodian border area.
   U.S. officials were aware of Bono's capture and said they were
working on his case through the International Red Cross. Washington
does not recognize the Phnom Penh government which was set up
following the late 1978 invasion of Cambodia by Vietnamese forces.
   Phnom Penh's Prime Minister, Hun Sen, spoke about Bono to
several Western correspondents visiting Phnom Penh last year.
   Phnom Penh is also known to be holding a number of Thais
captured along the frontier where Vietnamese and Phnom Penh troops
have been fighting Cambodian guerrillas since 1979.
</TEXT>
