<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 0542EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GemExpert     06-11 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gem Expert,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missing Woman's Body Found Floating In Hudson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of a gemologist who disappeared while
carrying more than $500,000 worth of diamonds was tossed into the
Hudson River after she was bludgeoned to death, officials said.
   Barbara Mangiameli, 33, a free-lance gemologist, was last seen
at her Manhattan apartment building on Feb. 4, when she had an
appointment to return six diamonds after a proposed sale fell
through.
   Her naked body, bound in the fetal position around the neck,
wrists and ankles, was found Thursday floating in the river near
the lower end of Manhattan, police said. Her body was covered by
plastic bags, police said.
   An autopsy Friday determined she died from multiple blunt force
injuries to the scalp and face that caused skull fractures, brain
contusions and brain hemorrhaging, said Ellen Borakove, a
spokeswoman for the medical examiner's office.
   ``She wasn't in the water for very long,'' Ms. Borakove said.
``She was not dead for a very long period of time from the time
they found her (Thursday). It certainly is not months. Whether its
weeks or days, I cannot pin it down.''
   She was identified through dental records, Ms. Borakove said.
   Two brothers who were friends of Ms. Mangiameli's were arrested
in the case April 11 and have been in custody without bail since,
police said.
   Raoul Rivalta, 48, and his brother Fausto, 33, allegedly
arranged a meeting between Ms. Mangiameli and a potential buyer
that never took place.
   Ms. Mangiameli called the diamonds' owner on Feb. 3 to say she
would return the six diamonds worth between $500,000 and $600,000
the next day.
   A resident of her apartment building saw her in the building's
vestibule the afternoon of Feb. 4, relatives said. She was not seen
after that.
   According to the complaint, Fausto Rivalta sold a pear-shaped
diamond that was among those Ms. Mangiameli had in her possession
to a West Palm Beach, Fla. pawnshop for $14,000 on Feb. 17.
</TEXT>
