<DOCNO> AP880611-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 0542EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Yugoslavia     06-11 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Police Feared Popular Opposition; Party Calls For Radical
Change</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yugoslavia's increasingly open press
has reported that federal authorities were worried about a popular
uprising if they seized control in Slovenia, the nation's most
liberal republic.
   The ruling Communist Party, meanwhile, called for radical
economic changes on Friday, including freer, profit-oriented
markets and more foreign investment to overcome Yugoslavia's
deepening economic crisis.
   Reports have circulated for several weeks that military
authorities in Slovenia were thinking about stepping in to quell
liberal tendencies in the northernmost of Yugoslavia's six
republics.
   Federal officials and Communist leaders in the republic have
denied any plans for such an action.
   But NIN magazine on Friday published what it said were excerpts
of a transcript of a discussion of the police role after such a
takeover. A police official, whom the magazine did not identify,
was quoted as speaking of police ability ``to control the situation
after the arrests, since it is believed that the people will come
out into the streets.''
   NIN also quoted Igor Bavcar, a spokesman for a group formed to
fight the arrests of two journalists who first wrote of the alleged
takeover, as saying the transcript means ``nobody believes that the
stories about the coup have been fabricated.''
   Authorities have denied any link between the journalists report
on the takeover and their arrests last week by military authorities.
   Police have said the journalists were arrested along with a
soldier after an unmarked document on combat readiness was found in
their possession.
   Bavcar said his group would decide this weekend whether or not
to call for a 15-minute general strike next Tuesday in protest at
the arrests.
   The Slovenian daily Delo reported from Ljubljana that more than
7,000 people have signed a petition calling for the release of the
trio.
   Money is pouring into a special account to help the families of
those held, and more than 200 companies, Communist party cells and
trade union groups have backed the petition for release, Delo said.
   Slovenia's official lawyers' union issued a statement saying
public unease over the case should be seen as popular concern over
preserving gains of democratization.
   ``State organs cannot any longer demand in advance uncritical
trust from the people,'' the lawyers said, calling for strict
adherence to the law in the handling of the controversial case.
   The party's 52-page blueprint for economic change, largely
adopted at a party conference last month, advocated ``the
strengthening of market mechanisms'' and recomended measures to
attract ``the investment of more foreign capital'' in the Yugoslav
economy.
   It said the party supported ``investment of private funds'' in
small businesses as a means of ``restructuring the economy and
overcoming high unemployment.''
   ``The theses call for sweeping economic reforms to ensure the
autonomy of enterprises, the full affirmation of all elements of
the market and of economic laws, a single home market and an
opening to the world,'' the document said.
   Yugoslavia suffers from 150 percent inflation, a $21 billion
debt, worker unrest and heavily endebted firms.
   The government recently undertook a strict austerity program
curbing wages and spending as part of sweeping changes to be
completed before the end of the year.
   One of the party's most radical proposals is to base the
economy, for the first time, on the profit motive, ending the
practice of subsidizing and, when necessary, rescuing money-losing
enterprises.
   The party blueprint also contained a reference to human rights,
widely seen as a victory for a liberal faction in the party.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
