<DOCNO> AP880611-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 0519EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TardyScholar     06-11 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tardy Scholar,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commencement Brings Vindication for Tardy Scholar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose doctoral dissertation was rejected by
a faculty committee in 1942 but hailed by historians four decades
later as a pioneering work has received his Ph.D.
   ``Celebrity is a new status and it's hard to get used to,''
Frank Bourgin, who gained national attention earlier this year when
his dissertation was finally accepted, said Friday.
   ``But if all this hoopla wasn't going on, I think I'd be feeling
quite depressed,'' said the 77-year-old retired civil servant, who
lives in Chevy Chase, Md. ``My polio is acting up, my walking
ability is reduced and I'm having difficulty getting out of a chair.
   ``But this attention, the commencement,'' he added, ``is such
great compensation.''
   Bourgin was a graduate student at Chicago and a disciple of the
late Professor Charles Merriam, the leading political scientist of
the day and a member of then-President Franklin D. Roosevelt's
circle of advisers known as the ``Brain Trust.''
   Under Merriam's guidance, Bourgin re-examined the history of
government planning in the United States. He then argued in his
dissertation that the country's early leaders, Alexander Hamilton
and Thomas Jefferson among them, had intended to use the powers of
the federal government to develop the fledgling nation's resources
through public works and other projects.
   The paper challenged the then-common conviction that Roosevelt's
New Deal social programs marked a departure from laissez-faire
principles attributed to the founding fathers.
   By the time his paper was rejected as not yet ``in satisfactory
shape,'' Bourgin was married with a child to support. He said he
couldn't afford to return to campus as a full-time student to
revise his manuscript, so he locked it away in a box.
   In the intervening years, he manufactured light fixtures, owned
a chain of men's clothing stores in Minnesota and became a federal
civil servant, eventually rising to become regional director for
the federal Office of Emergency Planning, supervising a five-state
region in the Midwest.
   ``But I never changed my mind on the essential idea I'd
developed in my paper,'' he recalled. ``I maintained my interest in
history, I looked everywhere, and whenever I read, I was constantly
looking to see if someone else had it.
   ``I was so convinced I was right, and so convinced of the
importance of it that tenacity was the easy part,'' he said.
   Bourgin's reward came last year, when he read historian Arthur
Schlesinger Jr.'s ``Cycles of American History,'' a chapter of
which made essentially the same argument Bourgin's paper had
offered nearly a half-century earlier.
   He wrote to Schlesinger, who looked at the dissertation and
wrote back: ``Congratulations on your path-breaking work ... I am
astonished by the fate of your thesis at Chicago.''
   Emboldened, Bourgin set in process a motion that culminated
Friday with Bourgin receiving his doctorate.
   ``I'm not sure how the paper was rejected the first time, but my
best guess is that after professor Merriam retired, my dissertation
became a kind of orphan.
   ``Also, I was already working at making a living while it was
being considered and I think the chairman of the department at the
time may not have wanted the degree cheapened by giving it to
someone who wouldn't use it,'' Bourgin said.
   ``I don't know if all that makes it any sweeter,'' he said.
``But it certainly has made the last few months of my life an
interesting time.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
