<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SpaceShuttle     06-11 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Space Shuttle,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Officials Cautiously Optimistic About Aug. 31 Shuttle Launch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pieces are coming together and
officials here are confident they soon will launch their first
space shuttle mission since Challenger exploded nearly 2{ years ago.
   Two 126-foot-tall solid fuel booster rockets were hooked up
Friday with a huge external fuel tank, and on Thursday the stack
will be joined with the shuttle Discovery.
   The projected liftoff date is Aug. 31. But NASA officials
caution the schedule is tight, with many milestones to be passed.
   ``The August target is optimistic, for sure, but given where we
are today, we've got a shot at it,'' launch director Bob Sieck said.
   ``We're getting close and there's a feeling of excitement
here,'' said astronaut Bob Crippen, who as deputy director of
shuttle operations will make the decision in the closing minutes
whether Discovery should be launched.
   Crippen, a veteran of four space shuttle flights, and Sieck
spoke at a news conference.
   When Discovery reaches the launch pad, workers will prepare it
for a critical flight readiness firing of its three main liquid
fuel engines.
   The 20-second ignition, with Discovery bolted firmly to the pad,
will test several modifications made to the powerful engines during
the long period the shuttles have been grounded.
   It also will provide countdown experience for the launch team.
   Also ahead, on Tuesday and on July 26, are two more full-scale
firings of test models of the solid fuel booster rockets at the
Morton Thiokol facility in Utah. A faulty booster joint was blamed
for the explosion of Challenger and loss of its seven crew members
on Jan. 28, 1986.
   Testing of the redesigned booster has gone so well that NASA was
able to confidently assemble here the two rockets for Discovery's
flight.
   Assigned to fly Discovery on the mission will be Frederick H.
Hauck, the commander; Richard O. Covey, the pilot; and mission
specialists George Nelson, Michael Lounge and David Hilmers.
   They are to deploy a communications satellite and conduct 11
science and technology experiments.
</TEXT>
