<1ST_LINE>r a PM-VDTVeto     06-11 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-VDT Veto,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>County Executive's Veto Of VDT Law Angers Unions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAUPPAUGE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union leaders criticized the Suffolk
County executive for his veto of a bill that would have made the
county the nation's first major municipality to regulate video
display terminals.
   ``I'm outraged at the county executive's submissiveness to the
business community, whose arguments of the cost of the legislation
are innocuous and untrue,'' state AFL-CIO President Edward J.
Cleary saud Friday.
   But Executive Patrick Halpin told reporters that several
businesses threatened to leave the county or cancel relocation
plans if he signed the legislation.
   ``In both cases, the consequence would be hundreds, if not
thousands of jobs lost, and these are losses that I do not think
Suffolk can afford,'' Halpin said.
   Under the bill, employers would be required to pay 80 percent of
the cost of eye examinations, glass lenses and frames on a yearly
basis, if needed.
   It also required 15-minute work breaks every three hours and
outlined strict work station standards, including what type of
chairs should be used, adjustability of the terminals and office
lighting.
   ``This law would cost local businesses millions of dollars to
implement at the same time that their competitors in other areas
faced no restrictions,'' Halpin said. ``This would be an economic
disadvantage to them of no small consequence.''
   Donald Rechler, chairman of the Association for a Better Long
Island, a group of 40 developers, said after the veto was announced
Friday: ``The economy of Suffolk County has just breathed a sigh of
relief.''
   The Legislature could override Halpin's veto with 12 votes. The
measure was originally approved by 13 of the 18 legislators.
</TEXT>
