<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MerryWidows     06-11 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Merry Widows,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kitchen Band Entertains Nursing Home Residents With Old Songs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>McHENRY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A band of widows low on talent but high on
spirit grabbed a few unconventional musical instruments _ a
washboard, a soap bottle filled with beans and a teapot _ donned
floral aprons, and embarked on a sentimental journey.
   ``You don't have to have talent,'' said one of the Happy
Tooters, Frances Widhalm, after a recent performance. ``Almost none
of us does. All you have to do is like music.''
   At 88, Mrs. Widhalm is the oldest of the Happy Tooters, with the
youngest being 62. The 15 women, all widows, perform at nursing
homes and retirement villages, choosing their material with people
their own age in mind.
   The songs are traditional, like ``Melody of Love,'' ``Alley
Cat'' and ``Peg O' My Heart.'' The orchestration, however, is
anything but traditional.
   The Happy Tooters play kazoos, shake soap bottles filled with
beans and croon into the spouts of teapots. Pianist Isabelle Miller
and drummer Madeline Behm play the only ``real'' instruments, but
someone occasionally chimes in on the triangle.
   Like any band worth its gigs, the Happy Tooters have uniforms _
blue floral aprons over white blouses with blue floral bonnets to
match.
   ``I've never sat in the audience, so I don't know what we sound
like,'' said Marion Schmitt, 74, of McHenry. ``But we do have fun,
and I think we do bring pleasure to people.''
   Mrs. Schmitt, the band's organizer and conductor, said she first
organized a kitchen band in November 1985, when her chapter of
Naim, a Roman Catholic support group for widows and widowers, was
slated to provide entertainment at a dinner in the Rockford diocese.
   The Happy Tooters made their debut March 9, 1986. It was
supposed to be a one-shot deal, but the show biz bug bit. They've
been touring northern Illinois ever since _ weather permitting.
   ``The ladies are getting up in age,'' Mrs. Schmitt explained.
``We try not to peform too much in July and August, when it's hot.''
   Cold weather and rain can also be a problem.
   ``We don't like to travel when the weather is unstable, we're
such a bunch of crips,'' Mrs. Miller said. ``But playing for people
makes us feel better.''
   Mrs. Schmitt pointed out to the elderly and infirm people who
were beginning to gather in the activity room at a home before a
performance.
   ``You see some pretty sad faces out there,'' she said. ``It
makes us feel good to see them smile.''
</TEXT>
