<HEAD>Cigarette Suit Jurors Complete Fourth Day Of Deliberations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury will take the weekend off
before resuming deliberations in a cigarette liability lawsuit
carried on by the widower of a lung-cancer victim who smoked for 40
years.
   The jury considering the Cipollone case ended their fourth day
of deliberations about 5 p.m. Friday with no verdict. It will
resume deliberations Monday.
   Jurors asked few questions during deliberations, which began at
noon Tuesday. They are considering whether or not to award damages
to Antonio Cipollone for the 1984 death of his wife, Rose, at 58.
   During the four-month trial, he charged that cigarette-makers
Lorillard Inc., Liggett Group Inc. and Philip Morris Inc. misled
the public about the dangers of cigarette smoking and contributed
to Mrs. Cipollone's death.
   The companies contend she made an intelligent, strong-willed
choice to smoke knowing the risks. They argue smoking is not a
proven cancer-cause, and that her type of cancer isn't linked to
cigarettes anyway.
   On Friday, jurors asked if the 1984 Surgeon General's report on
smoking and health was in evidence and whether they could see it.
It wasn't, and the judge said they couldn't.
</TEXT>
