<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Palestinians, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0430,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat Loyalists Fight Syrian-Backed Guerrillas In Camps</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with more deaths. PICkS up 3rd
graf, `Police said ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yasser Arafat's Palestinian guerrillas
and Syrian-backed dissidents battled for control of two Beirut
refugee camps for the fourth day today. Police reported eight
people killed and 17 wounded.
   That raised the casualty toll since fighting erupted Wednesday
in the Bourj el-Barajneh and Chatilla camps to 18 dead and 77
wounded by police count.
   Police said Arafat's Fatah faction, the main component of the
Palestine Liberation Organization, and Col. Saeed Mousa's
Fatah-Uprising battled with howitzers, mortars, rocket-propelled
grenades and machine guns.
   The fighting raged despite efforts by a security commitee made
up of representatives from several Palestinian groups to arrange a
cease fire.
   ``Several cease-fire calls overnight were ignored,'' said a
police spokesman, who cannot be named under standing regulations.
   A Fatah spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said his
guerrillas ``repulsed several overnight attacks from outside the
camps'' by Mousa's fighters.
   Arafat loyalists had dislodged Mousa's guerrillas from both
shantytowns in a series of battles over the last two months. But
the dissidents have regrouped on the fringes of the shantytowns,
where Syrian troops are in control.
   Mousa broke away from the PLO in a Syrian-inspired 1983 mutiny
against Arafat's leadership and established his headquarters in
Damascus, the Syrtian capital.
   Clashes between the rival groups have persisted in the Beirut
camps despite a reconciliation effort between Arafat and Syrian
President Hafez Assad to end their 5-year-old feud.
</TEXT>
