<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FuneralHome     06-11 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Funeral Home,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dozens of Decaying Bodies Found In Funeral Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have discovered dozens of
decaying bodies ``stacked like cord wood'' inside a closed funeral
home and dug up the yard outside in search of more.
   ``We're treating it as a mass disaster right now,'' said Lou
Eliopulos, chief investigator for the Medical Examiner's Office.
   So far, 44 bodies have been found inside the Howell Morning
Glory Chapel funeral home.
   The state Department of Professional Regulation suspended owner
Lewis J. Howell's permit to operate a funeral home on Wednesday
after the initial discovery of eight decomposed bodies.
   After the bodies were discovered during a routine state
inspection last week, Howell said he hadn't disposed of the bodies
either because family members couldn't be reached for instructions
or because the city hadn't given him needed paperwork for indigent
burials.
   The chapel has no refrigeration units.
   ``At this point, I am convinced that there are no more bodies in
the building,'' Lt. Jim Suber said Friday night after 36 bodies
were found. ``We are finished here today.''
   However, officials planned to bring in a front-end loader to dig
up the yard behind Howell Morning Glory Chapel to search for
bodies, The Florida Times-Union and Jacksonville Journal reported
in today's editions.
   Florida Department of Law Enforcement technicians who dug up
portions of the yard Friday searching for evidence of burials found
nothing.
   But that was not the case inside the building.
   Some of the bodies found were ``stacked like cord wood in the
closet,'' one unidentified official told the newspaper.
   The bodies on the bottom of the pile, he said, ``were more like
skeletons than corpses.''
   Meanwhile, of the original eight bodies found, four were buried
in the city's indigent cemetery and four were cremated, said Virgil
Green, chief of the city Welfare Division.
   One had died July 17, 1987. Three others died in January and a
fifth died in April, Green said. Records could not be found to
determine the date of death for the other three bodies found
earlier in the week.
</TEXT>
