<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0881 06-11 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0881,0666</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army To Speed Up Appeal Process For Detainees</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with comments from Palestinian
lawyer on appeals process. PICKS up 16th graf, `Israel radio .. .'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army ordered a speedup in the judicial
review process for some of the 5,000 Palestinian arrested during
the Arab uprising in the occupied territories. Defense officials
said the new system would benefit detainees by increasing judicial
supervision.
   But Palestinian lawyer Jonathan Kuttab today called the move a
charade and said Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin ordered the changes
after all detainees decided last week to challenge the system by
filing appeals.
   About 2,000 Arabs are being held for up to six months without
charges, most of them taken into custody since the uprising began
Dec. 8. They are called administrative detainees. The army also
holds about 3,000 Arabs awaiting trial or serving prison terms on
charges of anti-Israeli violence.
   Underground leaders of the uprising set aside today as a ``Day
of Solidarity'' with Palestinian prisoners and called for renewed
anti-Israeli protests.
   On Friday, soldiers bulldozed the cinderblock house of an Arab
from the West Bank refugee camp Jelazoun after he was arrested on
suspicion that he stabbed an Israeli-appointed Arab mayor.
   In the West Bank village of Beita, troops expelled about 100
Israelis who were planting olive trees to protest the army's
uprooting of orchards and demolition of 14 Arab houses.
   The army measures were in reprisal for an April 6 clash between
villagers and Israeli teen-age West Bank settlers in which two
Arabs and a 15-year-old Jewish girl were killed.
   Also Friday, the Government Press Office reinstated the press
credentials of NBC Television correspondend Martin Fletcher after a
six-week suspension imposed because he allegedly violated military
censorship.
   Kuttab said the changes in the appeals process were ordered
because under the current system, the army would be unable to deal
with the expected wave of appeals.
   ``Within the next two weeks, all detainees will have filed
appeals,'' Kuttab told The Associated Press. ``This is going to
impose a heavy burden on the system.''
   Under present rules, a three-member military committee hears the
appeals, and then refers the case to the area commander for a final
decision.
   Rabin on Friday ordered a military judge to take the place of
the review committee and make the final ruling in the case, said
ministry spokesman Eitan Haber.
   Haber said the new system would benefit the detainees by
speeding up the appeals process. Israel radio quoted military
officials as saying Rabin also ordered the changes to increase
judicial supervision over administrative detention cases.
   Several weeks into the uprising, the army scrapped a major legal
safeguard for the detainees which required that they appear before
a judge within four days after their arrest.
   In Jelazoun, the army demolished the home of 26-year-old Khamis
Jawdat Faraj, arrested Thursday on charges he knifed Mayor Hassan
Tawil, 74, of the West Bank town El Bireh as an act of Palestinian
nationalism.
   Israel radio said Faraj confessed to stabbing Tawil, who was
recovering at a Jerusalem hospital.
   It took about 30 minutes for a big yellow bulldozer to level the
three-room house where Faraj lived with his 60-year-old mother. An
almond tree, a plum tree and a rose bush were left standing in the
yard.
   The army said Faraj was detained several times previously for
alleged participation in anti-Israeli disturbances.
   The tree-planting ceremony in Beita was organized by the
``Committee for Beita,'' a group trying to force authorities to
make reparations to villagers whose homes were destroyed or damaged
by the army as punishment.
   Jewish settlers and the army initially blamed the villagers for
the death of Israeli Tirza Porat in the April clash, but an army
report later determined she was accidentally killed by a bullet
fired by an Israeli guarding the group.
</TEXT>
