<HEAD>Detained Europeans Charged With Murder, Kidnapping</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Europeans and a Filipino of
German descent arrested this week for alleged links with communist
rebels have been charged with murder and kidnapping, the military
said today.
   Brig. Gen. Alejandro Galido, chief of the military's Southern
Luzon Command, said in a telephone interview the charges were filed
by his legal officer Friday before a civil court in Quezon province.
   Galido declined to elaborate on the charges but said his command
had ``heavy evidence'' against the Rev. Klaus Schmidt, 52, a West
German Protestant minister; Stellan Hermansson, 30, a Swede who
says he is a free-lance journalist; and Antonio Bosch, a Filipino
businessman.
   Members of Sweden's Young Communist League said Friday in
Stockholm that Hermansson was their president. They said he arrived
in the Philippines on May 18 to gather information for lectures and
was to return to Sweden today.
   Hermansson and the two others were arrested during what the
military called ``clearing operations'' Wednesday in a
rebel-infested area of Quezon province. They were being held at the
command headquarters in the provincial capital, Lucena, 60 miles
southeast of Manila.
   Command spokesman Col. Hernani Figueroa said earlier the charges
stem from a New People's Army raid on the Quezon town of San
Francisco in February. Two people were killed in the attack, and
the rebels abducted two soldiers who later escaped.
   Hermansson denied the charges, said Eha Arg, first secretary of
the Swedish embassy, who visited him Friday. She said he told her
he was not even in the country in February.
   Galido said it was up to the judge to decide whether to grant
the three bail. The judge of the Municipal Circuit Court in
Mulanay, in Quezon province, has scheduled a hearing for Tuesday.
</TEXT>
