<HEAD>Police Mistakenly Arrest Most-Wanted Look-Alike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man mistaken by police as a fugitive killer
featured on a television crime show says he was frisked, handcuffed
and arrested before police realized they had the wrong man.
   ``Two of them had guns on me,'' Gary Bennett said in an article
in today's editions of the New York Daily News. ``One cop told me
if I would have moved or even twitched, he would have shot me.''
   Bennett, 28, said he thought the four officers who approached
him in a shopping mall parking lot were going to ticket him for his
car's noisy muffler.
   Instead, he was taken to the station house for two hours because
police thought he resembled the fugitive shown on the ``America's
Most Wanted'' television show.
   The Fox Television show, which features a different fugitive
each week, focused its May 22 episode on Carmine Esposito, 40, the
son of an alleged member of the Genovese crime family. Esposito is
sought in the 1983 murder of Timothy Dorsey, 25, who was gunned
down in a New York City restaurant.
   After the show aired, police in Mount Pocono, Pa., received a
tip that Esposito was in the area.
   Last Tuesday, police arrested Bennett, originally of New York
City. After an FBI check proved he was not a fugitive, he was
released.
   ``If we didn't follow up on the lead, we would have been
criticized,'' said Mount Pocono Police Chief David Swiderski.
