<HEAD>More Than 200 Alleged Gang Members Arrested In Sweep</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested more than 200 suspected gang
members in a 1,000-officer sweep that ended this morning in an
ongoing effort to rid the nation's second-largest city of
gang-related crime.
   ``We want to reassure the public that we're still committed to
solving the gang problem,'' said Deputy Police Chief William
Rathburn. ``We don't want the public to think we've gone away, so
we'll run these (sweeps) periodically to reassure them,'' he said.
   ``We're throwing out the big net,'' Rathburn added.
   Lt. Jim Tatreau said final tallies on the number arrested were
not available early today ``but it will be over 200 when we add
them all up.''
   ``There were definitely a lot of rock cocaine arrests, some
arrests for possesion of narcotics for sale, and there were
numerous weapons confiscated, including an AK47 assault rifle,''
Tatreau said.
   He said those arrested for serious crimes were held at city
jails while those picked up on lesser charges, such as driving
under the influence of alcohol, were released.
   The sweep, the second such police operation in two months, began
at 1 p.m. Friday when 1,000 officers fanned out across the city
looking for alleged gang members.
   ``We're going to do it again and again,'' said Police Chief
Daryl Gates at a briefing before the officers hit the streets.
   Half of the officers were deployed in the city's gang-ridden
South Central area neighborhoods.
   The last time 1,000 officers were out in force against gangs was
on April 8 and April 9 when Mayor Tom Bradley ordered them to
``take back the streets.''
   That sweep netted 1,453 arrests during its two days.
   Tatreau declined to say if the most recent gang sweep would
continue again tonight. But Rathburn had said earlier it could last
for several days.
</TEXT>
