<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Train Blast,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll Nears 100 in Train Blast; Sloppy Loading Blamed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death toll in a Soviet train explosion neared
100 as workers picked through rubble in the city of Arzamas, a
newspaper said today, blaming the blast on the improper transport
of industrial explosives.
   The force of the explosion made it difficult to determine
exactly how many died, the Communist Party newspaper Pravda
reported, saying the toll ``was approaching 100.'' It added that
200 people were hospitalized and 700 familes left homeless in the
industrial city 240 miles east of Moscow.
   Shortly after the explosion, a week ago today, the state-run
media put the death toll at 73. It rose to 80 on Wednesday. More
are missing and unaccounted for, Pravda said.
   The explosion caused millions of dollars in damages, Pravda
said, without giving a specific figure.
   Investigators have not yet determined what sparked the blast,
but it apparently stemmed from improper loading and handling of
explosives.
   It was clear ``the crew did not know what they were carrying,''
wrote Pravda correspondent V. Lisin.
   ``The cargo list on the train listed one type of explosive, but
in the wagons themselves ... was another more dangerous substance.
Worse than that, two types of explosives were placed together in
the first wagon, which is categorically forbidden,'' it said.
   Examination of wagons which did not blow up, Pravda said,
revealed ``severe violations of the rules for the transportation of
dangerous cargos.''
   Detailed reports of disasters were unheard of before Kremlin
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev came to power in March 1985 and began
the policy of ``glasnost,'' or greater discussion of some formerly
taboo subjects
</TEXT>
