<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PlaneEngine     06-11 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plane Engine,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Airlines DC-10 Lands After One Engine Shut Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Airlines jumbo jet from Dallas
carrying 185 people came in on only two of its three engines when
an oil warning light prompted the pilot to shut down the third, the
airline said.
   None of the 172 passengers or 13 crew members was injured, and
the DC-10 landed one minute early Friday evening at Los Angeles
International Airport, said airline spokesman John Raymond.
   ``On final approach the pilot encountered a low oil-pressure
light. He shut down the engine that the light involved,'' Raymond
said. ``It was a perfectly normal landing.''
   ``The oil pressure light will be checked out,'' Raymond said.
``Frequently a faulty light causes this. Either it's a bad light or
there may be a problem with the engine and that will be fixed,
too.''
   The Federal Aviation Administration will investigate the
incident, said an FAA regional duty officer who refused to give his
name.
   The jet was docked since Flight 79 from Dallas-Fort Worth was
the final American Airlines flight to Los Angeles for the day.
Raymond said it will be inspected by airline mechanics in Los
Angeles.
   A DC-10 can hold a maximum 290 passengers, not including the
crew, Raymond said.
</TEXT>
