<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Korea 1stLd-Writethru a0416 06-11 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0416,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radicals Stage Firebomb Attack On Government Building</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with more details on attack on
government buildings, clashes in two other cities. Pickup 10th
graf, ``Our struggle...''
^By C.W. LIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students hurling firebombs
attacked the Foreign Ministry and the prime minister's office
today, and student leaders vowed to stage another march to North
Korea for unification talks.
   Police said 26 students forced their way past guards at a back
gate of the Combined Central Government Building in downtown Seoul
and hurled at least 10 firebombs at the complex. Eight of the
attackers barricaded themselves in a third-floor cafeteria before
they were seized by police.
   Nobody was injured in the attack in which windows were smashed
and a police guard post and a waiting room blackened by flames and
smoke. Police said they arrested 18 attackers and that the others
fled.
   The building, across the street from the U.S. Embassy, houses
the prime minister's office, the Foreign Ministry and other major
government departments.
   Small clashes also were reported today in the provincial cities
of Taeju and Kwangju as riot police firing volleys of tear gas
dispersed students hurling rocks and firebombs. No injuries or
arrests were immediately reported.
   The attacks were mounted after riot police blocked thousands of
radical students on Friday from mounting a march to the North
Korean border for talks on reuniting the divided Korean peninsula.
Fighting began on Friday when police fired tear gas to drive back
students who hurled firebombs and battled with rocks and clubs to
try and break through to the border.
   Police officials said today that more than 800 students were
arrested in the clashes the day before. More than 100 police and
students were injured in the street clashes, they said.
   About 60,000 riot police were deployed to halt the march to the
border truce site of Panmunjom. Riot police remained on alert today
and troopers guarded key government buildings and U.S. diplomatic
offices.
   Radical leaders at a rally today at Yonsei University in the
west of Seoul vowed to mount another march to the border on Aug.
15, national independence day, and said they would not abandon the
reunification drive.
   ``Our struggle has ignited the mind of the people who want
reunficition of our land,'' one leader said in a speech.
   About 2,000 students applauded the speakers and shouted slogans.
But the students' mood was subdued and thousands of others who had
gathered at the campus for the march Friday left overnight.
   Speakers continued to denounce the United States and demand the
withdrawal of the 42,000 U.S. troops based in South Korea under a
mutual defense pact.
   ``Yankee go home'' and ``Reunification,'' students chanted.
   Radicals claim the United States enforces partition of the
Korean peninsula so it can rule the south as a virtual colony. A
wave of violent anti-American protests has hit South Korea during
the past month.
   The radicals, who represent between 10 percent and 20 percent of
college students, have failed to attract popular support with their
reunification campaign. The main opposition parties urged radicals
to abandon the march, saying it lacked public support.
   Most people in South Korea fear the totalitarian north is
determined to conquer the south. North Korea invaded the south in
1950 to start the Korean War and the two nations remain bitter
opponents.
   The North Korean government said its student delegates waited
Friday at Panmunjom for the South Korean students. It denounced the
United States and the South Korean government, claiming they want
to block reunification.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
