<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SouthAfrica     06-11 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pro-Government Paper Joins Outcry Over New Press Curbs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A loyal pro-government
newspaper today joined the outcry against new press restrictions,
and a prominent black moderate pleaded for the release of jailed
guerrilla leader Nelson Mandela.
   The new restrictions took effect Friday when the government
reimposed the nationwide state of emergency for a third year. They
tighten curbs on reporting about opposition activity and require
some journalists to register with the government.
   The Citizen, a pro-government Johannesburg daily, joined a wide
range of journalists, anti-apartheid leaders and others in
criticizing the restrictions.
   ``There is only one word for the new press curbs and that is
overkill,'' The Citizen's editorial said.
   It said the government appeared to have reached the point where
it was barring newspapers from reporting ``matters of vital concern
to everyone.'' It added: ``That will mean the public will be
uninformed and subject to rumor.'
   The Foreign Correspondents Association said in a statement: ``We
observe with irony that South Africa is progressively shutting down
the free flow of information at a time when the Soviet Union _
frequently depicted here as an enemy of press freedom _ is
noticeably moving towards a more open society.''
   Mangosuthu Buthelezi, leader of the KwaZulu homeland and one of
the blacks the government would like to draw into a
white-controlled power-sharing arrangement, said the extension of
the emergency was a tragedy.
   At an outdoor meeting near Durban, Buthelezi also appealed for
the release of Mandela, who is serving a life prison sentence for
his actions as leader of the outlawed African National Congress
guerrilla movement.
   ``Black South Africa will not rest until he is free,'' Buthelezi
said. ``Nothing the South African government can do will gain it
credibility while it treats Dr. Mandela as a dangerous enemy.''
   Buthelezi said Mandela might be the only person capable of
ending a bloody power stuggle in Natal province between militants
who support the ANC and more conservative blacks who follow
Buthelezi.
   ``I believe he (Mandela) would come out of jail to thump anybody
... who set black brother against black brother on the eve of a
final black victory over apartheid,'' Buthelezi said.
   As he spoke, about 70,000 fans packed London's Wembley Stadium
for a 10-hour rock concert honoring Mandela.
   Although the British Broadcasting Corp. pledged to cover the
extravaganza as a musical, not a political event, its commentator
referred to Mandela as ``a political prisoner.'' The South African
government threatened this week to expel the BBC for its allegedly
biased coverage of the government.
   One of the new restrictions imposed in South Africa on Friday
outlaws advocacy of a boycott of nationwide municipal elections
scheduled for October.
   Most major anti-apartheid groups, including 17 which were banned
in February, oppose black participation in elections organized by
the white authorities until blacks have voting rights on a national
level.
   The new regulations make it illegal to quote anti-government
statements from members of the 17 organizations and prohibit
newspapers from quoting any ANC members.
   Another new rule requires local news agencies, except for the
South African Press Association, to register with the government.
These small domestic news agencies, many of them aggressive in
covering anti-apartheid activity, could be ordered to submit their
dispatches to a government censor.
   A group of these alternative news agencies _ the East Cape News
Agencies _said the new regulation could be ``the first step on the
road to compulsory registration of all journalists ... with the
threat of deregistration if they misbehave.''
   The government ``seeks a nation of ignorant, pliant subjects,''
it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
