<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PhillyPrisons     06-11 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philly Prisons,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prison Population Falls Below Court-Ordered Cap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's jail population dropped below the
court-ordered limit, allowing the city to hold prisoners unable to
raise bail, officials said.
   The jail population this morning was 3,813, under the 3,850
maximum permitted by the court on weekends and holidays, Bail
Commissioner Charles Murray said. For other days, the maximum
prison population is set at 3,750.
   Since Wednesday many people, including alleged drug dealers, had
avoided jail when unable to raise bail because of the order by U.S.
District Judge Norma Shapiro that limited the city's prison
population.
   At the time the jails held nearly 4,000 men and women.
   The city began freeing prisoners on their own recognizance if
they were awaiting trial and had been unable to raise bail of
$2,500 or less.
   On Friday afternoon, Prison Superintendent Edmund Lyons said the
jails held 3,690 people and that, starting this morning, those
unable to raise bail would be held.
   ``The prison is open and people can be admitted on a regular
basis,'' Murray said early today. ``The moratorium right now is
lifted.''
   District Attorney Ronald Castille has termed the jail moratorium
``lunacy,'' charging that city prisons can hold as many as 4,300
inmates.
   Castille called on Mayor W. Wilson Goode to seek to have the cap
raised or find alternate confinement space.
   Prisoners who brought the lawsuit charged that Philadelphia's
prisons were overcrowded. They had demanded that each of the city's
3,200 cells should have only one person.
   Excluded from the moratorium are those charged with murder,
attempted murder, rape, attempted rape, kidnapping, arson, robbery
and aggravated assault in addition to crimes involving use of a gun
or knife or large amounts of drugs.
   Meanwhile, the city moved closer to increasing its cell space by
awarding a construction contract for a new $165 million Criminal
Justice Center. The center _ with jail space for 440 people, plus
courtrooms _ is expected to be completed in 1991.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
