<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Czechoslovakia-Church     06-11 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Czechoslovakia-Church,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Protest After Two Bishops Consecrated In Prague</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IVA DRAPALOVA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 5,000 people jammed St.
Vitus Cathedral today for the consecration of two assistant
bishops, the first such Roman Catholic appointments allowed by the
communist government since 1973.
   After the ceremony, hundreds of people shouted slogans such as
``Long Live Father Cardinal!'' ``Long Live the Pope!'' and ``We
Want Religious Freedom!'' outside the palace of Cardinal Frantisek
Tomasek.
   Tomasek, the head of Czechoslovakia's Catholic church,
officiated at a two-hour ceremony to mark the formal appointment of
Jan Lebeda, the 75-year-old Vicar General of Prague, and
64-year-old priest Antonin Liska as assistant bishops of Prague.
   Their appointment should lighten the workload of the 88-year-old
Cardinal.
   Papal emissary Francesco Colasuonno and Catholic officials from
neighboring Poland, West and East Germany, Austria and Hungary were
among those attending the majestic ritual in the cathedral.
   Colasuonno later shook hands with those who rallied outside
Tomasek's palace.
   Demonstrations involving hundreds of Catholics for religious
freedom have taken place almost every Sunday after Mass around the
cathedral and Tomasek's palace.
   A recent warming in relations between churches and the atheist
Communist authorities in the Soviet Union has not led to similar
church-state improvements in Czechoslovakia.
   After long negotiations with the government, the Vatican failed
to fill any of the 10 vacant sees in Czechoslovakia, where the
authorities have not approved any new bishops since 1973. Lebeda
and Liska are the first new assistant bishops since 1973.
   Tomasek has come under attack from state-run media in recent
months for supporting a petition for more religious freedom that
has garnered an estimated 600,000 signatures.
   In April, the cardinal wrote to Premier Lubomir Strougal urging
that the church and the authorities open a new dialogue. The offer
was rejected.
</TEXT>
