<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Apartheid-Rock 3ndLd-Writethru a0460 06-11 0760</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Apartheid-Rock, 3nd Ld-Writethru, a0460,0778</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Belafonte Calls For Mandela's Release At London Rock Concert</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2 grafs for grafs 2-3 pvs, ``Belafonte
introduced...youthful throng.'' to RECAST Belafonte quotes. Pickup
4th graf pvs, ``The British...''
^By BEN DOBBIN</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Harry Belafonte, a veteran
anti-apartheid campaigner, today kicked off a 10-hour rock concert
honoring Nelson Mandela by calling on South Africa to release the
black leader from prison.
   Belafonte, speaking to 70,000 fans at London's Wembley Stadium,
gave a brief but stirring message to Mandela on his upcoming 70th
birthday.
   Belafonte called Mandela a symbol of South Africa's ``cruel and
unjust system of apartheid,'' and said: ``We want to see you and
your fellow political prisoners freed.'' Cheers and a chorus of
``Happy Birthday'' rose from the mostly youthful throng.
   The British rock star Sting then began the peformance, which
organizers said would be seen on television by 750 million people
in 60 countries.
   Although the British Broadcasting Corp. pledged to cover the
extravaganza as a musical, not a political event, its commentator
referred to Mandela as ``a political prisoner.'' The South African
government threatened this week to expel the BBC for its allegedly
biased coverage of the government.
   Organizers said the concert, modeled on the 1985 Live Aid
``global jukebox'' for African famine relief, launches a five-week
series of rallies and celebrations in Britain leading up to
Mandela's 70th birthday on July 18.
   Mandela, leader of the outlawed African National Congress, was
among eight ANC leaders sentenced to life imprisonment 24 years ago
today for sabotage and conspiracy to topple the government. He has
since become South Africa's most prominent political prisoner.
   About 40 pop stars and groups _ including Whitney Houston and
Phil Collins _ were to perform on a huge stage at the north London
stadium.
   The Anti-Apartheid Movement organizers say half the proceeds
from the $45 tickets will go to seven children's charities in
southern Africa and the rest will fund its activities in Britain.
   Six hours of the concert was to be telecast in the United States
today by Fox Broadcasting, the Los Angeles-based network.
   The concert has been denounced by the South African government
and by right-wingers in Britain who claim that by televising it,
the BBC is violating its duty to be impartial.
   A BBC statement said the BBC is not paying for broadcast rights
and views the concert purely as ``an outstanding international
musical event.''
   Published reports said that when a message from Mandela smuggled
out of Pollsmoor Prison in Cape Town is read to the crowd, cameras
would cut from the stage to interviews.
   In London, 25 lawmakers in the governing Conservative Party
signed a House of Commons motion saying the BBC was violating its
rules by giving ``publicity to a movement that encourages the
African National Congress in its terrorist activities.''
   ``You can only say it is a political event because he (Mandela)
is a political prisoner,'' countered Archbishop Trevor Huddleston,
the main organizer of the show.
   South Africa said its London embassy complained to the BBC ``at
the highest level'' about broadcasting the concert and hinted it
might expel BBC reporters.
   That complaint follows one on Thursday by South African Law and
Order Minister Adriaan Vlok who said the BBC might be ordered out
of South Africa because of a film it broadcast in Britain this week
about detained black children in South Africa.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
   ANC President Oliver Tambo is billed as the concert's guest of
honor. The ANC is the main guerrilla group fighting South Africa's
government.
   Scheduled performers include George Michael, Miriam Makeba, Hugh
Masekela, Dire Straits, Eurythmics, Simple Minds, Roberta Flack,
Natalie Cole, the Bee Gees, Joe Cocker, Fat Boys, Ashford and
Simpson, Joan Armatrading, Bryan Adams, Paul Young, Jackson Browne,
Al Green and Jerry Dammers.
   There were to be several big-name surprise singers, raising a
rash of speculation in London's tabloid newspapers. The Sun chose
guitarist-singer Eric Clapton as the secret special guest, while
The Star tipped Michael Jackson to veer from his European tour.
   Among the hosts were singer Meatloaf, comedienne Whoopi
Goldberg, actresses Jennifer Beals, Darryl Hannah and Ali McGraw,
and film maker Sir Richard Attenborough.
   U.S. opera singer Jessye Norman closes the event with ``Nkosi
Sikelele Africa'' (God Bless Africa), the national anthem of the
ANC and several African states.
</TEXT>
