<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Presbyterians 1stLd-Writethru a0420 06-11 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presbyterians, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0420,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presbyterians Struggle With Nuclear Weapons, Abortion Issues</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `A subcommittee ...,' with work resuming today
on nuclear arms statement.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a victory for anti-abortion groups,
Presbyterian leaders have urged a change in the denomination's
pro-choice position, while others struggled with a major church
statement on nuclear weapons.
   A subcommittee today continued revising ``Christian Obedience in
a Nuclear Age,'' a paper that has been criticized by groups within
the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) who say it improperly glorifies
civil disobedience and resistance to government policies.
   Abortion and nuclear weapons were among the controversial issues
being debated during the nine-day meeting of the 3-million-member
church's 200th General Assembly, which ends Wednesday.
   On Friday, full committees of the assembly adopted a
wide-ranging statement on religious freedom, including
recommendations that pastors give up their tax exemptions for their
housing allowances, and adopted a paper titled ``Is Christ
Divided?'' which complains that special interest groups have split
the denomination and calls for more serious theological discussion
of issues.
   A committee Friday called for a change in the church's position
on abortion and a new study of the issue, but supporters of the
denomination's generally pro-choice position say they expect a
floor fight on the question. The assembly is scheduled to consider
the matter on Tuesday.
   Presbyterians Pro-Life, a sanctioned organization within the
denomination, wants the church to condemn abortion in all instances
except where the mother's life is in danger.
   PPL co-sponsored an appearance by Nobel Peace laureate Mother
Teresa in a rally before the convention began Tuesday. PPL hoped
Mother Teresa's reputation and staunch anti-abortion stance would
persuade commissioners to approve a new study, or a change in
church policy.
   Currently, the Presbyterian group opposes abortion as a method
of birth control, but says the decision rests with a woman in
consultation with her doctor and her conscience.
   Also Friday, the 18-member Christian Obedience subcommittee
retained language in the Christian Obedience paper that calls
nuclear war immoral, but changed a section labeling the theory of
nuclear deterrence immoral.
   T. LaFontine ``Fountain'' Odom, an elder from Charlotte, N.C.,
said the subcommittee revised the paper to say ``nuclear deterrence
as an end in itself'' is immoral.
   In addition, the subcommittee deleted recommendations calling on
local church groups to provide financial and moral support to those
who resist the government through tax protest and civil
disobedience.
   But the subcommittee left in recommendations calling for
creation of a voluntary Fund for Obedience to a High Authority
``for the assistance of those who suffer financial loss or
difficulty as a result of acts of conscience.''
   Many conservatives have blamed the Christian Obedience paper and
past social policy statements for the denomination's membership
decline.
   There were 2,976,937 church members in 1987, a decline of
154,191 since 1983, when the denomination was formed from two
Presbyterian groups that had split during the Civil War. The
denomination is almost 14 times larger than the second-largest
group, the Presbyterian Church in America.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
