<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RoadDrugs     06-11 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Road Drugs,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mandatory Drug-Testing Proposed for Interstate Truck Drivers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Teamsters union official says
mandatory drug testing of interstate truck and bus drivers is
unreasonable and resembles a politically motivated ``witch hunt''
by federal highway safety officials.
   The International Brotherhood of Teamsters ``will fight this all
the way,'' said R.V. Durham, the union's safety and health
director. The Teamsters represent 200,000 truckers nationwide.
   Durham responded Friday to a highway safety proposal by
Secretary of Transportation Jim Burnley for drug testing of up to 5
million drivers of interstate trucks, passenger buses and vehicles
hauling hazardous materials.
   ``We must act to identify those commercial drivers who abuse
drugs and get them off the roads,'' Burnley told a news conference
here. ``When one drugged truck or bus driver goes out on the road,
he not only puts the lives of many people in danger, he gives the
entire work force a bad reputation.''
   But Durham said Teamster drivers are the safest and most
responsible in the trucking industry and called the DOT proposal a
``witch hunt'' and ``a politically motivated move to beat up on
truck drivers.''
   Durham said that Teamster truckers were already subject to drug
testing as part of their biannual transportation department
physical exams, and also if there was probable suspicion of
substance abuse.
   ``Random testing is an unreasonable and unjustifiable violation
of a person's right to privacy. We believe government-mandated
random testing is unconstitutional,'' Durham said.
   Burnley's proposal was the latest in a series of department
efforts to make America's transportation network safer.
   In March, the drug testing program was proposed for the aviation
industry. In May, the railroad industry was targeted.
   There are no firm statistics to indicate how many of the
nation's truck drivers are drug abusers, he said. But he cited a
June 1987 test of 317 tractor-trailer drivers in Tennessee that
showed 15 percent of the drivers tested positive for marijuana,
cocaine and prescription stimulants.
   The proposed rule would cover 3 million to 5 million people who
drive commercial motor vehicles weighing more than 10,000 pounds,
vehicles that transport 16 or more people or vehicles that
transport hazardous materials.
   School bus drivers and intercity bus drivers would not be
affected by the proposal, he said.
   In Washington, the American Trucking Association endorsed the
effort but expressed concerns about how the tests would be
implemented.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
