<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PeaceConvoy     06-11 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peace Convoy,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peace Group Holds Vigil At International Bridge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAREDO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group trying to take a convoy of
truckloads of aid to Nicaragua has again been stalled at the border
in a dispute with the Trreasury Department over trade restrictions
on the Central American nation.
   ``They have gone back on what they said,'' said David Silk, a
spokesman for Veterans' Peace Convoy. ``We are back to square one.''
   The group already is three days behind schedule.
   U.S. Customs officials met late Friday with representatives of
the group.
   ``Last night they told us we would be forced to sign a statement
of intent stating essentially that we the convoy are wrong, we are
guilty of breaking the embargo law,'' Sean Guillete, a convoy
participant, said early today. ``Our lawyers are not at all happy
with this proposal.''
   Donna de la Torre, a U.S. Customs worker in Houton, told KTSA
radio in San Antonio the meeting was held to pass out papers to be
signed and go over guidelines.
   About 100 convoy members have been camped here since Wednesday
when Treasury Department officials informed them that the trip
would violate trade restrictions imposed on Nicaragua in 1985.
Violation of the regulations can result in fines of up to $50,000
and prison terms up to 10 years.
   Some 30 tons of food, clothing and medical supplies would be
allowed for humanitarian purposes, the government told the convoy
members, but their 37 vehicles could not be left in Nicaragua.
   Treasury's Office of Foreign Assets Control said the group would
have to apply for an export license, post cash bonds equal to the
value of the trucks, cars and buses, and give assurance the
vehicles would be returned to this country within 30 days.
   On Friday, Customs officials told the group they would not seize
their trucks if bonds were not posted.
   However, a Treasury spokesman in Washington said Friday
afternoon that Foreign Assets Control had not changed its position.
   Organizer Gerry Condon said the group planned to leave vehicles
in Nicaragua, but never intended to be out of compliance with the
law.
   The convoy began May 21 from different regions of the United
States and arrived in Laredo on Tuesday.
   ``We have baby food going bad in the 115-degree temperature down
here,'' Silk said. ``We are angry, tired of being toyed with.''
   Gullette said the group ``will do everything to avoid violence,
but at the same time the convoy believes in civil disobedience when
appropriate.''
   Convoy members say they are being harassed because of their
opposition to U.S. aid for the rebels fighting the leftist
Sandinista government. Treasury officials say they are simply
following standard procedures.
</TEXT>
