<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-MineDisaster     06-11 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Mine Disaster,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rescuers Find Body Of Last Missing Miner In Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BORKEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Search teams found the body of the
last man missing after an explosion in a coal mine, bringing the
total number of confirmed dead to 51, officials said today.
   The teams found the body late Friday, according to Peter-Carl
Ruehland, a spokesman for the Preussen Elektra company, which owns
the mine.
   On June 1, a powerful methane gas explosion ripped through the
Stolzenbach mine in Borken, located about 70 miles northeast of
Frankfurt.
   A total of 57 men were trapped in the mine after the blast,
which was West Germany's worst mine accident in over two 26 years.
Six miners were rescued June 4 after spending 65 hours trapped 500
feet underground.
   A local prosecutor has opened an investigation into the
explosion, reportedly to see whether a cigarette lighter flame may
have touched off the blast. Mine officials have said smoking was
strictly forbidden underground.
</TEXT>
