<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Children'sHome 1stLd-Writethru a0417 06-11 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Children's Home, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0417,0768</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dozens of Children Flee Baptist Boarding Home After State Awarded
Custody</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY6</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with state officials working
over weekend trying to reach parents and answering their questions.
Picks up in 7th graf, `Many of ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Highway patrol and sheriff's officers
today searched for dozens of children who fled a Baptist boarding
home after a judge granted the state temporary custody following
allegations of mental and physical abuse.
   About 80 of approximately 140 children living at the Bethel Home
for Children in Lucedale remained at large, police said late Friday.
   State officials said they would work over the weekend trying to
reach the children's parents and guardians.
   Youth Court Judge Robert Oswald of Pascagoula issued the order
at 11 a.m. Friday, saying there was probable cause to suspect
physical and mental abuse at the home. Minutes after he issued the
order, Welfare Department personnel arrived at the home. But in the
meantime, the youths apparently were alerted and most had fled.
   ``We were told they were allowed, if not encouraged, to leave
the campus, and some of the children said they were told to run,''
said state Welfare Commissioner Thomas Brittain.
   Some of the children, ages 8 through 17, were found in private
homes, restaurants and walking along the streets of Lucedale,
Brittain said.
   About 60 children were taken to dormitories on the campus of the
Mississippi State Hospital at Whitfield, he said. They were
undergoing physical examinations.
   After the decision was made to house the children at the
hospital, parents began calling the hospital, state hospital
spokeswoman Wynona Winfield said. Welfare Department social
workers, she said, told parents how to get to the hospital, how the
children were and answered other questions.
   Many of the youths were angry as they were taken into custody.
   ``You have no right, I want to be here with my people,'' said
Eric Parker, 16. ``I don't want to be here with all the rest of you
people who hate the truth. You better check yourself and make sure
you are not burning on the way to hell.''
   Officials were unsure how many children lived at the home
because its operator, the Rev. Herman Fountain, refused to provide
a list of residents, Brittain said.
   Fountain, along with several other ministers from the
fundamentalist church who flocked from Louisiana, Georgia and Texas
to support him, claim such boarding homes are protected from state
regulation because of the constitutional separation of church and
state.
   Oswald issued the order following a weeklong hearing on a
request by George County authorities. The hearing stemmed from an
investigation into a child who ran away from the home and refused
to return, claiming he was physically abused.
   In court papers, the youth, identified only by his initials,
said he was ``tired of being locked up, slapped and getting licks
all the time.'' He told social workers he was denied medical and
dental treatment during his 19-month stay at the Bethel home.
   Authorities have not charged anyone at the home with abuse but
are still investigating the allegations, Brittain said. Telephone
calls to the Bethel home were not answered late Friday.
   The judge ruled that according to Mississippi's Youth Act, the
children were being held in a detention home rather than a boarding
home. Detention facilities are required to notify the state of
children placed in their custody.
   Fountain was jailed for two days for refusing provide a list of
residents. But he was freed Friday without turning over the roster
after agreeing to an orderly transfer of the children to state
custody.
   When Welfare Department officials arrived, Fountain was already
at the home, Brittain said.
   ``We did not encounter any cooperation from him there. In fact,
it was just the opposite,'' Brittain said, declining to elaborate.
   Brittain said he was unsure whether any action would be taken
against Fountain.
   The court order gives the state 48-hour temporary custody of the
children, in addition to custody today and Sunday. Welfare
officials hope to locate and return the children to their parents,
Brittain said.
   ``We have information that some folks are trying to help the
kids escape out of state,'' he said.
   Based on his experience with the Bethesda Home for Girls near
Hattiesburg, where about 100 children were taken into state custody
in 1986, Brittain said he believed the children's parents would be
scattered throughout the country.
</TEXT>
