<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Spain-Tarradellas     06-11 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-Tarradellas,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands File Past Coffin of Catalonian Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people filed past the
coffin of Josep Tarradellas today in a final salute to one of the
few remaining figures of the ill-fated 1931-1939 Spanish Second
Republic.
   Tarradellas, who became the first head of the restored
Catalonian regional government in the post-Franco era, died Friday
in this northeastern Mediterranean city from complications of a
chronic lung ailment. He was 89.
   Spanish National Radio said by midmorning police estimated 3,000
people had filed past Tarradellas' glass-covered coffin draped with
the red-and-gold-barred flag of the autonomous region of Catalonia.
Tarradellas lay in state in the Palace of the Generalitat, the seat
of the regional government.
   The regional government declared three days of mourning for
Tarradellas, one of the founders of the Republican Left Party of
Catalonia in 1931.
   A government spokesman said a funeral Mass would be held Sunday
in Barcelona with burial later that day in nearby Santa Coloma de
Cervello, his hometown.
   Tarradellas served as a minister of the regional government of
Catalonia during the 1936-39 Spanish Civil War. He went into exile
when the rebel forces of Gen. Francisco Franco defeated troops
loyal to the Second Republic.
   When Tarradellas left Spain he vowed never to set foot in his
native region again until Catalonian autonomy was restored.
   As the Spanish transition to democracy began upon Franco's death
in 1975, he sought to restore the autonomous government of the
four-province northeastern region of Catalonia.
   King Juan Carlos appointed Tarradellas provisional head of the
Catalonian government and he returned to Barcelona Oct. 23, 1977,
where huge crowds were on hand to welcome him home.
   Tarradellas retired two years later and lived with his wife,
Antonia, who survives him.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
