<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Panda     06-11 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Panda,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexico's Papa Panda Suffering from Tumors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Biopsies have been taken of tumors found in
Pe-Pe, the father of Mexico City's giant panda family, the director
of the Mexico City zoo said.
   Maria Helena Hoyo, director of the Chapultepec Zoological
Garden, said in a telephone interview Friday that the biopsies were
taken Thursday to determine if the tumors are malignant.
   The results will not be known for at least three weeks, she said.
   She said doctors removed tissue from Pe-Pe's left armpit and
also from the groin area where inflammations of two glands were
detected. Experts from the National Zoo in Washington, D.C., helped
in the operation.
   Miss Hoyo said the 13-year-old panda ``is in good shape'' and
was eating.
   The tumors were found early this year.
   In March, Pe-Pe was reported as being lethargic, and his weight
had dropped to 249 pounds down his usual 275 to 285 pounds.
   China gave Pe-Pe and his mate, Ying-Ying, to Mexico in September
1975. They have produced four cubs through natural conception, the
largest such panda family outside China.
</TEXT>
