<1ST_LINE>r i AM-OfficialHitchhiker     06-11 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Official Hitchhiker,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Probe Promised Into Jailing of Man Who Denied Official a Lift</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kenya's attorney general promised to
investigate why a motorist who refused to give a ride to a stranded
government official was jailed for three months, press reports said
Saturday.
   Justice Mathew Muli told officials of the Law Society of Kenya
during a meeting Friday he would study the background of the case,
Nairobi newspapers reported.
   The Law Society urged the attorney general to establish on what
judicial grounds Peter Makau, 36, a factory technician from
Nairobi, was jailed. A magistrate in the western town of Eldoret
sentenced Makau to three months in jail on Thursday for ``very
unsocial behavior.''
   Makau pleaded guilty to a charge of ``uttering words of defiance
and disobedience to a lawful authority.'' The authority was Yusuf
Haji, the highest-ranking government official of the Rift Valley
province.
   Makau was driving through Eldoret on Wednesday when Haji,
ceremonially clad in his official pith helmet and khaki uniform,
flagged him down. The commissioner's car had broken down, and he
was late for an official function.
   Makau refused to pick him up and said: ``Go and find a GK
(government of Kenya) vehicle. My car is not a government vehicle.''
   The commissioner reported Makau to police, and he was brought to
court.
   Magistrate Njuguna Kimani jailed the technician without giving
him the option of a fine and told him, ``Government officials
deserve respect. The accused lacked respect.''
</TEXT>
