<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfRdp 4thLd-Writethru a0501 06-11 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0501,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranians Attack U.S.-Chartered Freighter and British-Flagged
Tanker</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with attack on British-flagged tanker.
No pickup.
^By NABILA MEGALLI</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian gunboats today attacked and set
ablaze a British-flagged tanker off Saudi Arabia and fired
rocket-propelled grenades at an American-chartered freighter in the
Strait of Hormuz, sources said.
   The raid on the freighter left one crewman dead and two injured.
   The British-flagged tanker, the 258,979-ton Esso Demetia, was
set ablaze at 6:05 p.m. southeast of the Saudi oil port of Ras
Tanura, according to gulf-based shipping executives, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   It was not known if the attack by two Iranian gunboats or the
resulting fire caused casualties aboard the Esso Demetia.
   Four hours earlier, two Iranian gunboats attacked the 11,744-ton
West German vessel Dhaulagiri 300 miles to the south as it sailed
into Hormuz, the waterway connecting the Persian Gulf and the Gulf
of Oman.
   The freighter was manned by a crew of five Germans and 14
Filipinos, the sources said. The seaman who was killed took a
direct hit, but it was not known whether it was from a grenade or
machine-gun fire, they said. Two crewmen were injured by shrapnel
from the rocket-propelled grenades, the executives said.
   A man with a Filipino accent was heard radioing from the
freighter for assistance. ``He was begging, almost crying for
helicopter assistance to remove the wounded,'' said one executive
who monitored the radio call.
   An Omani patrol boat later carried the injured to a hospital,
they said.
   The executives said the freighter was punctured with holes, but
no fire broke out. It was heading for the Saudi Arabian port of
Dammam, they said. The vessel was chartered by the American
President Lines Ltd. of San Francisco, to carry containers of cargo
to Arab ports in the gulf.
   The freighter's engine was not damaged, and it was expected to
go to the southern gulf port of Dubai for repairs, the sources said.
   The Iranian attacks were their first in two weeks and the fifth
and sixth since May 3, when the U.S. Navy broadened its protective
role to non-U.S. flagged vessels in the gulf.
   On Thursday, Iraqi warplanes shattered a two-week lull in the
``tanker war'' by attacking a salvage tugboat, the 742-ton
Singapore-flag Salverve. The raid killed two seamen, shipping
officials reported.
   On Friday, Baghdad Radio reported another Iraqi air raid hit a
``large maritime target'' off the Iranian coast. But there has been
no independent confirmation of that raid.
   Iran and Iraq, at war since 1980, have attacked more than 500
merchant ships in the gulf since early 1984. More than 300 seamen
have been killed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880611-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 1236EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     06-11 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0739</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAEN, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Film star Elizabeth Taylor, rumored to be
engaged to millionaire Malcolm Forbes, waved at reporters as she
arrived in a private jet to attend a ballooning festival at Forbes'
Normandy chateau.
   Taylor, dressed in black pants and a black-and-white checkered
blazer, flew to this northern French town aboard Forbes' plane on
Friday. The millionaire, who has denied the marriage rumors, met
her at the airport.
   On Sunday, Miss Taylor will attend the celebrity-studded 13th
international ballooning festival at Forbes' Balleroy castle.
   Forbes, owner of Forbes Magazine, has led trips by balloon and
motorcycle across a number of countries, including China and Japan.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-five years after he stood
face-to-face with George Wallace at the University of Alabama,
Nicholas Katzenbach returned to the campus to discuss Wallace's
vain attempt to keep the school segregated.
   Katzenbach, then an assistant U.S. attorney general in the
Kennedy administration, was sent to Tuscaloosa to enroll two black
students against the objections of Wallace, who was governor at the
time. A federal court had ordered the students' admission.
   ``At no time did we really know what Gov. Wallace would do,''
Katzenbach said Friday. ``It made us nervous.''
   Katzenbach, now a lawyer in New Jersey, was among 400
journalists, academics and university alumni who took part in a
three-day conference held to commemorate Wallace's 1963 ``stand in
the schoolhouse door.''
   Wallace, then serving the first of his four terms, had vowed
``segregation forever'' in his inaugural address, and had promised
he would physically prevent any attempt to register blacks at the
state university.
   But Wallace, after a long statement in defiance of the ``central
government,'' relented, allowing Vivan Malone and James Hood to
enroll.
   Wallace, who is wheelchair-bound as the result of an
assassination attempt and has made few public appearances since
leaving office last year, declined an invitation to attend the
conference. An aide, Elvin Stanton, said Wallace would not make a
statement about the anniversary.
   Wallace, who later changed his views on segregation, has said
that he made his stand largely to reduce the chances of violence
hitting the Tuscaloosa campus as it had at the University of
Mississippi earlier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crown Prince Abdullah Bin Abdel-Aziz
is making a three-day official visit to England at the invitation
of British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, the official Saudi
press agency reported.
   The prince left Saturday, it said, adding that the visit
officially starts Monday.
   Mrs. Thatcher visited Riyadh briefly in 1985, and King Fahd of
Saudi Arabia paid a state visit to London last year.
   Britain has close economic and diplomatic ties with Saudi Arabia.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author A.E. Hotchner says the idea of
giving stock in actor Paul Newman's food business to people who
helped get it started was briefly discussed but people knew any
stock would be largely ``ceremonial.''
   Hotchner insisted that a delicatessen owner who says an attorney
for Newman promised him 8 percent of stock in the business was
never among those considered for the gift.
   Newman, Hotchner testified Friday, wanted all profits from his
Newman's Own Inc. to go to charity. The stock idea was eventually
abandoned in favor of Newman's holding all stock in the company.
   Westport delicatessen owner Julius Gold contends that he
contributed 30 months' effort to Newman's company and believed that
his ``judgment and perseverance ... led to the success of this
corporation.''
   Newman's Own, whose products include salad dressing, spaghetti
sauce, lemonade and popcorn, has donated $15 million to charity
since 1982 and helped create a camp for seriously ill children in
northeastern Connecticut. The camp opened last week.
   Hotchner, a close friend of Newman who helped the actor launch
Newman's Own in 1980, portrayed Gold as just one of many people
from whom he and Newman casually sought advice.
   The writer admitted, however, that Gold did introduce him to a
food distributor who eventually became the broker for the new salad
dressing. Gold is also suing the broker.
   Nwman, accompanied to court for the first time during the trial
by his wife, actress Joanne Woodward, also revealed that his will
specifies that all company profits will continue going to charity
after his death.
</TEXT>
