<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-VOA     06-11 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-VOA,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Students Criticizing American Radio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's official news agency said Saturday that
Beijing University students are accusing the U.S.-supported Voice
of America radio network of demagoguery in its reports on recent
student unrest.
   In Washington, the network denied the charge.
   The harshly worded report by the Xinhua News Agency said VOA,
which has a large audience in China, had become a target of student
criticism.
   Xinhua quoted one unidentified physics student as saying VOA had
blown the situation on the Beijing University campus out of
proportion.
   He said the radio reported falsely that a student was arrested
in a brief sit-in at Tiananmen Square last Wednesday. It said VOA
gave a false impression by saying police had charged students to
disperse them.
   Police on Wednesday closed off the square to thwart a planned
pro-democracy rally by students. About a dozen students tried to
stage a sit-in on a sidewalk off the square but police stopped
them. Police said one man was detained, but he was not a student.
   Richard Carlson, director of the U.S. broadcasting network, said
in a statement Saturday that ``the VOA rejects the charge of
demagoguery or anything resembling that.''
   Carlson said the network ``carefully sourced and verified the
events'' before reporting them. He said VOA will continue to
provide accurate information ``about events which affect them
daily, including calls for democracy and freedom.''
   The June 2 murder of a graduate student at the university
ignited campus protests first of lax security and later of poor
living conditions for intellectuals and the slow pace of democratic
reform in China.
   Dozens of posters, some criticizing the government, were put up
and 1,000 students have gathered on a campus square each night to
debate political issues and whether they should hold demonstrations.
   Xinhua quoted a student as saying VOA is overly interested in
bad news about China. ``Therefore, I suspect it has the desire to
see China plunged into chaos,'' the student said.
   A law student reportedly asked, ``Is the radio not trying to
make the situation worse?''
   China's official media have criticized VOA for its reports on
nationwide pro-democracy student demonstrations in December 1986
and January 1987. The network said its reports were balanced.
   VOA, which broadcasts in Chinese, English and 42 other
languages, is a major source of information for students trying to
find out what is happening on campuses throughout China.
</TEXT>
