<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sicily-Missiles     06-11 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sicily-Missiles,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Preparing To Remove Cruise Missiles From Italy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COMISO, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Russians are coming, and the men and
women of the U.S. Air Force 487th Tactical Missile Wing are
preparing to show them what few Americans have seen _ 112 cruise
missiles.
   The missiles and their camouflaged launchers, positioned at this
base in remote southeastern Sicily, are stored under tons of earth
and concrete and surrounded by four rows of chain-link fence topped
with barbed wire.
   Soviet inspectors will arrive sometime after July 1 to count the
missiles and launchers to be eliminated under terms of the
superpower Intermediate-Range Nuclear Force treaty, which went into
effect June 1.
   Lt. Col. Joseph Wagovich, a spokesman for the U.S. On-Site
Inspection Agency, told visiting reporters Friday that over the
next three years, the missiles and launchers will be sent to the
United States and destroyed under the eyes of Soviet inspectors.
   ``Exactly when they are going, or how they are going, I am not
at liberty to say,'' he said.
   Wagovich said the plan is to send the missiles to the Davis
Mathis Air Force Base in Arizona.
   U.S. inspectors will monitor the elimination of intermediate
range missiles in the Soviet Union, East Germany and Czechoslovakia.
   Wagovich said inspection agency officials are working quickly to
make sure everything is ready for the Soviets, who can make their
first visit between July 1 and the end of August.
   ``We have had a very short time to recruit and train inspectors
and escorts. It has been a very extensive effort. We have conducted
mock inspections, testing different scenarios,'' said Wagovich.
   Two Soviet reporters already have visited this high-security
base. They came Friday with other reporters from Italy, the United
States, Britain and France.
   Soviet and East-bloc journalists have also been shown missile
bases in Britain, West Germany and Belgium. Western reporters
visited a Soviet base in the northern republic of Ukraine on June 3.
   During the visit to Comiso, Capt. Don Sparks demonstrated how
the launchers are raised and prepared for action. But the Air Force
did not allow reporters to see a cruise missile.
   Each of the mobile launchers can fire four 21-foot missiles that
can deliver a 200-kiloton nuclear warhead 1,500 miles at almost the
speed of sound.
   The atomic bomb dropped on Hiroshima, Japan, in 1945 had an
explosive force of 20 kilotons.
   Air Force officials, citing security reasons, declined to
discuss the number of warheads at Comiso or their total destructive
force.
   The Italian government agreed in 1982 to take the missiles, and
Comiso became the second base in Europe to accept cruise missiles.
The first were located at Greenham Common, England.
   Air Force officials estimate that the base _ a mostly treeless
379-acre expanse of asphalt, sun-baked earth and brown and beige
stucco buildings _ pumps $18.2 million a year into the local
economy.
   U.S. and Italian officials said no decision has been made on how
to use the base once the missiles have left or on what to do with
the 1,750 American and 179 Italian military personnel.
   Americans first came to this base 45 years ago.
   On July 11, 1943, American troops commanded by Lt. Gen. Omar
Bradley captured the Axis airfield after Allied bombers hammered
the base.
   Six days later, Allied fighter planes began to use the air base.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
