<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan-Afghanistan     06-11 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Afghanistan,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pakistan Rejects Allegations of Geneva Accord Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistan on Saturday denied
allegations that it is violating a U.N.-sponsored accord on the
Afghan war by aiding Afghan guerrillas.
   It also claimed that Afghanistan had made forays into its
airspace and territory.
   ``The allegations made by the Kabul side were rejected, and a
point by point reply has been handed over to the United Nations,''
said a Foreign Ministry official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The Pakistani official said the reply ``emphasized ... that
Pakistan cannot be held responsible'' for guerrilla actions against
the Kabul government inside Afghanistan.
   ``Pakistan is also not expected to prohibit the legitimate
political activity of the Afghan refugees who represent a
substantial segment of the Afghan population,'' the spokesman said.
   The United Nations sponsored an accord calling for withdrawal
from Afghanistan of the Soviet troops helping the Afghan government
in its 10-year-old war with anti-communist guerrillas.
   Pakistan, Afghanistan, United States and the Soviet Union signed
the accord in Geneva on April 14.
   Afghanistan repeatedly has charged that Pakistan is violating
the agreement, which took effect May 15, by continuing to arm
guerrillas. Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze made the
same charge at the United Nations on Friday and said the United
States, which supports the guerrillas, is partly to blame.
   In addition to the United States, China and Pakistan have armed
the guerrillas during their struggle to oust the Afghan government.
   Shevardnadze said as a result of the alleged violations, the
Soviet Union may be obliged to review the nine-month schedule to
withdraw its more than 100,000 troops from Afghanistan.
   The Pakistani spokesman also said there had been air and ground
violations of Pakistan territory by the Afghan government and
called this ``a serious breach'' of the Geneva accord. It did not
elaborate on the alleged intrusions.
   The Pakistani statement was given to the U.N. mission for
Afghanistan and Pakistan in Islamabad. The mission undertakes
inspections when it receives complaints of violations of the accord.
   It has offices in Islamabad and Kabul.
   Nearly 3 million Afghan refugees fled to Pakistan following the
Soviet military intervention in Afghanistan in December 1979. The
bulk of the refugee population remains in Pakistan because of the
fighting.
</TEXT>
