<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 1342EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CigaretteSuit     06-11 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cigarette Suit,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tobacco Companies Wage Public Relations Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While six jurors decide a lung-cancer
victim's damage claims against three cigarette-makers, the defense
is gearing up its public relations engine.
   Each day the jury deliberated last week, a public relations firm
for two of the defendants reserved satellite time for a package of
background videotape, expert commentary, graphics on 30 years of
tobacco cases and live interviews with lawyers. The material is
intended for use on television stations.
   The federal lawsuit waged by Antonio Cipollone over the 1984
death of his wife, Rose, at 58 has drawn heavy media coverage, and
the tobacco companies have waged a major public relations offensive
throughout the 4{-month trial.
   The jury deliberated last week for four days, beginning Tuesday.
It took the weekend off and will return to the case Monday.
   Lorillard Inc., Liggett Group Inc. and Philip Morris Inc. are
accused of misleading the public about the dangers of cigarette
smoking through advertising, public relations and inadequate
research.
   Anti-smoking advocates have hailed the trial as a gold mine of
bad publicity for the $22 billion industry because of dozens of
confidential company documents presented as evidence.
   The documents spoke of a ``gentlemen's agreement'' not to
conduct cancer research, of an industry ``strategy'' to create
``doubt about the health charge without actually denying it,'' of a
research program designed ``so that (the) results can not harm''
the industry.
   The companies say the documents were taken out of context, that
Mrs. Cipollone freely chose to smoke knowing the risks and that
smoking is not a proven cancer cause.
   On hand almost every day for damage control during the trial
were five public relations experts, including three from the Daniel
J. Edelman Inc. firm, which represents Lorillard and Philip Morris
and arranged for the satellite feed. A lawyer also was present to
answer reporters' questions.
   After Liggett's attorney delivered closing arguments, a
spokesman at the courtroom door handed out a news release
containing the lawyer's statement.
   ``This is, by everyone's admission, the most critical case, the
one that attracted the most attention'' among tobacco liability
suits, said Edelman Senior Vice President John Scanlon.
   Philip Morris spokesman Tom Ricke said the satellite feed is
partly a solution to the large number of requests for interviews
from television stations.
   ``One of the problems we have is, win or lose, our side
historically hasn't gotten a lot of play, especially in the
electronic media,'' he said.
   The feed will include live interviews with tobacco trial
attorneys to discuss the legal issues and arguments, according to
an advisory sent to television stations. A Wall Street analyst on
tape will discuss the impact of the verdict on the tobacco
industry, and a legal expert will talk about the ``implications of
such suits for society.''
   Television stations also can receive footage of cigarette
production and of stacks of industry documents provided to
Cipollone's attorneys.
   Neither Scanlon nor Ricke would comment on the cost of the feed,
which is being produced by the business television division of
Visnews International, a TV news agency. A satellite company
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said reserving eight
hours of satellite time averages about $5,000, not including
production and distribution costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880611-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 1354EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NorthDakotaLottery     06-11 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-North Dakota Lottery,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proposed Lottery Faces Different Sort Of Opposition in Second
Go-Round</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALE WETZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former governor fighting to defeat a
state lottery initiative for the second time in as many years has
picked up an unlikely ally _ representatives of the state's
multimillion-dollar gambling industry.
   ``They just happen to be on the same side that we've been on
since the proposal on lotteries has started,'' said Arthur Link, a
former congressman who was North Dakota governor from 1972 to 1980.
``I don't think it's ironic.''
   Lined up in opposition with Link, who opposes a state lottery as
a regressive tax on poorer citizens, are charities that are allowed
to run casino gambling in North Dakota.
   The proposal's primary backer predicts the measure will succeed
this year, helped by increased public awareness of flourishing
lotteries in neighboring South Dakota and Montana.
   ``Good God, we're the only one left,'' says Gorman King Sr., a
Mandan businessman who is spearheading the pro-lottery effort.
   Twenty-six states and the District of Columbia are operating
lotteries, and Wisconsin and Virginia are scheduled to start them
this summer. Voters in neighboring Minnesota are to decide in
November whether to allow one.
   North Dakota is the only state that has voted down a state-run
lottery.
   Voters will cast ballots in Tuesday's primary on whether to
approve a state lottery, which is now banned by the state
Constitution. The state's voters first rejected a lottery almost a
century ago, after gambling interests attempted to bribe the
Legislature into starting one.
   The constitution was changed recently to allow ``public-spirited
organizations'' to run gambling casinos, and more than 300 groups,
ranging from humane societies to American Legion posts, offer
bingo, blackjack and other games to benefit a variety of charities.
   North Dakotans spent $189.2 million on charitable gambling last
year, and once prizes, taxes and allowable expenses were deducted,
charities netted slightly more than $17 million in 1987, according
to the most recent attorney general's report.
   Critics contend a lottery would lure away the discretionary cash
North Dakotans now use for bingo and blackjack and thus hurt the
charities.
   ``It could have a direct effect on the organizations that are
trying to continue to fund their programs,'' said R.S. Guilderhus,
executive director of the Fargo-based Red River Human Services
Foundation.
   A lottery could conceivably drain away 70 to 80 percent of the
$500,000 in annual gambling proceeds his foundation now spends on
services, Gilderhus said.
   Winston Satran, director of the Home on the Range for Boys near
Sentinel Butte in extreme western North Dakota, said about 15
percent of the ranch's private donations come from fraternal
organizations that raise money from gambling.
   ``I think those (lottery) dollars would be diverted from what is
being spent on charitable gambling now,'' he said.
   King estimates a North Dakota lottery would gross $20 million
annually, with half of that sum returned to players as prizes. Of
the remainder, $7 million, or 35 percent, would go to the state
general fund; 10 percent would pay for lottery expenses; and 5
percent would go to vendors as commissions.
   ``It would be that much less that (the Legislature) would be in
your pocket for,'' King said of the projected $7 million in
proceeds. ``And it's a voluntary tax. It's up to you whether you
want to do it or not.''
   Link, a longtime friend of King, contends a lottery amounts to a
regressive tax on lower-income people and that its benefits would
be outweighed by its potential social costs.
   A lottery also represents a step beyond the existing charitable
gambling industry, said Link.
   ``This changes the role of government completely, in that it
puts the state government as the official promoter,'' Link said.
``The state ... is encouraging its own citizens to buy into a game
of chance where most of them have to lose. That's not the role of
state government.''
</TEXT>
