<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 1435EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Protest     06-11 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Protest,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>KGB Agents Reportedly Beat Protesters at Unauthorized
Demonstration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG </BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dissident said Saturday that KGB agents in
civilian clothes beat and threw protesters to the ground while
breaking up an unauthorized demonstration by dissidents demanding
the release of political prisoners.
   Yuri Mityunov said at least 12 members of the Democratic Union
opposition political group were dragged away and detained 15
minutes after the protest began Saturday in Moscow's Pushkin Square.
   ``The KGB were extremely rough,'' Mityunov, the Democratic
Union's spokesman, said in a telephone interview. ``They threw
people to the ground, and beat one woman so badly that people
became indignant.''
   Western journalists at the scene said young men in civilian
clothes dragged the demonstrators off the square. A week ago, a
demonstration was held in the same square but was not interrupted.
   The protesters Saturday, said by Mityunov to number about 100,
had gathered to call for the release of Valeriya Novotvorskaya, 38,
who was detained at 6 a.m. Friday at her Moscow apartment.
   The philologist and library worker, one of the founders of the
fledgling Democratic Union, is accused of taking part in an illegal
demonstration on April 15. Other members of the group say she has a
history of heart problems and is very ill.
   Mityunov said police did not permit her to take her medicine
with her when she was detained and said police refused her request
for medical assistance.
   Mityunov said the protesters in Pushkin Square carried banners
calling for the release of Ms. Novotvorskaya, for freedom for all
Soviets imprisoned for their views and for ``an end to repression.''
   He said one man was detained for handing out leaflets that
called for Ms. Novotvorskaya's release and that the others were
taken away by police because they had been carrying protest signs.
   ``They are now in one of Moscow's militia stations,'' Mityunov
said. ``Officials are not telling us where.''
   Last Sunday, members of the Democratic Union joined with groups
of Armenians and Crimean Tatars on Pushkin Square to call for the
release of Soviet political prisoners.
   When the demonstrators marched down Gorky Street, they were
given a police escort. Although they were not allowed to proceed to
Red Square, their chosen destination, police made no move to stop
them when they gathered across from Moscow's city hall and chanted
slogans.
   The Democratic Union was organized last month by a group of
Soviets who want to challenge the political monopoly of the
Communist Party. Among other goals, they are seeking a multi-party
parliamentary system along Western lines and the withdrawal of
Soviet troops from Eastern Europe and territory incorporated by the
Soviet Union during World War II.
   Group members say that if Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
policy of ``glasnost,'' or openness, is genuine, they will be
allowed to campaign for office.
   However, Mityunov said the fact that KGB agents, and not police
officers, broke up Saturday's demonstration was significant and
potentially worrisome.
   The Committee for State Security, known by its Russian-language
initials as the KGB, is attached to the Council of Ministers, the
equivalent of the country's Cabinet.
   ``Authorities here have decided to permit a small possibility of
democratization, but now they're starting to make
differentiations,'' Mityunov said. ``I think the powers that be
want to make a selection and arrest members of groups that are
hostile to them.''
   He said other unofficial groups were allowed to gather on
Pushkin Square at 4 p.m., less than one hour after the Democratic
Union's protest was broken up, and that no official move was made
to disperse them.
</TEXT>
