<DOCNO> AP880611-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 1515EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mecham     06-11 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham,0669</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham Criminal Case Goes To Jury This Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Evan Mecham long has
acknowledged he didn't itemize a $350,000 campaign loan on his
financial statements, but it will be up to a jury to decide this
week if that failure was a criminal act.
   Closing arguments are scheduled Tuesday after seven days of
testimony in the trial of the impeached Mecham and his brother,
Willard, on charges of concealing the loan.
   The prosecution's case is based on ``smoke and mirrors,'' Mecham
told reporters after the defense rested its case Friday without
testimony from either defendant.
   ``I'm confident that the state has not proven its case,'' the
former governor said, although he stopped short of predicting he
will be acquitted.
   ``We are confident that the jury will return a just verdict,''
prosecutor Barnett Lotstein said Friday.
   Mecham, a Republican, was removed from office April 4 by
impeachment conviction on two unrelated charges. The state Senate
decided not to consider a charge on the loan for fear of
prejudicing the criminal trial.
   He also was the subject of a recall movement, but an election
was canceled after his impeachment conviction.
   Mecham, 64, first received national attention in January 1987
for his decision to cancel a Martin Luther King holiday for state
executive branch workers on grounds it was illegally created by his
predecessor, Democrat Bruce Babbitt, without legislative
authorization.
   Mecham also drew criticism for defending an author's use of the
word ``pickaninny'' in a book in reference to black children, and
he made a variety of statements that offended women, Jews,
homosexuals and Japanese-Americans.
   In the criminal case, he faces up to 22 years in prison if
convicted on all six felony counts of perjury, willful concealment
and filing false documents.
   Willard Mecham, who was treasurer for his younger brother's 1986
campaign, faces up to 9{ years in prison if convicted of three
similar counts.
   The prosecution contended that Mecham's campaign badly needed
the $350,000 loan from developer Barry Wolfson, but that Mecham
wanted to conceal its source because it would contradict his
campaign theme of being ``beholden to no one.''
   None of Mecham's personal or campaign financial reports lists a
$350,000 loan from Wolfson. Instead, one campaign report includes a
$465,000 lump sum identified as a contribution from Mecham himself.
The $450,000 also included a $100,000 loan to Mecham from a
financial institution and a $15,000 contribution by Mecham.
   The Mechams put up two defenses: that the loan was properly
listed as part of the $465,000 lump sum, and that the failure to
itemize the loan was an innocent mistake by Willard Mecham.
   Also, former top Mecham aide Edith Richardson testified for the
defense that the loan was ``common knowledge'' among Mecham's inner
circle.
   The prosecution said it was immaterial whether Mecham's closest
aides knew about the Wolfson loan.
   ``This is the document where the public gets its information,
isn't that true?'' prosecutor Michael Cudahy asked one witness,
referring to Mecham's contribution and expenditure report. ``I'm
not talking about insiders in the campaign, finance chairmen, close
confidantes of Evan Mecham.''
   Mecham long has acknowledged that the Wolfson loan appeared
nowhere on his financial statements outside of the $465,000 lump
sum, until he filed an amended form in November 1987.
   He also insisted last fall that the loan was made to the
campaign, not to him personally.
   But Wolfson testified that he considered the loan a personal
one, not to the campaign.
   A former Mecham campaign finance committee member, Vern Gasser,
testified that he couldn't recall the meaning of notes he took
during a committee meeting in fall 1986. The notes said ``show Evan
borrowed money'' and ``don't show borrowed money.''
   Mecham refused to say Friday why he did not testify. His
attorney, Michael Scott, said he wanted to avoid having his client
``brutalized'' on cross-examination.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880611-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 1528EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w BC-DemocratsText     06-11 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Democrats Text,650</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the Democratic Party's
response to President Reagan's weekly radio address Saturday, given
by Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri:
   Since 1981, we've seen our trade deficit skyrocket more than
four times over. We've seen millions of manufacturing jobs lost and
thousands of farmers thrown off their land.
   During these years, the president has stood idly by, failing to
develop a trade policy to enhance American competitiveness. He even
called our trade deficit a sign of strength.
   Three years ago, the Democrats took the bull by the horns and
crafted a trade policy that would enhance our competitiveness. We
fought for fundamental change in our trade policy and were able to
forge a consensus, at least among Democrats, about what we must do
to do compete, strengthen education, improve productivity, and
invest in plan and equipment and people. The human factor would be
the most decisive factor of production.
   In a historic effort, Democrats working with Republicans were
able to craft a bill. It took three years and countless discussions
to write. It was designed to put the tools in the hands of our
workers and businesses, to improve our competitiveness and pry open
markets.
   Despite the strong support for the bill, President Reagan vetoed
the measure. In doing so, he deprived us of the trade policy we so
desperately need.
   President Reagan based his veto on his objection to the plant
closing provision in the bill _ a provision which he claims will
hurt business and had nothing to do with trade. America needs the
plant closing law.
   If we're going to prepare for the future rather than protect
against it, we must give our workers the time needed to adjust and
find new employment. It's a simple provision. It requires
management to give workers a 60-day notice of impending plant
closure _ nothing more, nothing less.
   During my travels across the country, I met countless workers
who had suffered from the lack of a plant-closing provision. There
is simply no justification for a worker showing up at the plant
gate for work to find it chained shut.
   Many businesses have joined with the president in fighting the
provision. At the same time they have fought for their own golden
parachute and 60-day notification for themselves in hostile
takeover situations. They refuse to grant workers the same
consideration. .
   I refuse to accept the president's notion that people can be
treated just like any other asset, to be discarded when no longer
needed. Our workers are the best in the world. They've proven their
ability to adapt to change. In many cases, labor and management
working together have been able to find solutions to the company's
problems.
   The plant closing provision is an investment in our people. It's
unfortunate that the president chose to scuttle the trade bill
because of his opposition to this provision. We desperately need a
trade bill. Trade is not an academic issue; it is a human issue. We
cant continue to follow the course set by this administration.
   We've seen our position as the world's largest creditor nation
erode to that of the largest debtor. We continue to run historic
trade deficits. Behind these numbers are real people _ business
people and workers who've seen their companies go under because of
unfair foreign competition, farmers who have lost their farms
because they can't sell their products overseas.
   It's time for a change in our trade policy to put our economic
ship of state back on course. The plain and painful fact is that
without any incentive for reciprocity many of our trading partners
are using our outdated assumptions to take advantage of us. We've
got to realize that the world has changed and we must change with
it.
   Mr. President, the trade deficit is not a sign of strength; it's
a sign of a failed policy. We must now work together to change that
policy and make America strong again.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
