<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SoCalQuake     06-11 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SoCal Quake,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Aqueduct Still Shut Down By Quake-Caused Power Failure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crews worked around the clock Saturday to
repair earthquake damage at a pumping plant that shut down the
California Aqueduct and its supply of water to the southern half of
the state, officials said.
   The damage to circuit breakers at the A.D. Edmonston Pumping
Plant, which pumps water over the Tehachapi Mountains northwest of
Los Angeles, was the most significant damage from Friday's quake.
   There was no water shortage because of sufficient supplies in
storage lakes, according to state Department of Water Resources
dispatcher Harry Said in Sacramento.
   ``The aqueduct itself ... is intact with no damage,'' he said,
and the plant was expected to begin pumping again on a limited
basis on Sunday.
   The only injuries blamed on the quake, felt in central and
southern areas of the state, were in Whittier, east of Los Angeles,
where a tree fell about the time of the temblor. A woman and two
men were treated for injuries, said Fire Capt. Harold Fullbright.
   The quake also tumbled rocks onto Interstate 5 close to the
quake's center, but traffic was not blocked. The quake was also
strong enough to knock goods off shelves at a Wheeler Ridge truck
stop.
   The temblor at 4:06 p.m. Friday measured 5.2 on the Richter
scale. It was centered on the Garlock Fault, 11 miles
north-northeast of Gorman in the Tehachapis northwest of Los
Angeles, according to seismologists at the California Institute of
Technology in Pasadena.
   It was followed by a series of aftershocks, the largest
measuring 4.0.
   The 200 mile-long Garlock Fault is the second-largest fault in
California. The largest is the 600 mile-long San Andreas Fault.
   The California Aqueduct runs 440 miles from Tracy, near the
Sacramento River delta, taking water that has flowed to the delta
from rivers in northern California, south to Perris in Riverside
County. It provides half of Southern California's water.
</TEXT>
