<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 1614EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-GOP-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0545 06-11 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GOP-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0545,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Primary Rivals Hit Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 graf following 11th graf pvs, bgng, ``Somebody
ought to xxx etc., to UPDATE with Kemp quotes.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vanquished Republican presidential candidates said
Saturday that George Bush represents ``safe change'' and transition
from the Reagan era, but warned GOP activists it would be fatal to
take his election for granted.
   ``It is not for the vice president to win this election by
himself,'' Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole told a ``Unity '88''
conference. ``The task is too large, the stakes are too high and
the opposition too bitter.''
   Dole was joined by Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y., and former Secretary
of State Alexander M. Haig Jr. in seeking to rally party officials
and activists from 16 states while Bush enjoyed a one-day campaign
respite in Houston.
   Meanwhile, Bush's campaign manager, Lee Atwater, said he would
not worry if Bush continued to trail Democrat Michael Dukakis in
the polls because Bush ``operates better in the underdog position.''
   Atwater also said he believes that Bush has a wellspring of
support in Florida, Texas, the Sun Belt states and much of the
west, and that this translates to a core support base constituting
210 of the 270 Electoral College votes needed to win.
   ``He's constantly underestimated,'' Atwater told the party
activists.
   Atwater said the possible disaffection of Jesse Jackson from the
Democratic cause, if Jackson is given short-shrift treatment in
Atlanta by Dukakis, ``offers a great opportunity'' for Bush to
improve his standing among minority voters.
   He also said he expects Bush to reap much of the support from
Democrats and independents who backed Ronald Reagan, saying these
voters ``will come back in droves'' when the Dukakis' views become
better known.
   Bush has been trailing Dukakis in public opinion polls,
sometimes by 15 or more percentage points. But Atwater noted Bush's
comeback from his loss to Dole in the leadoff Iowa caucuses and
said, ``Now, he operates better in the underdog position. He enjoys
it more. I don't care if we're behind. We may be behind all along.''
   The former candidates coupled appeals for Bush support with
stinging denunciations of Dukakis, the likely Democratic nominee.
   ``Somebody ought to let Gov. Dukakis know that there is no
owner's manual for the White House,'' said Dole, who during the
campaign had accused Bush of being a do-nothing stand-in for
President Reagan at ceremonial events.
   Kemp, speaking to a luncheon audience, urged Bush to keep
working to broaden the base of the party. He also said the
Republicans should not concede the Northeast to Dukakis.
   ``Please don't write off the Northeast. Please don't think we
can win by knitting together some kind of electoral base from the
Sun Belt, and forget the Northeast. ... Don't write off anybody,''
he said.
   Haig said that Bush ``represents safe change'' for America,
while Dukakis would bring about ``radical and dangerous change.''
   ``I think America in 1988 does not want extremism of the left or
righp,'' zaig said.
   Haig said the Massachusetts governor is the voice for
``discredited and disconsolate liberals,'' and told his GOP
audience the party must work to bring back disaffected
conservatives in its own ranks.
   ``We know that the Reagan revolution, the Reagan era, is nearly
over,'' he said. Haig said some conservatives who supported the
Reagan cause have become disenchanted, and he said the party must
be vigilant about voters who thirst for change after seven and a
half years.
   ``Many are beginning to nit-pick at the fringes,'' displaying
worry about such problems as drugs and declining educational
performance, he said.
   Speculation about Bush's likely choice as a vice presidential
running mate hovered over this meeting, popping up in lounge and
coffee-shop talk at the Hyatt Regency hotel here.
   During a workshop speech, Haig joked about suggestions that
``we're all here because we all want to be on the ticket.'' The
former NATO commander and onetime White House chief of staff for
President Nixon said ``I'm content'' with having made a try for the
GOP nomination.
   Bush has indicated he will not seriously consider whom to select
until Dukakis has made his choice known.
   Party Chairman Frank Fahrenkopf urged Republican activists to
work hard for Bush at the grass-roots level, saying that ``you
don't do from a podium, you don't do it with slick television ads,
and George Bush will not be the next president of the United States
unless we do it _ work hard.''
   Dole said Bush supporters should not be disheartened by the
various polls showing the vice president trailing Dukakis, saying
the governor had benefitted from eight weeks of primary victories
after the GOP race had essentially ended.
   America likes ``the calm and reassuring continuity George Bush
represents,'' Dole said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
