<HEAD>30,000 March Against Apartheid In Netherlands</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mandela Rally, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 30,000 people marched
against apartheid Saturday in one of the largest Dutch
demonstrations against South Africa's government, police said.
   No arrests occurred during the peaceful demonstration, said a
police official, who spoke on conditon of anonymity.
   The demonstration, which caused huge traffic jams downtown,
coincided with a 10-hour rock concert in London honoring Nelson
Mandela, a jailed black South African anti-apartheid leader.
   The demonstrators carried banners denouncing South Africa's
government as ``fascist.''
   During the rally, the Rev. Alan Boesak, the South African
anti-apartheid activist, attacked South Africa's system of racial
separation, in which its 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs.
   The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate
districts, schools and health services.
   Anti-apartheid feelings are widespread in the Netherlands, from
where the first white settlers of South Africa sailed in the early
17th century.
</TEXT>
