<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Gore     06-11 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Gore,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Joins In Spoof To Benefit American Cancer Society</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Was the American Cancer Society guilty
of ``boarish'' behavior in putting Sen. Albert Gore Jr.'s name on a
fund-raising letter advertising its Swine Ball without asking him
first?
   Gore's name appeared as honorary chairman of Saturday night's
charity event on a mailing signed by ``The Pig Fairy,'' and the
onetime presidential hopeful suggested, tongue-in-jowl, that
perhaps a federal investigation should be launched into
unauthorized use of his name.
   ``It is an honor to be named honorary chairman. Of course, it
would have been an even greater honor if they had asked me first,''
he said.
   Gore said he learned of the letter when Tennessee Valley
Authority Chairman Marvin Runyon wrote to him, remarking,
``Frankly, I am very surprised that you would allow your name to be
used with such a boarish event.''
   Runyon also said that in view of the fact that the number 1992
might have some significance for Gore, he was sending a check for
$1992 to the Swine Ball.
   ``This is a $4 reduction from last year, as I think under your
honorary leadership the event will be awful,'' Runyon joked.
   Gore, noting that Runyon actually gave $2,000 last year, called
the letter ``shocking evidence'' that the chairman of the
multimillion-dollar TVA ``cannot do simple arithmetic,'' since the
check is actually an $8 reduction from his previous donation.
   The Swine Ball is a spoof of the high-society Swan Ball, which
raises money for the Cheekwood Art Museum.
   Country superstar Waylon Jennings was to join the Metro Police
Blue Lights Band as entertainment at the fund-raiser, where guests
dine on hot dogs on stale buns, pig knuckles, beans, barbecue and
beer.
</TEXT>
