<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrainDerailment     06-11 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Train Derailment,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rail Worker Injured, Traffic Rerouted in Train Derailment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four railroad tanker cars, including two
containing flammable chemicals, overturned near downtown Saturday,
forcing authorities to close one of the city's main thoroughfares.
   A railroad worker was taken to a hospital with minor injuries he
received from inhaling vapor given off by anhydrous trimethylamine,
a volatile chemical that leaked from one of the cars.
   Only a small amount of vapor was escaping, said Deputy Fire
Chief William Hanf, and the other three cars were not leaking. One
of the other cars contained butane and the other two were empty.
   The accident occurred shortly after noon near the intersection
of Ohio 315, which links the city and its city's northern suburbs,
and Goodale Boulevard just northeast of downtown. Police and fire
officials closed two entrances to Highway 315.
   Charles Hartley, 41, the injured worker, was in fair condition
at Doctor's Hospital-North, a nursing supervisor said.
   According to a hazardous materials handbook published by the
U.S. Department of Transportation, anhydrous trimethylamine gives
off vapor that is irritating and harmful if inhaled and is
extremely flammable. The fumes may be ignited by heat, sparks or
flame, the handbook said.
   Butane, which is used as a fuel, is explosive and flammable.
</TEXT>
