<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 1652EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Turkey     06-11 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Turkey,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turkish Premier Due on Landmark Visit to Greece</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premiers Andreas Papandreou of Greece and
Turgut Ozal of Turkey open talks under tight security Monday in an
effort to cement a fragile reconciliation between the traditionally
hostile NATO allies.
   Ozal's three-day visit to Athens _ the first by a Turkish
premier in 36 years _ is the latest move to improve relations after
a Greek-Turkish summit at the Swiss ski resort of Davos in January.
   ``We went to Davos and agreed on a no-war course ... we haven't
ensured peace, but we're striving for consolidation of peace in the
region,'' Papandreou recently told Parliament.
   Fifteen months ago, Greece and Turkey nearly went to war over
oil-drilling rights in the Aegean in a flare-up that apparently
persuaded Papandreou to change his hard-line policy toward Turkey.
   For years, the former American economics professor had rejected
Ozal's offers of friendship, suggesting that Turkey had deep-laid
plans to invade several Greek islands near Turkey's Aegean coast.
   Papandreou's anti-Turkish rhetoric struck a chord with Greeks
who view Turkey with suspicion tinged with fear _ a legacy of four
centuries of Ottoman Turkish rule in Greece and periodic eruptions
of violence over the past 30 years.
   ``There were anti-Greek riots in Turkey in the 1950s, trouble
over Cyprus in the '60s and the Turkish invasion of Cyprus in 1974.
It's hard to believe the Turks really want to be friends,'' said
businessman Ioakim Papazoglou, whose family used to live in Turkey.
   Although Greeks welcome the reduced tension, the speed and style
of Papandreou's policy switch has produced criticism from both
conservatives and leftists.
   ``Perhaps the suddenness of Davos took people by surprise, but
what's being done is a step-by-step process that will take a long
time, perhaps a decade, to bear fruit,'' said a Greek diplomat who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Conservatives claim Papandreou has yielded ground to Turkey by
focusing on minor issues and boosting trade rather than on the
topics dividing the two countries.
   The crucial problems, they say, are the disputes over sharing
mineral rights in the Aegean continental shelf and the divided
island of Cyprus.
   Greece wants Turkey to agree on an appeal to the World Court for
a ruling on the continental shelf problem. Turkey would prefer the
dispute to be solved through direct talks.
   Following a public outcry over his failure to raise the issue at
his first meeting with Ozal of 1,619 Greek Cypriots missing since
the Turkish invasion, Papandreou says he will certainly raise the
Cyprus problem this time.
   During Ozal's visit, Greek Cypriots living in Athens intend to
march to the Turkish Embassy and lay a wreath outside Parliament.
   Greece is disappointed that Turkey hasn't withdrawn some of the
30,000 Turkish troops occupying the northern third of Cyprus as
proof of its commitment to better relations.
   The island was divided into Greek Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot
sectors by the Turkish invasion that followed a 1974 coup aimed at
uniting Cyprus with Greece.
   Greece also has linked Turkey's application to join the European
Economic Community with Cyprus. Papandreou has said Greece would
assist Turkey's membership bid in the 12-nation trade bloc if the
Cyprus problem was solved.
   The two premiers will meet in the seaside suburb of Vouliagmeni
under tight security. The security was stepped up following
anti-Turkish demonstrations and bomb attacks against Turkish
diplomats' cars during visits in May by Istanbul Mayor Bedrettin
Dalan and Turkish Foreign Minister Mesut Yilmaz.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880611-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 1703EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-OPEC     06-11 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OPEC,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OPEC President Urges Members to Set Aside Differences</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC President Rilwanu Lukman on Saturday
opened the cartel's 83rd meeting by urging members to set aside
their differences and reach a production pact that would stabilize
the floundering oil market.
   ``Only an accord based on consensus will achieve the required
impact and send the right signals to the market,'' Lukman told the
12 other oil ministers in his opening speech at the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries' regular mid-year meeting.
   The meeting began after 6 p.m. (12 noon EDT), more than three
hours late, lasted two hours, and adjourned until 10 a.m. (4 a.m.
EDT) Sunday.
   OPEC will try to decide whether to change an agreement among 12
of its 13 members to limit output to 15.06 million barrels a day.
The agreement, which was extended in December and expires June 30,
was designed to support oil prices at $18 a barrel.
   Iraq did not join in the pact, insisting on a quota equal to
Iran. The two nations have been at war since September 1980.
   Lukman, Nigeria's oil minister, was elected OPEC president for
another six months in a vote taken at the start of the first
session. He assumed the post in June 1986 and has been re-elected
at every meeting since then.
   Fernando Santos-Alvite, Ecuador's oil minister, was re-elected
vice president.
   Pessimism about the possibility of the cartel reaching agreement
on a new accord has depressed the oil markets, pushing prices well
below the target.
   The spot price of North Sea Brent Blend, the most widely traded
international crude oil, fell 52 cents to $15.85 a barrel on
Friday. West Texas Intermediate, the U.S. benchmark crude, dropped
42 cents to $16.865 on the spot market.
   A Venezuela-led group has wanted to cut production to push oil
prices up while Saudi Arabia leads other OPEC members who want to
raise output or at least hold it steady to maintain the cartel's
market share.
   Industry analysts believe OPEC is so deeply divided that it will
extend its current agreement for three or six months.
   But late Saturday, Venezuela appeared to have softened its
position.
   Its oil minister, Arturo Hernandez Grisanti, said, ``I am not
sure we have the unanimity to reduce the production level.
   ``Anyway, if we maintain the current level of production, I
believe that prices will start going back up'' because of an
expected increase in demand in the second half of the year.
   Saudi Arabia has wanted to increase oil output to take advantage
of that anticipated increase in demand.
   The Iran-Iraq war remains a major problem.
   Iranian Oil Minister Gholamreza Aqhazadeh said his country
couldn't guarantee that it would continue to accept a quota, which
currently stands at 2.369 million barrels a day, if Iraq, which is
producing 2.6 million barrels a day, continued to refuse to accept
a quota.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880611-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 1715EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-US     06-11 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-US,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Envoy Says Anti-Nuclear Law Would Shut Down U.S. Bases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States would close its
military bases here and end its security relationship with the
Philippines if an anti-nuclear bill became law, a U.S. diplomat
said Saturday.
   Charge d'Affaires Kenneth Quinn made the statement during a
queston-and-answer session following a speaking engagement in
suburban Quezon City. He was asked if Clark Air Base and Subic
Naval Base would still be useful to the United States if such a law
were passed.
   ``No,'' Quinn replied. ``It's the end of our security
relationship. We will be less capable without Clark and Subic, but
we'll get the job done.''
   The 23-member Senate on Monday approved a bill banning nuclear
weapons and nuclear-armed ships and planes from Philippine
territory. The bill is expected to run into resistance in the
more-conservative, 200-member House of Representatives.
   It also would have to be approved by President Corazon Aquino,
who has veto power.
   U.S. policy is not to confirm or deny the existence of nuclear
weapons in specific places.
   In his talk, Quinn said ``nuclear weapons, for all their
destructive effects, have kept peace better than anything else in
history.''
   Noting that this country has battled a communist insurgency for
19 years now, Quinn said Filipinos ``should not fear nuclear
weapons, but the increasing prospect of communism.''
   ``Filipinos have the right to be worried, but not of nuclear
weapons but of the prospects of radical communism which has
destroyed religion in several countries,'' the diplomat said.
</TEXT>
