<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Generally Dry But Record Lows In East And Northwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Temperatures were unseasonably cool Saturday over the eastern
half of the nation and in the Pacific Northwest, with low
temperature records tied or broken in 33 cities.
   Rain was scarce with showers and thunderstorms primarily over
southern Florida. No city reported more than an inch of rain during
the six hours up to 2 p.m.
   The low temperature of 47 at Knoxville, Tenn., toppled a record
that had stood since 1878, and the low of 49 at Nashville tied a
record on the books since 1877. The low of 43 at Topeka, Kan., tied
a record set in 1889.
   Other records: Astoria, Ore., 40; Atlantic City, N.J., 45, tie;
Batesville, Ark., 47, tie; Baton Rouge, La., 59, tie; Birmingham,
Ala., 50; Bristol, Tenn., 41; Calico Rock, Ark., 41; Camden, Ark.,
49; Chattanooga, Tenn., 49;
   Columbus, Ga., 54; Conway, Ark., 48; El Dorado, Ark., 48;
Fayetteville, Ark., 45; Fort Smith, Ark., 52, tie; Hot Springs,
Ark., 50; Huntington, W.Va., 41, tie; Huntsville, Ala., 52;
Jackson, Miss., 50; Jonesboro, Ark., 49;
   Mena, Ark., 45; Meridian, Miss., 47; Monroe, La., 53;
Montgomery, Ala., 52; Olympia, Wash., 36; Paducah, Ky., 45; Pinson,
Ala., 45; Texarkana, Ark., 52, tie; Waco, Texas, 54; Williamsport,
Pa., 38, tie; Yakima, Wash., 35.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees at Sexton Summit, Ore., to 98 at Tuscon, Ariz. The low for
the day was 32 degrees at Flagstaff, Ariz., about 250 miles north
of Tucson and more than 4,000 feet higher, and at West Yellowstone,
Mont.
   For Sunday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast over
southern and central Florida. Scattered showers and thunderstorms
were forecast from northern New Mexico to Montana and North Dakota.
   Highs in the 70s and upper 60s were predicted from the northern
Rockies to the northern Pacific Coast and along the coast of
California; generally in the 80s and lower 90s east of the Rockies;
and in the 90s and above 100 in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
