<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Religion     06-11 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Religion,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Graham Preaches as Christian Celebration Continues in Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Billy Graham brought his impassioned
brand of preaching to a church packed with Russian Orthodox
believers on Saturday, but the evangelist's fire-and-brimstone
delivery failed to ignite his listeners.
   Graham's appearance was part of this communist country's
celebration of the 1,000th anniversary of the arrival of
Christianity.
   ``Some things change, some things never change,'' Graham told
the crowd gathered in the 17th-century Church of Our Lady of Kazan
at Kolomenskoye in southern Moscow. ``God never changes. Human
nature never changes.''
   ``Your liturgy is based on the Bible. And the Bible says that
the world will be shaken from time to time,'' Graham said, clearly
alluding to the social changes that Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev is attempting through his reforms.
   Graham, a Southern Baptist evangelist, was in Moscow as part of
the officially sanctioned celebration of the introduction of
Christianity into Russia by Prince Vladimir of Kiev in 988.
   Graham's English-language sermon was translated into Russian by
the Rev. Vladimir Sorokin, head of the Russian Orthodox seminary in
the northern Russian city of Leningrad.
   The Soviet congregation reacted coolly to Graham's sermon, only
waving their hands when he asked at one point if they were happy. A
few clapped politely as he was driven away from the church in a
government-owned black Chaika.
   ``It was strange,'' one woman told another as the worshipers
filed from the church and mingled with those who had not been able
to find room inside.
   Blue-shirted uniformed police officers were scattered at the
edge of the grounds but made no move to interfere with the
proceedings.
   Soviet authorities brutally repressed the church in the years
after the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution, especially under Josef V.
Stalin, jailing or killing many priests and nationalizing church
property.
   Until recently, police surrounded churches on such religious
holidays as Easter, allowing only the elderly to enter.
   Under Gorbachev, the state has returned to the church the
Monastery of the Caves in Kiev, agreed to build an old-age home for
priests, and promised to liberalize a 1929 law which sanctioned
suppression of the church.
   In another sign of relaxation, authorities on Friday released a
Russian Orthodox deacon, Vasily Shipilov, who spent 36 of his 60
years in psychiatric prisons.
   Signals that authorities will moderate constraints on the church
have aroused mixed reactions among visiting clergymen.
   Graham, who said during a 1982 visit that he thought the church
in the Soviet Union was free, this time said only that ``the people
seem to be warmer. That makes me glad,'' according to his
spokesman, Edward E. Plowman. Graham did not speak with reporters
at Saturday's service.
   Cardinal John O'Connor of New York said Friday, ``I think anyone
in his right mind prays that Mr. Gorbachev is sincere and wants to
bring about a new era.''
   O'Connor, the highest-ranking American in the largest Vatican
delegation ever to visit the Soviet Union, was scheduled to attend
an evening religious vigil Saturday night.
   That service is in preparation for the celebration Sunday of one
of the holiest dates on the Russian Orthodox calendar, known as
``Sunday of All the Saints Who Shone Forth in the Land of Russia.''
   Soviet President Andrei A. Gromyko, whose prominence in the
Soviet government dates to the Stalin era, met Saturday at the
Kremlin with foreign religious dignitaries who are in Moscow for
the church millennium.
   Gromyko assured his guests that authorities were working quickly
to redraft the law on religion to guarantee greater tolerance of
believers, the official Tass news agency said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
