<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Czechoslovak-Church     06-11 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovak-Church,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholics Rally Behind Defiant Cardinal at Consecration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IVA DRAPALOVA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 5,000 Roman Catholics packed
St. Vitus Cathedral on Saturday for the consecration of two
assistant bishops, the first such appointments allowed by communist
authorities since 1973.
   Catholics seized the opportunity to show their support for
defiant Cardinal Frantisek Tomasek, the archbishop of Prague and
the Catholic primate of Czechoslovakia.
   After the ceremony, hundreds of believers massed at the entrance
to the archbishop's palace, shouting ``We want religious
freedom!,'' ``Long live father cardinal!'' and ``Long live the
pope!''
   Tomasek has come under strong attack from state-run news media
this year for supporting a petition for more religious freedom,
which has been signed by an estimated 600,000 people.
   Saturday's ceremony was the first public consecration of
assistant bishops in Prague in 55 years and was marked by repeated
calls for more bishops denied by the communist regime.
   Tomasek officiated at what was a major church gathering to
celebrate the formal appointment of Jan Lebeda, the 75-year-old
vicar general of Prague and 64-year-old Antonin Liska as assistant
bishops of Prague.
   The state was represented by Minister of Education Milan
Kymlicka and officials of the state church authority, but not by
Vladimir Janku, the head of the department.
   The first churchman to speak was parish priest Karel Otcenasek
from Trmice in northern Bohemia, who was consecrated as bishop in
1951 at age 29 but was never permitted by the authorities to take
up office.
   In his address, frequently interrupted by applause, Otcenasek
assured the cardinal: ``You feel the difficulties and fears of us
all. ... The church in our country speaks in a single voice and
that comes out of your mouth.''
   In April, the cardinal wrote to Premier Lubomir Strougal urging
that the church and the authorities open a new dialogue. The offer
was rejected amid indications the Communist Party is reinforcing
its atheist drive.
   Tomasek said in his short sermon, ``We expect this to be only
the beginning of further consecrations of bishops. Nine dioceses
have been waiting a long number of years for their diocesan
bishops.''.
   Ten bishoprics in all have been reported to be vacant. Tomasek's
mentioning nine apparently has to do with one bishopric being Greek
Orthodox.
   The event was attended by bishops from Poland, East Germany,
West Germany and Austria.
   After the ceremony, papal emissary Archbishop Francesco
Colasuonno addressed the congregation in Czech, assuring the
faithful of ``church solidarity.''
   Later, the faithful lined up six deep along the short route to
the archbishop's palace, cheering church dignitaries as they were
driven by.
   They then gathered in front of the palace, shouting their
support for the cardinal and for religious freedom and singing
hymns.
   The crowd dispersed peacefully after about 45 minutes. Police
looked on but did not interfere.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
