<1ST_LINE>r i AM-East-WestSecurity     06-11 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-East-West Security,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Verity Says Massive Western Investment No Cure-all For East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POTSDAM, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Commerce Secretary C. William
Verity on Saturday said that massive Western loans to the Soviet
bloc could backfire without fundamental changes in the East's
economic system.
   Verity said on the final day of the three-day East-West
conference that large increases in Western lending might boost
living standards in the East ``at least for awhile. ... But such
lending does not generate the means of future repayment.
   ``There are massive systematic failings that can only be solved
by changing the system itself _ by a repudiation of rigid
centrally-planned monopolies and a move toward meaningful prices,
and decentralized enterprise,'' he said.
   West Germany's foreign minister, Hans-Dietrich Genscher, also
told the conference on East-West security that the two German
nations ``bear a special responsibility'' for reuniting Europe.
   Verity urged the East to strive for currency convertibility by
1995 so the Soviet Union and its allies could do business in
international markets using their own currencies.
   ``Currency convertibility is the necessary act for the Eastern
economies to join the world economy,'' Verity said.
   He also criticized the human rights situation in the East bloc,
especially targeting the conference host country, East Germany.
   ``Traveling to Potsdam, most of us drove through check-points in
the Berlin Wall and saw armed guards at the ready. Restrictions on
freedom of movement and conscience are still daily facts of life,''
Verity said.
   Genscher's speech marked the first time a West German leader of
Genscher's rank made an official address in East Germany.
   Genscher, who left East Germany in 1952, made several references
to World War II as well as to atrocities that occurred during Adolf
Hitler's rule of Germany.
   ``It is obvious that we Germans bear a special responsibility
for overcoming the division of our continent,'' Genscher said.
``The bitter experiences of this century prompt those nations to
keep a watchful eye on us Germans.''
   Genscher spoke out strongly for a ``common European house.''
   ``We Germans must render a major contribution to building
confidence between East and West. We want to re-activate the once
so varied and fruitful bonds between Germans and Russians. We want
to develop and deepen them with the aim of overcoming the division
in Europe,'' Genscher said.
   Genscher also praised the reforms of Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev and rejected any suggestion that increased East-West
cooperation could ``decouple the European allies.''
</TEXT>
