<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Queen     06-11 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Queen,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trooping the Color: Queen Honored On Official Birthday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cavalrymen and foot soldiers in scarlet tunics and
bearskin hats paraded in the center of London Saturday to honor
Queen Elizabeth II with the Trooping the Color on her ``official''
birthday.
   The queen, who is 62, celebrated her real birthday on April 21,
but the official birthday ceremonies are held on the second
Saturday of June when the weather normally is better. The sky was
overcast and there was a damp chill in the air Saturday.
   This year, for the first time since 1973, the 1,588 men of all
five regiments of the Brigade of Guards joined the parade because
all are currently based in London.
   The guards _ Grenadier, Coldstream, Scots, Irish and Welsh
regiments _ are often scattered, seeing service in such places as
Northern Ireland and the Falkland Islands.
   Four generations of the royal family joined the ceremony this
year, riding in coaches or on horseback to the Horse Guards Parade,
an open square in Whitehall, where the queen inspected the Irish
Guards while massed bands played.
   Each year one regiment performs the honors, marching in
intricate patterns and carrying the ``color,'' or regimental
standard.
   Elizabeth, wearing a blue coat and wide-brimmed hat, arrived in
a horse-drawn phaeton and took the salute standing on a dais. It
was the second year she had used the carriage since retiring her
horse, Burmese, which she used to ride sidesaddle for the occasion,
wearing a scarlet uniform.
   The queen's 5-year-old grandson, Prince William, was with his
mother, the Princess Diana, and his great-grandmother, Queen Mother
Elizabeth, in her carriage.
   Riding horseback was the heir to the throne, Prince Charles in
his uniform as colonel of the Welsh Guards, along with the queen's
husband, Prince Philip, a colonel of the Grenadier Guards.
   On her return to Buckingham Palace, the queen appeared on a
balcony to wave to her subjects and thousands of tourists.
   Saturday's pageantry was based on the ceremony used for guard
mounting in the 18th century and was first performed on the
sovereign's birthday for King George III. But during the 18th and
19th centuries the trooping was seldom attended by the monarch.
   In 1895, the color was trooped in the quadrangle at Windsor
Castle, west of London, and Queen Victoria took the salute from a
carriage. From that year on, a senior royal person has always been
in attendance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880611-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 1859EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Humphrey-Senate     06-11 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Humphrey-Senate,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Humphrey Wins Senate Endorsement of DFL</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Hubert H. Humphrey III
won the Democratic-Farmer-Labor Party's endorsement on the first
ballot Saturday to challenge Republican U.S. Sen. David Durenberger.
   In his acceptance speech, Humphrey, 45, invoked the name and
ideals of his father, the late vice president who 40 years earlier
won the DFL nod and his first U.S. Senate election.
   ``As I stand here today, I'll say for the record that his vision
of America is still alive, in you and in me _ the people of
Minnesota,'' Humphrey said.
   Humphrey received 64.05 percent of the 1,323 votes cast, four
percentage points more than required for endorsement.
   Peace activist Polly Mann, 67, received 23.52 percent of the
vote, 9.42 percent was for ``no endorsement,'' and 1.63 percent was
for other candidates.
   Humphrey declared the first-ballot endorsement a great victory,
but others said he should have done better.
   ``No one ever says the DFL does things in lockstep,'' said
Humphrey, a former state senator and attorney general since 1983.
   The leader of an anti-abortion caucus took credit for denying
Humphrey, who received 808 votes, an additional 118 votes that were
cast for no endorsement.
   Leo LaLonde said his caucus members refused to vote for Humphrey
because he does not support a constitutional amendment that would
outlaw abortion.
   Prior to the endorsement vote, Humphrey asked for the delegates'
support in a voice reminiscent of his late father.
   ``I ask for your endorsement,'' Humphrey said. ``I ask that you
give us the time and the passion and the energy to make this the
great country that it will be.''
   In his acceptance speech, Humphrey sought to tie Durenberger to
the policies of President Reagan and Vice President Bush.
   ``For the future of our country, we must unite to defeat the
Reagan-Bush administration, and we must defeat their henchmen, like
Dave Durenberger,'' Humphrey said.
   Durenberger, said Humphrey, ``is part of the problem down in
Washington. He talks about Minnesota values but he votes and acts a
different way.''
   Durenberger has voted against school lunch programs, student
loans, Head Start and education funding, Social Security and
Medicare, Humphrey said.
   ``I want to invest in America's future, invest in America's
people again,'' Humphrey said.
   Durenberger is unopposed for the Independent-Republican
endorsement, which is to be made at next weekend's IR state
convention.
</TEXT>
