<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Terrorists     06-11 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Terrorists,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Public Security Says Foreigners' Safety Ensured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China on Saturday said it would ensure the safety
of foreigners here after warning the U.S. Embassy of a possible
terrorist attack on Americans in Beijing.
   ``All foreigners in China, whether they are stationed here on a
long-term basis or have come for a short stay, can conduct their
activities here as usual and should not be worried,'' said the vice
minister of public security, Gu Linfang, in a report carried by the
official Xinhua News Agency.
   Gu also was quoted by Xinhua as saying that ``some persons
recently attempted to harm Americans in China,'' but the report
gave no specifics.
   It quoted Gu as saying, ``The Public Security Department has
already taken necessary measures in this regard, and the problem
has been solved.''
   The U.S. Embassy sent an ``urgent notice'' Thursday to Americans
living in Beijing warning of a possible attack by terrorist from an
unidentified third country.
   High-level Public Security officials informed the embassy of the
threat and told it there was Middle East involvement, but the
Chinese gave no other details, embassy officials said.
   No known incidents have occurred of attacks in China against
Chinese or foreign residents, and China has good relations with
Mideast nations which have been accused of fostering terrorist
activities.
   The embassy in years past sent out similar warnings based on
worldwide alerts against terrorists, but this was the first time
the threat was directed specifically to Americans in China, embassy
officials said.
   On Friday, the Foreign Ministry issued a statement saying, ``The
Chinese government always attaches importance to the security of
foreigners in China, and the security of foreigners in China is
ensured.''
   The advisory sent by the embassy warned Americans to avoid
restaurants, markets, nightclubs and other public places known to
be hangouts for Americans and other foreigners.
   An estimated 1,500 American businessmen, diplomats, students and
teachers and their families live in Beijing.
   Beijing's International School, tourist hotels and American
businesses all stepped up security measures Friday in response to
the warning.
</TEXT>
