<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 1936EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Academy     06-11 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Academy,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Youth Movement Leads To Resignations In Soviet Academy Of Sciences</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixteen members of the Soviet Academy of Sciences
have resigned simultaneously as authorities press a campaign to
bring new blood into the prestigious institution, Tass said
Saturday.
   The official Soviet news agency said it was the largest mass
resignation in the history of the 900-member, Moscow-based academy,
which traces its roots to Peter the Great's creation of a Russian
Academy of Sciences in 1724.
   The academicians' terms normally would not have expired until
1990. Their departure appeared clearly linked to a drive led by
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev to enlist Soviet scientific
apparatus in his drive for scientific and technological progress.
   That step is seen as crucial if Gorbachev's campaign for
``perestroika,'' or economic and social restructuring, is to
succeed.
   Lev Semyonov, head of the academy's personnel department, told
Tass the scientists' mass resignation ``was prompted by a desire to
draw young and talented organizers of science into the
reorganization process more actively.''
   Among those who resigned was Anatoly Alexandrov, who was academy
president until he was replaced in October 1986 by Guri Marchuk.
Alexandrov was named a counselor of the academy's presidium, or
government body, Tass said.
   Six other men who had served as secretaries of various branches
in the academy also asked to be relieved of their duties and made
counselors ``for reasons of age,'' Tass said.
   Elections to fill the vacancies will be held before June 20,
Tass said.
   A rujuvenation process in the academy began in December, when
255 new academicians and lesser-ranking corresponding members were
elected at a two-day meeting of the academy's membership.
   Many newcomers were from 40 to 45 years old.
   New rules were put into effect last year requiring academicians
to retire at age 75.
   Semyonov said ``the renewal of personnel in the academy would go
on,'' Tass reported. He said 20 directors, three deputy directors
and 160 heads of subdivisions still hold their positions despite
their ``advanced age.''
   The academy in the past has jealously guarded its integrity even
at the risk of incurring political displeasure. It insists on
holding its elections by secret ballot, when other Soviet
organizations vote by a public show of hands.
   Physicist and human rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov, an
academy member, was stripped of state honors and privileges after
becoming active in the Soviet dissident movement of the 1970s. But
academy members refused to oust him, and he kept his title of
academician even after being exiled to Gorky in 1980.
   In December 1986, Sakharov, 67, was allowed to return to Moscow
to resume his research work in physics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
