<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BelmontNewspapge     06-11 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Belmont Newspapge,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Risen Star, Son of Secretariat, Wins Belmont Stakes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Risen Star romped to a 14}-length victory in the
Belmont Stakes Saturday in a runaway reminiscent of his father,
Secretariat, who became a Triple Crown champion at Belmont 15 years
ago with a 31-length victory.
   Risen Star, who also won the Preakness, missed matching
Secretariat's Triple Crown by finishing third in the Kentucky
Derby, the first of the three classic races.
   The winning margin was the fourth-largest in the 120 years of
the Belmont. Secretariat set the record in 1973, Count Fleet won by
25 in 1943 and Man O' War won by 20 in 1920.
   Ridden by Eddie Delahoussaye, Risen Star completed the 1{ miles
in 2:26 2-5. It was the second-fastest Belmont ever, topped only by
the American-record 2:24 raced by Secretariat.
   Winning Colors, the filly who won the Kentucky Derby, finished
last in a field of six 3-year-olds and failed in her effort to
become the first filly to win two Triple Crown races.
   Brian's Time finished third, two lengths behind Kingpost and 11\
lengths in front of Cefis. Granacus finished fifth.
   Risen Star paid $6.20, $4.80 and $2.80. Kingpost returned $11
and $3.80 while Brian's Time was $2.60 to show.
   The victory was worth a winner's share of $303,720 to Risen
Star, who also picked a $1 million bonus for having earned the most
points in the three Triple Crown races _ 11 for his third in the
Kentucky Derby and two firsts. Winning Colors also had six points
going into the race.
   The bonanza gave Risen Star a bankroll of $2,029,845 on a record
of eight wins in 11 career starts.
</TEXT>
