<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Virginia-5thDistrict     06-11 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Virginia-5th District,0585</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Ghost Of Daniel Lurks In 5th District Race
^By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DANVILLE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time in 20 years, there's a
tight race in the 5th Congressional District _ to fill the seat of
the late Rep. Dan Daniel, a Democrat who voted often with
conservative Republicans.
   Both Republican Linda Arey and Democrat L.F. Payne Jr. have
tried to portray themselves as the right kind of conservative for
the district described by officials of both parties as one of the
country's most old-fashioned.
   The contest has featured broadcast and campaign-trail
mudslinging, a novelty for the district and one neither side
predicted will work when voters go to the polls in Tuesday's
special election.
   Often, the disputes have centered on what Daniel, who died last
January, would have thought of the race.
   The Arey campaign proudly pointed to an interview late last year
in which Daniel referred to her as his ``ideological soul mate.''
The Payne camp has accused Ms. Arey of trying to put words in a
dead man's mouth by parlaying that comment into an apparent
endorsement.
   Arey's campaign denies the charge.
   ``I'm sure if they had the same quote they would use it,'' Arey
campaign manager Jeff Butzke said.
   About a week before the election, Rep. Stan Parris, the 8th
District Republican, went so far as to say he was ``absolutely
conviced that if Dan Daniel were alive today he would be here
supporting Linda Arey.''
   That did not sit well with 5th District Democrats, who said
neither Ms. Arey nor Payne will ever match Daniel's superb
political ability to please people from each party. Daniel was a
lifelong Democrat who worked his way up from the textile mills yet
voted often with conservative Republicans.
   As the campaign wound down, Daniel's son, Jimmie, had harsh
words about the use of his father's name.
   ``I continue to hear and read from various sources what my
father, Dan Daniel, would be doing if he were alive today,'' Jimmie
Daniel said in a statement. ``Much of what is being said and
written is completely contrary to his view as I knew it. I think it
is unjust and insensitive for a candidate or campaign to speak as
if Dan Daniel had or would have endorsed them.
   ``The fact is, he had not endorsed any candidate for his House
seat. It was his way to seek office on his own merit, and I am sure
that he would prefer that his successor be elected on theirs.''
   Ms. Arey's latest television ads said it was time for voters to
continue the 5th District's conservative ``legacy'' of Daniel.
Payne has said that as a successful developer, he is better
qualified to handle the district.
   Each side has lined up strong partisan support.
   Ms. Arey, who formerly worked in several posts with the Reagan
administration, has the president speaking for her on radio spots.
She also lined up late-campaign appearances by former
Transportation Secretary Elizabeth Dole and Vice President George
Bush, who will be the Republican presidential nominee, as well as
several GOP congressmen.
   Payne has gotten the nod from the commonwealth's Democratic
establishment. Stumping for Payne have been Gov. Gerald Baliles,
Lt. Gov. Douglas Wilder, Attorney General Mary Sue Terry and House
Speaker A.L. Philpott.
   Both sides have predicted a close race and observers have said
there will perhaps be a rematch in November's general election.
</TEXT>
