<1ST_LINE>u w AM-North-Gadhafi 1stLd-Writethru a0573 06-11 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-North-Gadhafi, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0573,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Book: North Wanted To Use Terry Waite To Lure Gadhafi For Bombing
Raid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs before final graf pvs to UPDATE with report
of second North plan to kill Gadhafi.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver North wanted to use Anglican church
envoy Terry Waite to lure Libya's Col. Moammar Gadhafi to his
Tripoli compound to increase chances Gadhafi would be killed in the
1986 U.S. attack, according to book excerpts published in U.S. News
& World Report.
   The plan was considered and rejected, and North had to be
content with drafting a White House statement to be released in the
event Gadhafi was killed, which would call his death
``fortuitous,'' according to the account.
   The book, ``Best Laid Plans, The Inside Story of America's War
Against Terrorism,'' was written by David Martin, Pentagon
correspondent for CBS, and John Walcott, national security
correspondent for The Wall Street Journal.
   It looks at the events surrounding the April 15, 1986, U.S.
bombing raid on Libya, which American officials said were conducted
in response to Libya's role in the bombing of a West Berlin disco
frequented by U.S. servicemen.
   According to the book, North, then a National Security Council
aide, planned to ask Waite to go to Tripoli on April 14 to meet
with Gadhafi. Waite, the hostage negotiator from the Church of
England, would ask Gadhafi's help in freeing the hostages in
Lebanon. Waite would then depart, leaving Gadhafi to spend the
night at his compound, the book said.
   Waite, himself now believed a hostage in Lebanon, would not be
told that he was being used to set Gadhafi up for a killing, the
book said.
   Such an assassination plot would have violated American law.
Previous published reports have said that North and others on the
National Security Council plotted the bombing Libya as a way of
assassinating Gadhafi.
   U.S. officials have said the bombing was not an assassination
plot, although they have conceded that officials ``wouldn't have
been upset'' if Gadhafi had been killed.
   The book, excerpted in the magazine's June 20 issue, also
reports that North was so eager to ``get Gadhafi'' that he doctored
the intelligence section of an ``action memo'' prepared for
President Reagan. North wanted Reagan to think that a second Libyan
raid would be more successful than the intelligence community or
the Pentagon believed, according to the excerpts, which did not
provide further elaboration.
   The bombing mission, known by the code name ``Operation El
Dorado Canyon,'' had among its targets a frogman school, a Tripoli
airfield and the compound that contained Gadhafi's military-staff
headquarters and family home. Some bombs fell on civilian areas,
and one U.S. F-111 bomber never returned, its two-man crew later
declared killed in action.
   Gadhafi was apparently unharmed, although there were rumors that
the attack had left him confused and disoriented. Libyan officials
reported that his 15-month old adopted daughter was killed and two
young sons were wounded.
   CBS reported Saturday that after Gadhafi survived the first
attack, ``North immediately came up with another plan to kill him.''
   Under that plan, North wanted to have an unidentified friendly
foreign leader telephone Gadhafi so that U.S. officials could
monitor the conversation and pinpoint his location, CBS said. That
plan, too, was rejected by administration officials, the report
said.
   North, a former Marine lieutenant colonel, has since retired
from the military and is awaiting trial on charges stemming from
the diversion of profits to the Nicaragua rebels from U.S. arms
sales to Iran. He was fired from his NSC job in November 1986, when
the diversion became public.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880611-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 1954EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Election     06-11 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Election,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Runoff Vote For A New National Assembly Sunday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French voters on Sunday choose a new National
Assembly that either will give President Francois Mitterrand a
Socialist majority or force him to continue ``cohabitation'' with
the right.
   Five weeks after Mitterrand won re-election with a solid 54
percent of the vote over conservative former Premier Jacques
Chirac, the Socialist position appeared to be eroding and what once
was seen as a leftist landslide in the Assembly voting has become a
contest.
   The Socialists recently talked about giving away constituencies
to centrists as part of their ``opening'' to non-Socialists, but
they now are fighting for every seat and acknowledging the
possiblity of defeat.
   Despite polling fewer popular votes nationwide than
conservatives in the first round, the Socialists are given the edge
to win a majority in the Assembly because of peculiarities in the
spread of their support.
   Publication of polls is prohibited by law in the week before an
election, but unpublished surveys indicate a Socialist advantage.
   In the first round of the legislative elections on June 5, the
Socialists won 40 of the 577 seats in the Assembly and the
Communists won one. On the right, the conservative Rally for the
Republic and center-right Union for French Democracy won 77 seats
and minor rightist parties four.
   Sunday's runoffs are being held in the 453 districts where no
candidate won a majority in the first round. In addition, a first
round is being held for two seats in French Polynesia.
   In districts where no candidate won a majority in the first
round, all candidates with 12.5 percent or more were eligible for
the runoff.
   As they have done in past years, the Socialist Party and the
Communist Party agreed to support the leading leftist candidate. In
districts where the Socialist candidate was ahead, the Communist
candidate withdrew, and vice versa.
   The event of the week was the traditional right's similar deal
with the extreme right National Front, the party accused by nearly
all political leaders of being racist and xenophobic. Though
involving only a small number of seats, the left immediately seized
on the issue and accused the Rally for the Republic and Union for
French Democracy of signing a pact with the devil.
   For Jean-Marie Le Pen's National Front, it's the difference
between being shut out of the National Assembly altogether and
winning some seats. For the traditional right, it could be the
difference between being in power or in the opposition.
   The Rally for the Republic and Union for French Democracy denied
there was any ``deal'' with the National Front.
   From 1981 to 1986, the Socialists had absolute power. In 1986,
after the National Assembly's five-year term expired, the right won
a slim majority. But because Mitterrand had two years left on his
seven-year term, the right and the left were forced into
``cohabitation,'' or power-sharing.
   The politicians hated cohabitation. But numerous polls indicated
voters liked the balance of power between the right and the left.
   Analysts said Mitterrand's score was due to his personal
popularity and not necessarily an indication French voters want a
return to leftist policies. On the other hand, his solid victory
did create a certain momentum.
   The president said recently he thought it unhealthy for one
party to have all the power in France. Nonetheless, sensing his
party was in trouble, he went on national television Thursday to
ask voters to give him a clear majority with which to work in
Parliament.
   As in the presidential campaign, not much attention has been
paid to the issues. With all of the talk focusing on the
``opening'' and the National Front, little concrete has been said
about unemployment, social security or education.
   The French may be tired of voting. Turnout during last week's
first round was 65.74 percent _ a postwar low.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
