<HEAD>Student Involved in Rumored Suicide Pact Charged With Underage
Drinking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRVIEW, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager who said his idle threat of a
graduation prank led to rumors of a suicide pact and a school board
decision to cancel the ceremony has been charged with underage
drinking and reckless driving, police said.
   Neal Loeslein, 18, was arrested after his car went out of
control and hit a tree early Friday, state police said. An
18-year-old passenger in Loeslein's car also was cited for underage
drinking. There were no injuries reported
   On Tuesday, the Fairview School Board canceled graduation
ceremonies scheduled for Sunday because of rumors that some
students might kill themselves on stage.
   Loslein said school officials overreacted after he threatened to
``make this graduation one that no one would forget.'' He said he
made the comment to embarrass an assistant principal whom he
disliked, not to promote violence.
   On Christmas Day, Loeslein witnessed the suicide of his best
friend, Theodore Hetz, who shot himself with a .44-caliber Magnum.
   The Fairview Ministerial Association arranged a meeting Sunday
between students and administrators to discuss the situation.
