<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 2017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BoozyAuction     06-11 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boozy Auction,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Booze From Great Lakes Shipwreck Finds Buyers 75 Years Later</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Scotch whisky and scotch cq as AP style. Whyte & Mackay
Scotch Whiskey cq in brand name.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tipplers with a thirst for treasure got a chance
Saturday to bid at an auction of bottles of scotch and champagne
recovered from a Great Lakes shipwreck 75 years ago.
   Susie Shaw bought her dad some Scotch whisky for a Father's Day
present, three bottles that had been slowly vintaging in the cool
waters of Lake Huron since the S.S. Regina went down on Nov. 9,
1913.
   ``It tastes very good,'' said Ms. Shaw of Chicago, who paid $180
for the bottles of Whyte & Mackay Scotch Whiskey and sampled some
of the lake-bed booze at a pre-auction tasting session. ``It's a
novelty, my father is a scotch drinker.''
   So far, about 300 bottles of French champagne and Scotch whisky
have been salvaged from the Regina, one of 19 ships that went down
in the great November storm.
   Several thousand more bottles still rest under 80 feet of water
roughly 3{ miles offshore from Port Sanilac, about 80 miles
northeast of Detroit, said commercial diver Wayne Brusate.
   Brusate accidentally discovered the wreck in July 1986 while
searching for a tugboat that sank in the late 1960s.
   ``I was surprised to find the cases of liquor,'' said Brusate,
of Marysville, Mich. ``Most freighters on the Great Lakes carried
coal, iron ore and tons of wheat, but this was like a general
store.''
   The Regina, a 249-foot Canadian freighter, went down with all 27
crew members during one of the worst storms in Great Lakes history.
   ``You can buy scotch anywhere, but only here can you buy it from
the lake bottom,'' said Deanna Chan, president of Freedom Marine
Ltd. of Vancouver, British Columbia, the ship's salvagers. ``It's a
piece of our history, a collector's item.''
   About 100 people attended Saturday's auction, run by Christie's
auctioneers, at the University Club in downtown Chicago.
   Brent Albrecht, a representative of Clicquot Inc. U.S.A., bid
$85 for a bottle of 1906-1908 vintage Veuve Clicquot for the
champagne company's museum in Reims, France.
   The 60 bottles auctioned brought a total of $3,460, said Michael
Davis, vice-president of Christie's wine division.
   ``This was sort of a first for us, an experiment,'' he said.
``We are neither disappointed or ecstatic, because there's no real
track record for this. We're glad the bottles found buyers.''
   In December, the first auction of Regina artifacts in Detroit
found bidders paying $15-$35 for lumps of coal, matchsticks, and
spoons, Ms. Chan said.
   At a marine auction on Sunday in Newport, R.I., the ship's
compass, navigation lights and other nautical equipment were to be
sold.
   The proceeds will help finance further salvage operations which
are scheduled to resume next month, Brusate said.
   He estimated that only about 10 percent of the ship's cargo has
been recovered so far.
   The search will concentrate on finding the ship's safe, which
reportedly contained $86,000 in gold coins, worth at least $2
million at current bullion prices, Ms. Chan said. The gold was
believed to have been the payroll for workers building the Sault
Ste. Marie locks in Michigan's Upper Peninsula.
   When the salvaging work is completed, the wreck could yield a
treasure worth about $5 million, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
