<1ST_LINE>r p AM-People-Speakes     06-11 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Speakes,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Speakes Says Media Doing Poor Job of Covering Presidential
Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BILOXI, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former White House spokesman Larry Speakes
said Saturday the media is doing a poor job of covering the
presidential campaign, focusing more attention on theatrics than on
issues.
   ``Voters want more meat and potatoes on the election, and the
press is simply not giving that to them,'' Speakes said. ``The
press is giving all mood music and no lyrics. The coverage is very
superficial.''
   Speakes, addressing the Mississippi Association of Broadcasters,
said the media is dead wrong on presidential handicapping.
   ``Don't ever go to the race track with a political reporter,''
he told the broadcasters.
   Speakes was President Reagan's spokesman for six years. He
recently lost his job at Merrill Lynch in the wake of publicity
generated by his admission in his book, ``Speaking Out,'' that he
had concocted quotes he attributed to the president.
   Speakes said the weakness in television election coverage is its
failure to tell voters the candidates' plans.
   ``Television news is giving a hybrid of charisma and fact,''
Speakes said, ``And that's not good enough. Too much is at stake.''
   In its coverage of Jesse Jackson, Speakes said, the media has
been ``lavishing its attention on his charisma, not his specific
plans. There is a schizophrenia in television coverage between
giving information or entertainment.''
</TEXT>
