<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Presbyterians 2ndLd-Writethru a0604 06-11 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presbyterians, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0604,0779</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Major Positions Of Presbyterians Being Refined</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 9th graf ``The committee'' with three grafs to clarify
that incumbent will be nominated from floor, not from committee,
and add background. Picks up 10th graf pvs ``The Christian...'' </NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A committee of the 200th General Assembly of
the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) adopted a resolution Saturday
calling on Israel to end its 20-year occupation of the West Bank
and Gaza Strip.
   The resolution said Israel has ruled the occupied territories
with a repressive policy. It also asks the United States to end aid
that subsidizes Israeli settlements in the occupied territory.
   Elsewhere at the assembly, Presbyterians began taking final
action on less controversial issues facing the denomination while
decisions were pending on major statements on nuclear war, health
care and election of a top officer.
   While the general assembly began receiving committee reports, a
four-member writing team met behind closed doors to draft a
preliminary recommendation on ``Christian Obedience in a Nuclear
Age.''
   The team is working from a paper, written last year after a
five-year study, which has drawn widespread criticism within the 3
million-member denomination for its discussions of tax resistance
and the immorality of nuclear war and nuclear deterrence.
   The writing group, which was joined by the two leaders of the
originating task force, reworked the paper's lengthy policy
statements and background to incorporate changes. The report will
be presented to a subcommittee Sunday, with a report to the entire
Peacemaking and International Relations Committee expected Monday.
   The entire assembly is expected to take up the report Tuesday.
   Also Saturday, a committee recommended that Harriet A. Nelson, a
lay leader from Napa, Calif., be nominated for a four-year term as
stated clerk, the officer responsible for operation of the assembly.
   The committee, which could have nominated two people, considered
seven candidates including the current stated clerk, the Rev. James
E. Andrews, but declined to nominate him.
   Andrews was elected four years ago after serving 10 years as
stated clerk of the Presbyterian Church in the United States and
one-year as co-stated clerk after the mainly southern PCUS rejoined
with the northern church in 1983.
   Andrews and at least one other person have already said they
will be nominated from the floor. The 630 commissioners, or
delegates, are scheduled to vote Tuesday morning.
   The Christian Obedience paper has been revised to delete
corporate church support of tax resistance and other actions of
conscience against the government. However the subcommittee left in
a recommendation for a voluntary Fund for Obedience to Higher
Authority to offer assistance to resisters.
   On Friday, the 18-member subcommittee retained language in the
paper that calls nuclear war immoral. But it changed a section
labeling the theory of nuclear deterrence immoral to read ``nuclear
deterrence as an end in itself'' is immoral.
   The Rev. Arnold Come, a former seminary president who helped
write the original report and sat in on the writing committee, said
he expected some deleted portions would be restored before the
report went to the assembly floor Tuesday.
   A committee also adopted a resolution to provide all delegates
to the assembly with letters to sign and send to Secretary of State
George P. Shultz urging him to work to release U.S. and other
hostages held in Lebanon.
   Tom Sutherland, one of the Americans held hostage, is a
Presbyterian elder and president of American University in Beirut
who has been held four years last week.
   The committee also voted to distribute yellow ribbons to the
commissioners to help remember the hostages, who also include Terry
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press
when he was taken hostage March 1985.
   Sunday's major event is a kickoff of the church's bicentennial
year celebration with a hour-long television program being beamed
by satellite around the country.
   The denomination was formed in 1983 from two Presbyterian groups
that had split during the Civil War and is almost 14 times larger
than the second-largest group, the Presbyterian Church in America.
   The assembly rejected a resolution Saturday asking that the
organization begin reunion talks with the conservative,
200,000-member PCA, which is based in Atlanta.
   In addition, a report was adopted critizing the Evangelical
Presbyterian Church, a 27,000-member denomination which the PCUSA
accused of undermining some local congregations in efforts to get
them to switch denominations.
   Commissioners approved the church's continued involvment in the
Consolution on Church Union, an effort by nine Protestant
denominations to move toward agreements recognizing each other's
sacraments by the mid-1990s.
</TEXT>
