<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0584 06-11 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0584,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas And Contras Peg Peace Prospects On Washington</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with Ortega blaming Reagan for
collapse of talks; picks up 3rd pvs: And the..</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega on Saturday
blamed the Reagan administration for the breakdown of peace talks
with U.S.-backed rebels but said his government was prepared to
resume negotiations.
   Ortega told a group of factory workers in Managua that the
United States was seeking ``to make dust of the peace plan, to burn
it, incinerate it.''
   He claimed that rebel leaders met in Washington with Elliott
Abrams, assistant secretary of state for inter-American affairs,
several days before last week's three days of negotiations to work
out a strategy ``to kill the peace plan.''
   But he said his Sandinista government is prepared ``to continue
discussing outstanding points in the negotiating process'' with the
rebels.
   Both the Sandinistas and rebels appear to be pegging their peace
proposals on Washington's reaction after the collapse on Thursday
of the latest round of talks.
   It is believed the Sandinistas hope to achieve a peace pact with
the rebels, known as Contras, before the Reagan administration
leaves office next year. President Reagan is a strong backer of the
Contras and a peace agreement could dim if not eliminate prospects
for renewed U.S. military aid to the rebels.
   And the Contras say the possibility of a resumption of such aid
puts pressure on the government to accept democratic reforms.
   The fourth round of talks failed last week to find an end to the
war that has been waged for more than six years. Although the
Contras said there would be no further meetings, it appeared that
they left the door ajar.
   Alfredo Cesar, the head of the Contra delegation, said Thursday
as the talks broke off, ``We have reiterated our deep conviction to
looking to solutions to the conflict in our motherland in a
civilized way.''
   Contra leader Adolfo Calero was in Washington last week and was
quoted by the rebels' Radio Liberacion as saying, ``The armed road
is the only option left for democratization in Nicaragua.''
   A Contra plan submitted Thursday was described by the government
as ``irrational.'' It called on the Sandinistas to disband the
Supreme Court, revise the public security law, rewrite the
electoral laws and set up an assembly to rewrite the 1987
constitution.
   The White House put the blame for the breakdown of the talks on
Sandinista ``intransigence.'' Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the
Reagan administration was studying renewed military aid to the
rebels.
   Washington had backed and trained the rebels covertly or with
congressional approval since 1981. Military aid legally stopped
Feb. 29, and Congress voted down Reagan's request for more war
funding.
   The U.S. Congress last approved Contra military aid in June
1986. The Soviet bloc and Cuba support the Sandinistas.
   On the first of three days of talks last week, the Sandinista
delegation claimed the rebels wanted the negotiations to fail to
pave the way for new U.S. militlary aid.
   A cease-fire has been in effect since March 21, but both sides
have accused the other of violations.
   The Sandinistas' 80,000-member armed forces have continued to
receive Soviet military goods and it is believed the Contras, said
to number between 6,000 and 10,000, have been stockpiling supplies
and weapons during the fragile truce.
   The Sandinistas have been in power since July 1979 after
defeating the forces of right-wing President Anastasio Somoza in a
civil war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
