<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Pollution     06-11 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Pollution,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>200,000 Without Water After Pollution Poisons Loire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOURS, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city fire department doled out water
under police and army protection Saturday as the homes of more than
200,000 people remained cut off from drinking water because a
chemical fire polluted the Loire River.
   Thirty trucks and two trains had hauled more than 1,300,000
gallons of drinking water to Tours since Friday.
   Tours Deputy Mayor Jean Royer asked citizens not to water
gardens or wash cars and not to hoard bottled drinking water.
   Investigators tested the level of carcinogenic pollution in the
Loire after an explosion and fire at the Protex factory in
Anzouer-en-Touraine, 15 miles northeast of Tours Wednesday. The
accident injured one person and sent cancer-causing phenol and
metallic pollutants into the Brenne, a tributary of the Loire.
   Protex makes synthetic carpets and floor coverings.
   Environment Minister Brice Lalonde said the water mains to Tours
were cut off Thursday afternoon, shortly after traces of phenol
were detected in the city's drinking water.
