<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0500 06-11 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0500,0648</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Factional Fighting Kills Nine</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs to UPDATE with landmine exploding at abandoned
French Embassy compound.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Palestinian guerrilla factions
battled with rockets and mortars Saturday for control of two Beirut
refugee camps. Police said nine people were killed and 35 wounded
in the fourth day of fighting.
   The battle in west Beirut pitted PLO leader Yasser Arafat's
Fatah guerrillas against the breakaway Fatah-Uprising faction of
Col. Saeed Mousa. Fatah is the main guerrilla faction of the
Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Since fighting began Wednesday in the Bourj el-Barajneh and
Chatilla camps, 19 people have died and 95 have been wounded.
   Shell blasts and staccato bursts of gunfire shook Beirut as
guerrillas hammered each other's positions with mortars, recoilless
cannons, rocket-propelled grenades and heavy machine guns, police
said.
   They said Mousa's gunners, stationed in Syrian-controlled hills
in Lebanon's central mountains overlooking Beirut, pounded both
camps with howitzers and mortars.
   About 50 Palestinian women who fled Chatilla and Bourj
el-Barajneh demonstrated Saturday at west Beirut's Mar Elias
refugee camp, which has stayed neutral in the clashes.
   ``What a shame. A Palestinian beats a Palestinian with fire!''
chanted the demonstrators as they reached the office of
Fatah-Uprising.
   Col. Mousa, better known as Abu Mousa, broke away from the PLO
in a Syrian-inspired 1983 mutiny against Arafat's leadership and
established his headquarters in Damascus, the Syrian capital.
   The heavy clashes continued through the day, despite several
cease-fire calls by a security committee made up of representatives
of various Palestinian groups.
   The latest truce reached at noon eased the fighting, but tension
was still high.
   Police said the big guns fell silent, but sporadic exchanges of
gunfire were heard.
   Palestinian officials said 95 percent of Chatilla and Bourj
el-Barajneh's 29,000 residents have fled the camps to live with
relatives or in makeshift homes in basements of unfinished
buildings in Beirut. Others took refuge in shantytowns in south and
north Lebanon.
   A statement signed, ``who is left from Chatilla's residents,''
appealed to the leaders of the PLO and Fatah-Uprising to try to
stop the bloodshed.
   ``We appeal to you in the names of Chatilla's patient and
steadfast children, women and elderly to intervene and work
seriously and quickly to stop this crazy shelling of our camp,''
the statement said.
   ``The shelling has taken the lives of women, elderly and
children and caused grave damage to the camp. It has become almost
impossible to walk through the camp because most of its alleyways
are blocked with rubble,'' added the statement.
   Chatilla bore the brunt of fighting between PLO guerrillas and
Shiite Moslem Amal militiamen in their three-year war for control
of the Palestinian refugee camps.
   Almost every shack in Chatilla is roofless and has gaping holes
or bullet scars from the war between the PLO and Amal, which sought
to prevent the Palestinian guerrillas from rebuilding the Lebanese
power base they lost after the 1982 Israeli invasion.
   The war ended in April 1987 after Syrian troops deployed around
the shantytowns, ending a nearly five-month Amal seizure.
   Arafat's loyalists had flushed out Abu Mousa's guerrillas from
both embattled shantytowns in previous rounds of fighting in the
last two months, despite a reconciliation effort between Arafat and
Syrian President Hafez Assad.
   But the dissidents regrouped on the fringes of the two camps,
where Syrian troops are in control.
   On Saturday, a falling tree branch set off a landmine inside the
old French Embassy compound on Rue Clemenceau in west Beirut,
causing minor damage but no casualties, police said.
   The compound was abandoned after a 1985 spate of kidnappings of
foreigners and is guarded by a few French marines and Lebanese
police. They maintain mines in the embassy gardens to prevent
trespassing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
