<1ST_LINE>r i AM-YugoslavDebts     06-11 0155</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslav Debts,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Creditors Reschedule Yugoslav Debts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifteen Western creditor countries
and Kuwait agreed Saturday to reschedule nearly $1 billion of
Yugoslavia's debts, the state news agency Tanjug reported from
Paris.
   It said the agreement involves $946 million of capital and
interest and was reached after two days of ``lengthy, exhaustive
and delicate negotiations'' with a Yugoslav delegation led by
Finance Secretary Svetozar Rikanovic.
   Tanjug said the accord will be signed soon, rescheduling
Yugoslav debts and interest due between April 1, 1988, and June 30,
1989 _ a period covered by a stand-by arrangement with the
International Monetary Fund.
   Postponement of repayments is for 10 years, with a six-year
grace period, according to the agency.
   The agreement also provides for possible medium-term
rescheduling of debts amounting to nearly $4 billion, depending on
how fast Yugoslavia carries out its economic reforms and on future
agreements with the IMF, the report said.
</TEXT>
