<2ND_LINE>AM-Venezuela-Drugs,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. And Venezuelan Navies Seize 38 Tons Of Pot Aboard Colombian
Boat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Venezuelan authorities seized
a Colombian fishing boat loaded with 38 tons of marijuana in the
Caribbean Sea, police officials reported Saturday.
   The boat, bound out of Barranquilla, Colombia, was seized Friday
near the Paraguana Peninsula, about 70 miles east of Colombia, the
officials said.
   ``The Mara III boat was probably bound for one of the Caribbean
islands, with the U.S. as its final destination,'' Venezuelan
Police Commissioner Francisco Sibila said in a telephone interview.
   Sibila did not give details of the U.S. Navy intervention.
   ``We alerted the Venezuelan coast guard ships patrolling the
area that the boat was approaching our territorial waters. Our
coast guard asked for help from U.S. ships that at the time were
also navigating close to the area the Colombian ship was to pass,''
Sibila said.
   ``They (a U.S. naval ship) actually captured the boat and turned
it over to a Venezuelan P-15 coast guard ship,'' the Sibila said.
   The Colombian craft and its crew of six Colombians were taken to
military facilities of the Monjes islands and then to Punto Fijo
city, where they will probably face trial on Monday, the officer
said.
   No comment was immediately available from the U.S. Embassy in
Caracas.
   Venezuela and the United States maintain a close cooperation
that includes sharing information in the anti-drug fight.
