<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 2205EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AfghanElections     06-11 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan Elections,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Alliance Promises Elections Within Four Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The seven-party Afghan alliance, long
beset by internal feuding between Moslem moderates and
fundamentalists, promised Saturday to hold elections within four
months on a future government for Afghanistan.
   The elections, to be held before Oct. 15, will be held among
guerrillas in Afghanistan and refugees in Pakistan and Iran. They
will choose a council that will vote on setting up an interim
Moslem government to challenge the Soviet-backed Marxist
administration in Kabul, the Afghan capital.
   The election decision should bury a leading cause of dissension
within the fractious Moslem umbrella organization.
   Alliance spokesman Gulbadin Hekmatyar said the decision was
unanimous.
   Ahmad Gailani, head of the moderate National Islamic Front of
Afghanistan and the man who will replace Hekmatyar as of Wednesday,
said the alliance has been divided over the makeup of the interim
government.
   ``We believe it should be referred to the people. ... Some of
our friends ... (in the alliance believe) everything should come
from the top,'' Gailani said.
   The alliance is often divided into two camps _ moderates and
fundamentalists. But on this issue, moderate Gailani and Hekmatyar,
who is considered an extreme fundamentalist, stood together in
demanding elections.
   An election commission set up months ago by the alliance will
decide the details of holding an election in the midst of a war
that goes on unabated despite the start of a Soviet troop
withdrawal. The commission has a July 1 deadline for its report.
   ``Eighty percent of Afghanistan is free. I don't see the problem
of an election,'' said Gailani.
   Aside from polling Islamic guerrillas and Afghans living inside
the war-torn country, an estimated 5 million refugees living in
Pakistan and Iran will be asked to vote. ``One third of our
people,'' are refugees, said Gailani.
   He cautioned against anticipating elections ``according to
Western ways. It's not possible.'' Gailani envisions elections that
combine the Western one-man, one-vote concept with traditional
Afghan jirgas, or councils.
   Gailani insisted that regardless of the methods employed or the
composition of this government, it is only transitional until Kabul
falls and a nationwide election can be held.
   Critics demanding elections argued against seven men making
decisions and claiming to represent the majority of Afghans. The
alliance is often split, 4-3, with fundamentalists in the majority.
   One of the latest alliance decisions taken over objections from
the moderate camp called for a boycott of attempts by U.N.
negotiator Diego Cordovez to help form a broad-based,
representative Afghan government.
   Gailani said mujahedeen leaders should at least talk to
Cordovez, who mediated at the Geneva talks resulting in the Soviet
commitment to withdraw its estimated 115,000 troops from
Afghanistan. A boycott, argued Galiani, only leaves the alliance in
the dark and dependent on second-and third-hand reports.
   Gailani foresaw few difficulties in coordinating elections among
commanders inside Afghanistan. He denied charges that mujahedeen
have begun fighting among themselves for captured weapons and
ammunition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
