<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Punjab,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Killed In Police Raids, Heroin and Weapons Seized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police raids in Punjab state left four
people dead, including at least two suspected Sikh terrorists.
Gunmen killed a Sikh political adviser, news reports said Saturday.
   Police also seized heroin valued at $5.25 million, found a large
cache of weapons and arrested 13 suspected Sikh extremists in raids
over a 24-hour period ending Saturday, the United News of India
news agency said.
   In another report, the agency said Charan Dass Ghai, a lawyer
and adviser to the Sikhs' Akali Dal party, was called from his home
in Moga town by two men who shot him to death.
   UNI and government-run television reported the seizure of the
heroin and listed the value, but gave no further details.
   Various news reports gave these accounts of the four deaths
during the police raids:
   Security forces killed two suspected Sikh terrorists early
Saturday in a gunfight in Shankar village in Jalandhar district. A
third suspect escaped.
   On Friday night, members of the Border Security Force killed
Swaran Singh in a shooting near the Bab Pir border outpost in
Amritsar district when he tried to cross into Pakistan and ignored
orders to halt. The reports said Swaran Singh was a close associate
of a man accused of terrorist attacks.
   A security unit fired on a group of seven people trying to enter
India from Pakistan near the Mangli border post, also in Amritsar
district, killing one. The six others fled and the patrol found a
large cache of arms and ammunition.
   Sikhs comprise only 2 percent of India's population of 800
million but are in a majority in Punjab. Militant Sikhs have been
fighting for a separate homeland in the state since 1982, targeting
for attack security personnel, Hindus and moderate Sikhs.
   In another development, hundreds of residents of the northern
city of Srinagar protesting government plans to raise electricity
rates battled police Saturday with rocks and crude bombs.
   News reports said at least 55 people were injured, including 40
policemen and two rioters shot by police while trying to burn a
bridge.
</TEXT>
