<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Earthquakes,0108</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Moderate Temblors Shake Southwestern Greece</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PIRGOS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two moderate earthquakes two minutes apart
shook this southwestern town Saturday, but there were no immediate
reports of injuries or damage, police said.
   The Athens Seismological Institute said the tremors measured 4.4
and 4.3 on the Richter scale, with the first quake at 1:36 p.m.
(6:36 a.m. EDT).
   Their epicenters were 125 miles west of Athens in the area
around Pirgos.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by ground motion recorded on a seismograph.
A magnitude 4 quake can cause moderate damage.
