<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Shootings-Hispanics     06-11 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shootings-Hispanics,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Community Awaits Grand Jury Action In Fatal Shooting By Police
Officer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM STRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PERTH AMBOY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The police officer whose fatal shooting
of a Hispanic man triggered violent protests earlier this week will
be sued for allegedly beating another Hispanic man in a separate
incident last month, an attorney said Saturday.
   The streets of this town remained calm for the second straight
night Saturday, but several residents said rioting could break out
again if the officer is not indicted after an investigation of the
shooting.
   Rock-throwing rioters broke windows and looted and toppled a car
Wednesday and Thursday nights to protest the shooting of two
Hispanic men by Sgt. Allen C. Fuller.
   Fuller shot and killed Carmen Coria and critically wounded
Coria's brother, Matteo, outside a bar early Monday. Fuller has
said he fired in self-defense after Carmen Coria approached him
holding a bottle. The officer has been suspended with pay pending
the outcome of the investigation.
   Matteo Coria remained in critical condition in Robert Wood
Johnson Memorial Hospital in New Brunswick, a nursing supervisor
who declined to be identified said Saturday.
   Lawsuits expected to be filed in federal and state courts next
week will charge that Fuller and other officers used excessive
force and violated the civil rights of Edwin Ramos during a drug
bust May 19, said Jack Dudas, attorney for Ramos.
   Fuller and several other officers beat Ramos, who required
hospitalization for a cracked skull and possible brain damage,
Dudas said. Police allege Ramos was hospitalized for swallowing a
quantity of cocaine, the lawyer said.
   Ramos was admitted May 28 to the county jail and held in lieu of
$15,000 bail on charges of drug possession, resisting arrest and
aggravated assault, said Officer Mark Rodziewicz of the county
sheriff's department.
   Dudas said other defendants in the lawsuits would be the city of
Perth Amboy, which runs the police department; Middlesex County,
which trains the officers; and Mayor George J. Otlowksi, who is the
police director.
   Otlowski said he knew about the Ramos case but declined comment.
   He again praised Fuller, calling him a ``man on a crusade'' who
had probably the highest number of arrests on the narcotics squad.
   Middlesex County Prosecutor Alan Rockoff said he had no
knowledge of the Ramos incident.
   Police Chief Edward Mullen did not return calls to his home
Saturday.
   Rockoff met with Hispanic community leaders Friday and agreed to
investigate the shooting of the Coria brothers and present the case
to a grand jury to halt the street violence.
   Residents said Saturday that the 109-member police force was
tainted by a few bad officers and many singled out Fuller, who they
said frequently harassed Hispanics.
   If there is no indictment, ``a real riot could break out,'' said
Frank Morales, 29. ``We don't want that to happen. We want a good
community.''
   ``He thought he was `super cop,''' said Joseph E. Gregory, 37.
``He was an accident waiting to happen.''
   ``The problem is with him, not the police department,'' said
Hector Julio, 28. ``He thinks he's something like Dirty Harry.''
   City and county officials also agreed Friday to form a
commission to investigate bias in the city and to establish a
community council to hear grievances against police.
</TEXT>
