<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0542 06-11 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0542,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Hailed At State Convention; Gets Glowing Tribute From
Kennedy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3 grafs for penultimate graf pvs, bgng: ``Dukakis
refused ...'' to UPDATE with later appearance.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis thanked cheering home-state
supporters Saturday for their support and received a glowing
tribute from Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, who said Vice President George
Bush was a ``dead duck'' in his race for the presidency.
   ``You have made me what I am, and I am eternally grateful,''
Dukakis told delegates to the Massachusetts Democratic Convention.
``Nobody has been blessed more than I.''
   Dukakis, whose official job at the convention was to introduce
Kennedy to accept the party's endorsement in his re-election bid,
opened his remarks by thanking the delegates and state officials
``for making it possible for me and for us to do what we have done
the past 15 months.''
   ``This commonwealth of ours and its people have set an example
that I'm proud of and you're proud of and that I hope will set an
example for the nation beginning in January of 1989,'' the
Massachusetts governor said.
   ``We have not only built an economic future for our people that
we can be proud of, but we have done it with sensitivity and
compassion. And that in the last analysis is the measure of us, and
of our state and of our nation.''
   For a day, the often-contentious Massachusetts Democrats engaged
in a love-fest, paying tribute to Dukakis and Kennedy, who is
seeking his fifth full term in the Senate and whose endorsement was
the only major official convention business.
   Dukakis, who noted that he was first elected to the state
Legislature the same year Kennedy began his Senate career _ 1962 _
called the senator ``our leader for many, many years'' and praised
Kennedy for his positions on issues ranging from civil rights to
national health insurance.
   He then thanked Kennedy for bringing ``his special gifts to
people'' on Dukakis' behalf during the presidential campaign.
   Kennedy, who failed in a 1980 bid to wrest the Democratic
presidential nomination away from President Carter, announced in
1986 that he would not seek the presidency in 1988, clearing the
way for Dukakis' entry into the race.
   ``President Dukakis, it has a nice ring, doesn't it?'' Kennedy
said at the opening of a speech filled with praise of Dukakis and
criticisms of President Reagan and Bush, the vice president and
certain GOP nominee.
   ``Some people say don't count your chickens before they're
hatched,'' Kennedy said. ``Well, I say the Republicans have already
hatched their chicken in this campaign _ and George Bush is a dead
duck.''
   ``Mike Dukakis is the man who did it for Massachusetts and Mike
Dukakis is the man who can do it for the United States of
America,'' Kennedy said. ``No one will campaign longer or harder
for him than Ted Kennedy.''
   The convention was held at the Boston Garden. The last major
political event there was a rally hosted by then-Sen. John F.
Kennedy on the eve of his election to the presidency in 1960.
   Dukakis was in an unusually festive mood later Saturday as he
addressed the Boston Press Photographers Association at a banquet.
   He told the gathering that before coming to the dinner he ``went
over to a Harvard boutique to pick up my speech for tomorrow.''
Bush, who went to Yale, has tried to characterize Dukakis as
elitist because of his Harvard ties.
   The photographers presented Dukakis with their annual good
fellowship award and a mock presidential seal featuring a cod in
place of the eagle on the actual seal. Dukakis, who frequently
rides the subway to work, also was given two fare tickets for the
subway in Washington.
   On Sunday, Dukakis was headed to Salt Lake City to address the
nation's mayors before returning to Boston for several days at the
Statehouse. On Monday he is to meet with congressional leaders in
Boston to discuss drug education and interdiction programs and is
scheduled to travel to Washington Tuesday morning to deliver a
speech on U.S.-Soviet relations.
</TEXT>
