<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Demonstration,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Abortion Demonstrators Arrested For Blocking Clinic</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Juli is CQ in 4th graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DOBBS FERRY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 150 anti-abortion
demonstrators were arrested on disorderly conduct charges Saturday
for blocking the entrance to a women's health center, police said.
   More than 200 people blocked the doors of the Women's Medical
Pavilion around 7:30 a.m., said Sgt. Frank Palsy of the Dobbs Ferry
Police Department.
   More than 150 were arrested and taken by bus to police
headquarters and other municipal buildings, police said.
   They were released within a few hours on their promise to appear
and face trespassing charges. But Juli Loesch, a spokeswoman for
Operation Rescue, the Manhattan-based group that staged the
demonstration, complained that police kept the demonstrators from
leaving to keep them from resuming their protest.
   ``We believe they are being held in preventive detention in
violation of the Constitution,'' Loesch said.
   It was unclear whether the medical office opened Saturday. In
the morning a woman who answered the phone there hung up on a
reporter without answering any questions. In the afternoon, an
answering service took calls.
   ``This is a rescue,'' Loesch said. ``We wanted to stop the
abortions that were to occur today and to offer alternative
solutions to abortion, including counseling and information on
medical care.''
   Speaking from New York, Loesch said police arrested the Rev.
Jesse Lee, pastor of the Neighborhood Church in Greenwich Village;
Thomas Herliahy, an anti-abortion activist, and Bishop Austin
Vaughan, an auxiliary bishop of the archdiocese of New York.
   During the first week in May, Operation Rescue staged
anti-abortion rallies where more than 1,600 people were arrested.
</TEXT>
