<DOCNO> AP880611-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 2223EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Brawley     06-11 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brawley,0615</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reporters Walk Out Of Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY35, NY36</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper and its reporters were singled out
for blame Saturday at a rally for supporters of a black teen-ager
who claims she was abducted and raped by white men, and reporters
responded by walking out.
   The rally organizers then banned The Associated Press and
several other news organizations from a Sunday morning church
service to be attended by the teen.
   The incident began during a tirade by lawyer C. Vernon Mason
about a Newsday story earlier this year that said the Rev. Al
Sharpton was a federal informant who wore hidden microphones to
meetings with civil rights leaders and organized crime figures.
   Mason, Sharpton and lawyer Alton Maddox have made a racial issue
of the case of Tawana Brawley, 16, of Wappingers Falls, who claims
she was abducted and sexually assaulted by six white men over a
four-day period last November.
   After initially cooperating with authorities, she and her family
have refused to participate further, charging a cover-up. Glenda
Brawley, the mother of Tawana Brawley, was sentenced to 30 days in
jail Monday for failing to appear before a grand jury looking into
the case.
   The lawyers and Sharpton say Mrs. Brawley took ``sanctuary'' at
Bethany Baptist Church in the predominantly black
Bedford-Stuyvesant section of Brooklyn, where about 200 people
attended the rally. Mrs. Brawley was present but did not speak.
   At one point, Mason shouted, ``Tell them, (Gov.) Mario Cuomo,
how you tried to set Al Sharpton up for physical assassination.''
Mason then asked all Newsday employees to stand, and two black
reporters did.
   Security guards, reading from a list of reporters in attendance,
told the other Newsday employees to stand. All except Juliette
Fairley, 21, stood.
   One of the guards put his hand on Ms. Fairley and asked her to
stand, but she resisted.
   ``I'm standing up. She doesn't have to,'' reporter Clem
Richardson told the guards. Richardson and Ms. Fairley are black.
   About 18 reporters from other news organizations stood in
unison. When a guard said, ``Security wants Newsday reporters to
leave,'' their colleagues walked out, too, in a show of support.
   ``I left out of solidarity for reporters, black and white, who
have been covering this story honestly, aggressively and faithfully
for more than six months,'' said Lyle Harris, a Daily News reporter
who is black.
   The Rev. Porter Denson, one of the rally organizers, later said
the guard had been misunderstood and that no one had been asked to
leave. Michael Cottman, a Newsday reporter, said he had been asked
to leave.
   Afterward, Richardson and Billy House, a reporter for the
Poughkeepsie Journal and the Gannett News Service, met with
Sharpton, Maddox and Mason.
   The advisers said that because of the walkout, which Sharpton
termed ``unprofessional,'' several news organizations would be
banned from a Sunday morning church service. They were The
Associated Press, United Press International, the Poughkeepsie
Journal, Gannett News Service, The New York Times, the Daily News,
USA Today and Newsday.
   Hours after the rally, a representative of Mason called the AP
and UPI to say that Tawana Brawley would attend the service and
asked that the service be listed on the daily schedule of events
provided by the news services.
   Timothy Gilles, a spokesman for Attorney General Robert Abrams,
who was appointed by Cuomo as special prosecutor in the case, said
city police were not arresting Mrs. Brawley because ``we have no
intention of swooping in to participate in the media circus that
the Rev. Sharpton and attorneys Maddox and Mason are intending to
orchestrate.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
