<DOCNO> AP880611-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 2330EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-VirginiaCandidate     06-11 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Virginia Candidate,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dawkins Takes GOP Senate Nomination</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphotos RN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROANOKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maurice Dawkins, a black businessman and
former Democrat, won the Republican nomination Saturday to run for
the U.S. Senate seat against former Democratic Gov. Charles S. Robb.
   Dawkins, 67, is the first black to run for the Senate from
Virginia since Reconstruction.
   He won a first ballot nomination over two rivals after promising
to ``put an end to the era of Chuck Robb'' in a fiery address at
the state GOP convention.
   ``They said it couldn't be done, but we did it,'' Dawkins said
after his nomination. ``They say Chuck Robb can't be beaten, but
we're going to beat him.''
   Dawkins and Robb will square off for the seat currently held by
Rep. Paul. S. Trible Jr., who is not seeking re-election.
   Dawkins, a lobbyist and retired minister who lives in the
northern Virginia suburbs of Washington, D.C., defeated Andrew
Wahlquist, a former Senate aide, and Gil Faulk, a McLean attorney,
for the nomination.
   His speech combined a thundering attack on Robb with frequent
references to God, faith and family. He ended by leading the
delegates in singing ``God Bless America,'' brining the crowd to
its feet and swinging many uncommitted delegates into his camp.
   Dawkins switched to the GOP after George McGovern won the
Democratic presidential nomination in 1972.
   He unsuccessfully sought the GOP nomination for lieutenant
governor in 1985.
   Robb is considered a huge favorite to win the seat. He won the
governorship by a fairly narrow margin in 1981 but left office
highly popular four years later. Virginia does not allow governors
to serve consecutive terms.
   Robb, a lawyer and former Marine who served in Vietnam, is
married to Lynda Bird Johnson, daughter of former President Lyndon
Baines Johnson.
   A number of Republican leaders said privately that nominating a
black candidate could cost the party some traditional support among
conservative white voters.
   Political analysts said Dawkins' nomination was a calculated
gamble to take away traditional Democratic support from minority
voters.
   ``They're stealing thunder from 1989,'' said Larry Sabato, a
University of Virginia political science professor. The Democratic
Party is widely expected to nominate current Lt. Gov. L. Douglas
Wilder to run for governor next year. Wilder is the highest elected
black official of any state.
   Although Dawkins is considered the underdog, he entered the
nomination contest late and has not been cast against Robb in any
polls.
   Also Saturday, convention delegates rejected a bid by a
supporter of Pat Robertson for a seat on the Republican National
Committee.
   Incumbent Flo Traywick defeated Anne B. Kincaid, who coordinated
Robertson's presidential nomination campaign in the state.
   Asked whether her defeat represented a rejection of Robertson's
followers by GOP regulars, Ms. Kincaid said, ``You're not going to
hear that from me.''
   But Mark Rozell, a political analyst at Mary Washington College,
said the vote showed ``that the Robertson people don't have as much
influence here as many people said they would.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
