<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DisarmamentRally     06-11 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Disarmament Rally,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>About 60,000 People Participate In Disarmament Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY25</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 60,000 people participated Saturday in a
march for nuclear disarmament and rally in Central Park that
brought together 200 peace, labor, religious and human rights
organizations.
   The event was the city's largest political demonstration since
1982, police said.
   The activities capped a week of activities in support of the
Third United Nations Special Session on Disarmament. The coalition
organizing the event is seeking to increase interest in abolishing
nuclear weapons by the year 2000.
   ``This is a New York event to say, `We still believe,' '' said
Peter Yarrow of the folk singing group Peter, Paul and Mary.
   Along the roads winding through Central Park were booths set up
by organizations that distributed literature, sold buttons,
T-shirts and records.
   The day's events began with a torch lighting ceremony at the
United Nations. The torch came from the Eternal Flame at the
Hiroshima Memorial in Japan.
   Those who arrived early then marched to Central Park for the
international program of cultural presentations and speeches, which
featured among others Coretta Scott King, folks singers Ronnie
Gilbert, Pete Seeger and Yarrow and Midnight Oil, an Australian
rock group.
   Leslie Cagan, national coordinator for the sponsoring coalition,
said the demonstrations can have a ``momentous effect on the
national political agenda.''
   The coalition is calling for the abolition of nuclear weapons,
self-determination for all nations, an end to military intervention
and a shift from military buildups to global economic development.
   Police officials said the crowd was the largest at a
demonstration in the city since 250,000 people attended the United
Nations' Second Special Session on Disarmament in 1982.
</TEXT>
