<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 2340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HollowPoints     06-11 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hollow Points,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LAPD Wins Trial Use of Hollow-Point Bullets; Critics Vow Court
Fight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police here have won permission to use
hollow-point bullets on a trial basis, outraging critics who say
the bullets inflict far more serious wounds than conventional
ammunition.
   ``We're very disturbed,'' said Joel Maliniak, a spokesman for
the American Civil Liberties Union of Southern California. ``These
bullets are designed to cause as much bodily harm as possible. They
cause greater ripping, tearing and death.''
   Hollow-point bullets mushroom to the size of a dime upon impact
and have the force of a punch to knock a person down, said police
spokesman Cmdr. William Booth. They are far more likely to stop a
suspect than round-nose bullets that can pass through someone's
body, he said.
   Police Commissioner Bert Boeckmann said statistics show that
hollow-points cause no more damage than round-nosed bullets and are
less likely to pass through someone's body and ricochet.
   ``We're getting so many instances of bullets going through
people and striking another person,'' Boeckmann said. ``We're all
convinced this is an improvement. I see it as something that's
safer, by far.''
   The Police Commission approved use of the bullets for a one-year
trial period on May 31, said commission President Robert Talcott.
   Public protests blocked an attempt by police Chief Daryl Gates
in 1980 to adopt hollow-points, which are used by the Los Angeles
County Sheriff's Department and other law enforcement agencies
nationwide.
   Critics said they were not notified the issue would be on the
commission's agenda May 31 and said they only learned of the
decision Friday from a Los Angeles Herald Examiner reporter.
   ``We would have lobbied against it,'' said Michael Zinzun,
chairman of the Coalition Against Police Abuse. ``We'll see if we
can take legal action for a moratorium and stop it.''
   The city is not expected to have the new ammunition available
until September, but an interdepartment bulletin advises officers
they may purchase the bullets at their own expense at local gun
stores.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
