<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spain-Greenpeace     06-11 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Greenpeace,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greenpeace Ship Sirius Immobilized By Spain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IBIZA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spanish naval authorities immobilized the
Greenpeace ship Sirius at Ibiza when it tried to interfere with the
entry of a U.S. aircraft carrier at nearby Majorca island, port
officials said Saturday.
   They said the steering gear of the 152-foot Sirius was sealed
off by Spanish officials soon after the craft arrived at this
Mediterranean Balearic island port on Friday.
   Navy authorities told the captain, Ed Engels, that the Sirius
was to stay in Ibiza until further orders and could not set sail or
use its rubber rafts, according to the port officials who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Crewmembers of the USS Dwight David Eisenhower carrier turned
water hoses on anti-nuclear protesters in four rubber dinghies
launched from the Sirius who tried to stop the warship from
entering Palma port on Thursday.
   Xavier Pastor, a Greenpeace official, said in a communique
Thursday the environmental organization was protesting the Spanish
government's allowing nuclear weapons into its territorial waters
in violation of a March 1986 referendum.
   Green peace claims the carrier is equipped with nuclear
armaments.
   It is U.S. policy not to confirm or deny whether a U.S. ship has
nuclear weapons.
   Spaniards voted in 1986 to retain membership in the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization with the conditions that Spain be free
of nuclear weapons, the U.S. military presence be reduced and
Spain's armed forces remain outside the integrated NATO military
command.
   Pastor said a Spanish navy official and two sailors were on duty
aboard the Sirius and national police kept watch on the ship from
port.
   ``Nobody informed us on the cause of stopping the ship,'' he
said.
   A U.S. official, who spoke on condition he not be identified,
confirmed that Greenpeace had ``attempted to interfere with the
docking'' of the carrier but said it anchored successfully without
damage or injury to either side.
</TEXT>
