<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 2328EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Doctors-Medicare     06-11 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Doctors-Medicare,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors Treating Medicare Patients May Be Rated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 300,000 physicians who treat Medicare
patients may be rated in a federal government study on the quality
of their patient care, according to a published report.
   The New York Times reported in its Sunday editions that the
proposed federal budget that takes effect Oct. 1 includes funds for
preliminary work on the study.
   The study, which would take several years to complete, would
rate doctors by name and the results would eventually be made
public, the Times said.
   ``We plan to measure the performance of individual physicians by
seeing how well their patients do,'' said Dr. William L. Roper,
administrator of the Health Care Financing Administration in the
Department of Health and Human Services.
   ``There are differences in the quality of care given by
physicians and hospitals,'' Roper said. ``We can measure those
differences, and that information should be conveyed to the
public.''
   Factors that could be used in rating doctors include such things
as mortality rates, speed of recovery and complexity and severity
of illnesses, he said.
   The study would be similar to one done by the federal government
on mortality rates of nearly 6,000 hospitals and a forthcoming
study on the quality of care in 15,000 nursing homes, the newspaper
said.
</TEXT>
