<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 2346EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0605 06-11 1187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0605,1230</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with Belasco, Allen obits; AMs separate on Saragat
moved as a0594.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Giuseppe Saragat</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Giuseppe Saragat, Italy's first socialist president,
died at home Saturday from a heart ailment. He was 89.
   A founder of the Social Democratic Party and a staunch
anti-communist, he joined the Socialist Party in 1922. He went into
exile in Austria and then France when dictator Benito Mussolini
rose to power in 1926.
   Years later, in 1947, he broke with the Socialist Party and
formed the Social Democratic Party as a pro-Western, anti-communist
force.
   During his seven years as the fifth president of the Republic,
beginning in 1964, Saragat worked for reforms in housing, medical
care, education and taxation.
   Saragat was born Sept. 19, 1898, in Turin and obtained a
university degree in economics and commerce. He worked as a bank
clerk and for a newspaper and wrote political books under the pen
name ``Togaraso.''
   He was elected to Parliament four times and served three times
as deputy premier. Saragat supported the Socialist-Christian
Democrat alliance that governed Italy during six of his seven years
as president.
   Saragat engineered the merger of his party with the bigger
Socialist Party in 1966, but when the unified party took a beating
in the 1968 elections the two again separated.
   Saragat is survived by his son and daughter.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Leon Belasco</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORANGE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leon Belasco, a Russian immigrant who
parlayed his comedic talents and ability to do a range of foreign
accents into a career as a charactor actor spanning four decades,
died June 1 at age 85.
   Belasco, born in Odessa, Russia, in 1902, appeared in scores of
movies, including ``Topper Takes a Trip,'' in 1939 and ``The
Russians Are Coming, The Russians are Coming,'' in 1966.
   He generally played excitable characters, frequently appearing
as a head waiter, landlord or ballet master.
   Born Leonid Simeonovich Berladsky, Belasco began his career as a
violinist and orcehstra leader, working with the Andrews Sisters in
1936. His movie career took off in 1939 when he won small roles in
several films.
   Among the better known movies he appeared in over the years were
``Broadway Serenade in 1939, ``Holiday Inn,'' with Bing Crosby and
Fred Astaire, in 1942, and ``Casablanca,'' with Humphrey Bogart and
Ingrid Bergman, also in 1942.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Byron Allen</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT LAKES, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Byron G. Allen, former assistant to
U.S. Commissioner of Agriculture Orville Freeman and a key figure
in the merger of the Democratic and Farmer-Labor parties, died
Friday at the age of 86.
   Allen, the DFL's first candidate for governor in 1944, was the
Minnesota national Democratic committeeman from 1948 to 1955.
   A native of Iowa, Allen was elected to the Iowa Legislature at
age 25 and served there until 1932. In 1933 he became secretary of
the Iowa Senate. He was director of the Iowa Old Age Assistance
System, a predecessor to the Social Security system, from 1934 to
1939.
   He and his family moved in 1940 to Detroit Lakes, where he
continued a farm management and insurance business founded by his
grandfather.
   Allen was a member of the fusion committee that met in June 1944
to found Minnesota's Democratic-Farmer-Labor party. Hubert H.
Humphrey was the chief spokesman for the fusion Democrats.
   A few months later, Humphrey managed Allen's campaign as the
DFL's first candidate for governor. Allen lost to Republican Edward
J. Thye.
   Allen gave one of the 17 speeches nominating Franklin D.
Roosevelt for president in 1944.
   In 1955, Allen was appointed Minnesota Commissioner of
Agriculture and left the post to become assistant U.S. secretary of
Agriculture in 1961.
   He returned to Detroit Lakes in 1969 and continued the family
business until retiring about three years ago.
   Survivors include a son, a daughter, a sister and five
grandchildren.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Helen Musgrove</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTMINSTER, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Helen ``Patches'' Musgrove, a Vietnam
War correspondent and registered nurse who operated a shelter for
Chinese refugees, died Tuesday of pneumonia after a stroke. She was
69.
   Mrs. Musgrove worked as a war correspondent in the late 1960s
and early 1970s after persuading a Florida newspaper to hire her
even though she had no newspaper reporting experience.
   Her career in Asia began after the death of her husband, when
she traveled to Hong Kong, opened a dress manufacturing plant and
sold designer clothes to U.S. customers. She also opened a shelter
for Chinese refugees in Hong Kong.
   Mrs. Musgrove went to Vietnam in 1966 and became a correspondent
after receiving the sponsorship of the Jacksonville (Fla.) Journal.
For 6{ years she covered the war, entertained U.S. servicemen and
helped with medical needs.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Josep Tarradellas</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Josep Tarradellas, one of the few
remaining figures of Spain's 1936-39 Second Republic and former
head of the autonomous Catalonian government, died Friday from a
chronic lung ailment. He was 89.
   When he fled Spain in 1939, Tarradellas vowed never to set foot
in the country until Catalonian autonomy had been restored.
   Tarradellas was the last major Republican exile to return to
Spain after the death of dictator Gen. Francisco Franco in November
1975. He came back in 1977.
   Under Spain's 1978 constitution that restored democracy,
Catalonia recovered its autonomous status lost when Franco's forces
emerged victorious in the 1936-39 Spanish Civil War.
   King Juan Carlos named Tarradellas head of the Catalonian
autonomous government of Generalitat in 1979. He retired from
politics in 1980.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Herman Crook</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Herman Crook, a harmonica player who was
the oldest member of the Grand Ole Opry, died Friday of respiratory
failure after suffering a heart attack. He was 89.
   Crook was the last remaining charter member of the Grand Ole
Opry, founded in 1925. He returned to the Opry last weekend after a
nine-week absence due to health problems.
   In 1926, Crook led a country music string band on the Saturday
Night Barn Dance and went on the Opry in 1927. The band is the only
act left that represents the original tradition of the Opry. The
band plays for cloggers, who perform traditional mountain dancing.
   Crook was among the Opry musicians who participated in
Nashville's first recording sessions in 1928. By the 1960s, the
Opry had become a modern, highly professional program, and the
traditional sound of Crook's group, the Crook Brothers Band, became
a less prominent part of the show.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>James H. Anderson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James H. ``Andy'' Anderson, a former chief
of bureau for The Associated Press, died Thursday. He was 84.
   Anderson, a native of Independence, Kan., joined the AP in
Kansas City in 1927. He transferred to St. Louis in 1935, and later
became chief of bureau in Oklahoma City from 1944-46.
   Anderson continued to work in Oklahoma City until his retirement
in 1968.
   Stanley M. Swinton, assistant general manager of the AP at the
time of Anderson's retirement, said in 1968 of Anderson's work in
Oklahoma City that ``much of the bureau's success in that period
had been the result'' of his efforts.
   Memorial services for Anderson are scheduled for Saturday at
First Presbyterian Church in Oklahoma City.
</TEXT>
