<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Nixon-Impeach     06-11 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nixon-Impeach,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Mulls Impeachment Decision on Judge Nixon</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House investigators are pondering whether to
recommend impeaching U.S. District Judge Walter L. Nixon Jr. of
Mississippi, who is serving a five-year prison sentence for lying
to a federal grand jury but is still drawing his $89,500 salary.
   Nixon refused to testify during two days of impeachment hearings
which ended Friday, but his lawyers claimed he was the innocent
victim of ``big prize fever'' among overzealous prosecutors eager
to put a federal judge behind bars.
   Defense attorney David Stewart told the House Judiciary
subcommittee on civil and constitutional rights that Nixon ``has
committed no crime and has engaged in no impeachable offense.''
   But former federal prosecutor Reid Weingarten said Nixon was
``aggressively lying'' to a grand jury when he denied he discussed
a drug smuggling case involving the son of a wealthy Mississippi
investor with whom he had business dealings.
   Weingarten said Nixon had a ``sweetheart deal'' with the
investor, Wiley Fairchild, who had sold the judge three profitable
oil well properties for bargain prices in 1980. Nixon paid $9,500
for oil and gas rights and reportedly netted $55,000 from the deal.
   Nixon has testified that the transaction was legitimate and that
he made no promises of return favors for Fairchild.
   Although he was accused of discussing the drug charges against
Drew Fairchild with the elder Fairchild and a former Mississippi
prosecutor, Nixon insists that he never talked to anyone about the
case.
   He also says the questions posed during his grand jury
appearance were ambiguous.
   Nixon, 59, a federal judge since 1968 and chief judge of the
southern district of Mississippi for the past six years, is serving
a five-year prison sentence at Eglin Air Force Base, Fla.
   The Supreme Court denied Nixon's appeal of his perjury
conviction last January. He can continue to hold office and draw
his salary, however, unless he resigns or is convicted at a Senate
impeachment trial.
   Before Nixon entered prison in March, the Judicial Conference of
the United States, the chief policymaking body of the federal
judiciary, reported unanimously to House leaders that
``consideration of impeachment may be warranted'' in Nixon's case.
   Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., chairman of the Judiciary
subcommittee that conducted impeachment hearings, said his panel
would leave the record open for further comments in Nixon's case
until June 14.
   Shortly after that date, Edwards said, the panel will decide
whether to recommend impeachment by the full House.
   A separate Judiciary subcommittee headed by Rep. John Conyers
Jr., D-Mich., ended three weeks of impeachment hearings Thursday on
federal judge Alcee L. Hastings of Miami, who was acquitted of
bribery conspiracy in 1983.
   Hastings' fellow judges charged that he actually committed the
crime and tried to conceal his involvement by lying under oath and
fabricating evidence at his trial.
   Neither Hastings nor Nixon testified at their impeachment
proceedings.
   The only other federal judge to be indicted while in office was
Harry E. Claiborne of Nevada, who was imprisoned for tax evasion.
The Senate convicted Claiborne of ``high crimes and misdemeanors''
in October 1986 and removed him from the federal bench.
</TEXT>
