<HEAD>Customs Seizes 428 Pounds Of Gold From British Gurkhas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Customs authorities have discovered more
than 400 pounds of gold in luggage belonging to Gurkha soldiers of
the British armed forces, officials said.
   Customs officials said Friday's haul was the biggest ever of the
precious metal in the Himalayan kingdom.
   A chartered cargo flight of Royal Nepal Airlines brought 168
boxes of goods belonging to the Gurkhas who are serving in the
British army and based in Hong Kong. Officials found 428 pounds of
gold in the boxes.
   About 1,000 pieces of gold were found in boxes belonging to one
soldier, Rajendra Gurung, officials said.
   Gurkhas are a member of the Rajput people and hail from the
mountains of Nepal. They are known for their fighting prowess.
