<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DivorceIdentity     06-11 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Divorce Identity,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Says Couples Must Stop Hiding Identities In Divorce Filings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge says he will refuse to
accept divorce papers filed only under the initials of couples, but
a colleague says the judge should respect their wish for privacy.
   ``If people are too ashamed to let the world know that they are
getting divorced, they should stay married,'' Judge Margarito Garza
wrote in a memo to 148th District Court Clerk Oscar Soliz.
   Divorce petitions are public record and appear regularly in many
newspapers. Initials in some cases are used to obscure the
identities of couples.
   Garza asked Soliz to call the new policy to the attention of
anyone who is filing a divorce suit.
   Judge Joaquin Villarreal of the 347th District Court said he
disagrees with Garza's stance.
   A divorce ``is a personal matter between husband and wife,''
Villarreal said. ``If the two parties don't want the public to know
they are getting divorced, it's fine with me.''
   Soliz said he cannot refuse to accept such a case if the
petition is in order, and that cases are assigned randomly by
computer.
   In initials-only cases assigned to Garza's court, Soliz said he
will ask attorneys to modify the papers to fit with the judge's
specifications.
</TEXT>
