<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Terrorism     06-11 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Terrorism,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Tightening Border Control To Combat Terrorism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan is tightening control over its ports of entry
and exit to prevent terrorists from passing through, Foreign
Minister Sosuke Uno said.
   Several suspected Japanese terrorists have been arrested in
Japan and abroad in recent weeks, and an attack in Naples, Italy in
April is believed to have been carried out by Japanese radicals.
   Uno on Friday told the Japan National Press Club that Western
nations participating in this month's summit in Toronto would
discuss coordinating security efforts to ensure an incident-free
Summmer Olympics in Seoul, South Korea.
   ``We must make the Seoul Olympics succeed,'' Uno said. ``It will
be a topic of discussion at the summit.'' The Games are scheduled
to open in the South Korean capital in September.
   Members of the radical Japanese Red Army, which carried out
numerous terrorist acts in the 1970s, have been arrested in recent
months. The latest suspect was arrested this week in Manila and was
extradited to Japan. Because some traveled or planned to travel to
South Korea, authorities suspect they may have been planning to
disrupt the Olympics.
   Uno said Japan was intensifying control over its border points
to prevent terrorists from entering or leaving.
   The foreign minister also said Japan would host a symposium on
international crime including terrorism, narcotics and organized
crime later this month.
</TEXT>
