<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Carlucci-SouthKorea     06-11 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carlucci-South Korea,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Secretary Says South Korean Riots Don't Threaten American
Forces</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Secretary of Defense Frank Carlucci said
Friday anti-American riots in Seoul are an ``internal'' South
Korean problem and do not threaten U.S. forces there.
   ``I got no sense whatsover that our forces were in any jeopardy
in South Korea. On the contrary, I received nothing but warm
hospitality everywhere I went,'' Carlucci said at a news conference
a day after arriving here from visits to Japan and South Korea
following the Moscow summit.
   ``One would have thought that if there were any risk to our
soldiers, there would be some demonstrations against me, and there
were none,'' he said. ``I think what we're seeing is limited in
scope. It's an internal Korean matter and not appropriate for me to
comment on.''
   In Seoul on Friday, riot police firing tear gas blocked
thousands of radical students from marching to communist North
Korea for reunification talks. The radicals claim the United
States, with its 42,000 troops in South Korea, enforces partition
to rule the South. Protests throughout Seoul were bitterly
anti-American.
   Carlucci was in South Korea for annual U.S.-South Korean
security consultations at which security for the 1988 Summer
Olympics also was discussed.
   Of his talks with his Soviet counterpart at the Moscow summit,
Carlucci said he hoped real gains had been made between the
superpowers, but the United States should not let its guard down in
the face of friendly gestures from the Soviet Union.
   ``We have yet to see perestroika (restructuring) impact the
Soviet military establishment,'' Carlucci said.
   ``It would be certainly premature and the height of folly now
for us to throw up our hands and say all is well while the Soviet
military machine continues to roll on.''
</TEXT>
