<DATELINE>COSTA MESA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jazz composer Herbie Hancock says he's
happy to share the limelight of his current concert tour with
musical ally Chick Corea.
   ``I guess this is the first time my band has toured with another
name act, but it's Chick, so it's like family,'' said Hancock, who
is in the middle of a monthlong, 23-city tour, currently at the
Pacific Amphitheatre in Orange County.
   ``One night we'll be his opening act and the next night he'll be
ours,'' Hancock said. ``He's a friend, so there's no competition.''
   Hancock said he's only scratched the surface of his new career
direction _ film scoring _ although he already won an Academy Award
for the score of one of the eight films for which he wrote the
music, the 1986 ``Round Midnight.''
   His latest film score was for the street gang movie ``Colors,''
starring Sean Penn and Robert Duvall, which some feared might
ignite real-life violence.
   ``I don't understand that controversy,'' Hancock said. ``The
movie didn't even show a viewpoint. But the controversy sure helped
at the box office.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cellist Fred Sherry will become artistic
director of the Chamber Music Society of Lincoln Center next June,
society president Henry S. Ziegler announced.
   Sherry, 40, music administrator of the society since 1981, will
take over at the end of the society's 20th anniversary season,
Ziegler said Friday.
   He replaces Charles Wadsworth, 59, the society's artistic
director since it was established in 1969. Wadsworth is resigning.
   Sherry said he intends ``to present a wide range of serious
music, appealing to all music lovers and devotees of all musical
styles, and to maintain the Chamber Music Society as the standard
by which chamber music performances today are judged.''
   Trained at the Juilliard School, Sherry has been identified with
20th century music through his career. He has toured America,
Europe and Japan with jazz pianist Chick Corea.
