<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mother Clara Hale, known for her work with
drug-addicted babies, will start a new residence for pregnant drug
addicts as part of a program aimed at strengthening family ties,
her daughter says.
   The Hale House Respite, expected to open Oct. 1 in a newly
purchased building, will give eight to 10 pregnant women ``a safe,
quiet, clean, pleasantly decorated home environment. ... Something
many of them have never known,'' said Lorraine E. Hale, president
of Hale House Center Inc. and daughter of the founder.
   ``The streets are their alternative to the Respite,'' she said
at a news conference Friday as her mother stood next to her.
   Participants must attend a daily drug rehabilitation program,
submit to urine tests for drugs and keep appointments at a prenatal
clinic. Mothers with AIDS will be permitted in the program.
