<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 0212EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     06-11 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Scoffs at Bush Criticism; Says Veep Questions Premature</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis says Republican George
Bush has adopted a ``losing strategy'' for the fall campaign and
the vice president's rival says he will focus on the issues despite
Bush's personal attacks.
   Dukakis, his party's certain presidential nominee, also said
Friday that it was ``much too early'' to ask him about potential
running mates.
   And, taking a position likely to feed Bush's criticism of
Dukakis' foreign policy views, Dukakis said he would move the U.S.
Embassy in Israel from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem if he was elected and
Israel continued to recognize Jerusalem as its capital.
   Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor, today was to address a
friendly audience at the state Democratic Party convention, being
held to formally bestow an endorsement on the re-election bid of
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.
   On Friday, after having a quick lunch with former President
Jimmy Carter, Dukakis responded to Bush's statements a day earlier
that Dukakis was an elitist whose views were far from the political
mainstream.
   At first, he offered a blunt ``I don't'' when asked how he
planned to respond to Bush's attacks. He then went on to say: ``I'm
going to campaign on the issues. ... I'm going to talk about the
future.''
   Later, Dukakis, who attended Harvard Law School and has many
advisers with Harvard ties, laughed when asked if he would point
out Bush's own Ivy League background. The vice president attended
Yale.
   ``I really am not interested,'' Dukakis said. ``I don't think
the American people are interested. I think that's a losing
strategy.''
   Democratic rival Jesse Jackson has been pressing Dukakis to
offer him the No. 2 spot on the ticket. Dukakis, asked if Jackson
met his criteria for the spot, said it was ``much too early'' to
respond.
   ``The process has just begun,'' Dukakis said. ``This will take
several weeks.'' Dukakis campaign chairman Paul Brountas, a law
school classmate of the governor, is heading the search, which
Dukakis has said he hopes to complete prior to the Democratic
National Convention in mid-July.
   Dukakis spent a good portion of a media briefing dancing around
the question of whether he would move the embassy in Tel Aviv to
Jerusalem, which Israel considers to be its capital.
   Dukakis said U.S. embassies should ``go where the host nation
says its capital is,'' adding later that the policy was a ``regular
rule of diplomatic courtesy.'' Later, when pressed for a direct
answer on whether he would move the embassy if Israel maintained
Jerusalem was its capital, Dukakis said: ``If Israel determined
that that's where it wants its capital then that is its capital.
I'd put our embassy there.''
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, interviewed Friday by
NBC-TV, said moving the embassy to Jerusalem ``would ruin'' Middle
East peace efforts.
   Shultz who said it would be inappropriate for the United States
to recognize Jerusalem as the Israeli capital because the city is
regarded as occupied territory subject to disputes between Israel
and its Arab neighbors.
   Dukakis said he and Carter had a ``terrific'' meeting and talked
about ``lots of things.'' He refused to be more specific. He said
he expected Carter to campaign for him in the fall. Bush frequently
tries to tie Dukakis to the last Democratic administration.
   On Sunday, Dukakis was to travel to Salt Lake City to speak to
the nation's mayors, kicking off a week in which he will focus on
drug and anti-crime programs.
</TEXT>
