<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Sweden-Soviet     06-11 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sweden-Soviet,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Delegation Studies Swedish Welfare State</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHAN RAPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet delegation has spent two weeks
in capitalist Sweden studying the social welfare system to see
whether any aspect could be used to reform the Soviet economic and
social system.
   ``We are not here to copy, we are here to find efficient methods
that, within our socialistic system, are the most efficient for our
social development,'' Vice Finance Minister Viacheslav Senchagov
said Friday as the delegation ended its visit.
   Sweden is a capitalist country, but its taxes are among the
world's highest. Tax income finances welfare programs which health,
child care and education free for everyone and guarantees liveable
retirement pensions.
   Soviet economic experts and bureacrats examined the Swedish
retraining programs, the tax system, the labor exchange and
cooperative companies. They also visited factories and farms.
   Delegates said Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
``perestroika'' policy was now in its most active stage. It was
most important to increase production while safeguarding social
goals, they said.
   Perestroika means restructuring in Russian and is a buzzword for
Gorbachev's program which seeks to reform the Soviet economy and
social system.
   ``We are looking for a tax system to stimulate innovation and
how to use taxes to get work collectives to use the socialist
property in the best way,'' Senchagov told a news conference.
   Speaking through an interpreter, he said the danger of
perestroika was that it might create economic inequality. In
Sweden, incomes are equalized by a progressive taxes that takes as
much as 78 percent in the top tax brackets.
   The delegation arrived to Sweden on May 29 at the invitation of
social democratic Prime Minister Ingvar Carlsson. It was scheduled
to return to Moscow today.
   Another member of the group, Leonid Abalkin, Director of the
Soviet Academy of Sciences' Institute for Economy, described the
Swedish model as dynamic and efficient.
   ``The social motives and humanistic goals in Sweden ... are very
attractive to us, and we sympathize with the system,'' he said.
   Asked why the Soviet Union had started turning to capitalistic
countries for ideas Abalkin said ``there is nothing peculiar about
the fact that we after 70 years turn to other countries.''
   ``The Socialistic system is open for all positive things in the
world,'' he said.
   Head of delegation, Anatoliy Miliukov, said Sweden's extensive
labor exchange and retraining programs, which include government
subsidies to companies that give workers time off for study, were
of great interest.
   He said that as a result of perestroika the number of officials
at various ministries are being cut down sharply and that in Moscow
alone the number of employed in half of the ministries had been cut
by 30-40 percent.
   ``We have retired a lot of these people, others have been
transferred to other institutions, for instance to research,''
Miliukov said.
</TEXT>
