<1ST_LINE>r w PM-EPA-Dinoseb     06-11 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-EPA-Dinoseb,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Use of Herbicide Halted Except In Limited Instances In Northwest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency says the
last two manufacturers of a weedkiller that can cause birth defects
must stop selling the herbicide, but the agency will allow
short-term continued use on some food products in three
Northwestern states.
   EPA Administrator Lee M. Thomas on Friday announced the agency
has reached a settlement with the two makers of the herbicide
dinoseb that would halt most current sales and distribution of the
product.
   But the government has said Cedar Chemical Corp. and Drexel
Chemical Co., both near Memphis, Tenn., can sell their existing
stock for use during the rest of this year on dry peas, lentils,
chickpeas and green peas in the states of Washington, Oregon and
Idaho. The remaining stock may be used in 1988 and 1989 on berries
in Washington and Oregon.
   EPA spokesman Al Heier said Thomas decided to allow limited
continued use of dinoseb into 1989 although it can cause birth
defects and poses a hazard to men's ability to have children. Heier
said there is no substitute herbicide to treat weeds affecting
certain plants in the Northwest.
   Certain crops ``would have been rather devastated'' if the EPA
had banned the weedkiller altogether, said Heier.
   Heier characterized the exceptions as small and said the tight
restrictions were designed to protect people from exposure to the
chemical.
   Several environmental groups had opposed any further sales of
the weedkiller and any provision allowing for the use of existing
supplies.
   But EPA estimated it would cost $40 million to purchase all
existing supplies of dinoseb from chemical companies and another
$155 million to dispose of it as federal law requires.
   Friday's agreement came as a result of a challenger by Cedar and
Drexel to an EPA emergency ban of dinoseb issued in October 1986.

</TEXT>
