<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TVMarti     06-11 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TV Marti,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Subcommittee Agrees To Spend $7.5 Million For Programming
To Cuba</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From a blimp floating over the Florida Keys, a
proposed U.S. government television service would beam a daily diet
of American news shows, sitcoms and soap operas to the people of
Cuba.
   A Senate Appropriations subcommittee on Friday agreed to spend
$7.5 million to start a TV version of the U.S. Information Agency's
Radio Marti, which has been broadcasting to Cuba since May 1985.
   ``We want to accelerate the free flow of information to our
friends in Cuba and we want to send the message of democracy to
everyone on the island,'' said Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C.,
chairman of the Senate panel that agreed to add the funds to USIA's
1989 budget.
   The USIA budget is to be considered by the full committee on
Thursday next week.
   Cuban-Americans have been pushing the project as a natural and
more effective follow-up to the radio service that is named for
Cuban patriot Jose Marti and devotes its air time to promoting the
cause of freedom in Cuba.
   ``TV Marti would be a much more powerful medium'' for informing
Cubans about world events as well as what is happening in their own
country, said Jorge Mas Canosa, chairman of the presidential
advisory board for Radio Marti.
   A program mix of American, Mexican and South American comedy,
variety and soap operas would easily draw Cuban viewers, he said.
   ``They are anxious to learn about the outside world,'' said Mas,
who heads the Cuban American National Foundation, which helped
found Radio Marti.
   The Radio Marti advisory board recently completed a feasibility
study on television broadcasting to Cuba. Radio signals can easily
reach the island 90 miles off Florida, but TV broadcasting would be
more difficult because of the nature of the signals. A TV
transmitter would have to be high enough to be in direct line of
sight of the island.
   The advisory board said the most feasible option would be to
transmit the signal from a blimp floating over the Florida Keys.
   Mas predicts that TV Marti would be even more successful than
the radio service, which Radio Marti officials estimate reaches
about a quarter of Cuba's 10 million people.
   But others are concerned about the kind of reaction a TV Marti
would elicit from Cuban leader Fidel Castro. As soon Radio Marti
went on the air, Havana retaliated with immigration sanctions,
tried to jam the broadcasting signal and interfered with the
reception of U.S. radio stations by their American audiences.
   U.S. broadcasters are concerned about possible interference from
retaliatory jamming as well as from the U.S. signal transmitted
from the blimp, said William Haratunian, a consultant for the
National Association of Broadcasters on international matters. A TV
signal transmitted so high in the air could cause problems for
American TV stations nearby, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880611-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 0121EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-OPEC Bjt   06-11 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-OPEC, Bjt,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OPEC Ministers Split Over Cutting Oil Production</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEDE prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disagreements among OPEC ministers
meeting here today could cut as much a $2 off the price of a barrel
of oil, benefiting consumers the world over, analysts say.
   One faction of the oil-producing group is pushing for a cut in
production. A Western-oriented camp is bracing to block the move.
   Venezuela, Libya, and Algeria want a production cut to keep oil
prices at $18 a barrel. But a Saudi Arabia-led group has opposed
the idea, which failed to gain the support of oil ministers at this
week's Arab Summit in Algiers, Algeria.
   Twelve of the 28-year-old cartel's members agreed in December to
extend a quota of 15 million barrels a day until June 30. Iraq,
which is at war with Iran, refused to sign the accord because it
demanded a production quota equal to Tehran's.
   Now, the members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries are so divided over production controls that many
analysts expect them to fight over the issue for at least a week _
and then give up. They were expected simply to extend the existing
quota until the end of the year.
   Harry Neustein, a New York-based oil trader who was to observe
the meeting, says the disagreement will cause oil prices to fall.
   ``It's going south, which of course, is great for the
consumer,'' Neustein said.
   Some analysts said the lack of a new accord could force prices
down by as much as $2 a barrel below the organization's target of
$18.
   The oil markets also showed little confidence in the ministers'
ability to reach a consensus. The July contract price of West Texas
Intermediate, the U.S. benchmark crude oil, fell 34 cents to $16.73
a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange on Friday. That was
its lowest level in more than two months.
   In addition, the cartel nations are doing little to help boost
the price. Currently, they are producing an estimated 18.5 million
barrels a day, 3.4 million barrels a day more than their agreement
allows.
   The majority camp, led by Venezuela, wants to cut production to
push oil prices up nearer OPEC's target price. Venezuela ideally
would like to cut production jointly with the interested producers
outside the cartel.
   The non-OPEC members involved in the dialogue with OPEC are
Angola, China, Colombia, Egypt, Mexico, Oman and Malaysia. Norway
is attending the meeting as observer, while Britain is not
represented.
   Venezuela aggressively backed an unsuccessful attempt by
non-OPEC producers in late April to get the cartel to agree to cut
production.
   A minority of four OPEC nations, led by heavyweight Saudi Arabia
_ OPEC's largest producer _ blocked that attempt at the
extraordinary OPEC meeting six weeks ago at which no new agreement
was reached. At the mid-year meeting, the minority opponents of the
plan, again led by Saudi Arabia, want to boost production to match
predictions of an increase in demand in the last six months of
1988, analysts said.
   However, the cartel's members don't even agree on how large
demand will be.
   Estimates range from 17.6 million barrels a day to 18.9 million
barrels a day.
   In the first half of the year, demand was 17.7 million barrels a
day, analysts say.
</TEXT>
