<HEAD>Newspaper: North To Make Million From Speeches</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Marine Lt. Col. Oliver North, with perhaps
50 speaking engagements in front of him this year, could make more
than $1 million, a newspaper reported today.
   The former White House aide will charge $25,000 for a 40-minute
speech _ or about $600 a minute _ several industry sources told The
Miami Herald.
   Bernie Swain, partner in the Washington Speakers Bureau,
exclusive representatives for North, predicted his client will make
as many as 50 appearances this year.
   Swain told the newspaper he has booked 18 dates since North
retired from the Marines Corps in May.
   North, scheduled to be the first Iran-Contra defendant brought
to trial by special counsel Lawrence Walsh, faces up to 85 years in
prison and $4 million in fines for allegedly defrauding the
government and obstructing justice.
   He began his public speaking in May at Liberty University in
Lynchburg, Va., where he received an honorary degree. A
600-square-foot American flag formed the backdrop as evangelist
Jerry Falwell likened North to Jesus Christ. Both were victims
``indicted, convicted and crucified'' by a special prosecutor,
Falwell said.
