<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SubmarineContract     06-11 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Submarine Contract,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fast-Attack Submarine Contracts Awarded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy awarded a contract for two of this
year's fast-attack submarines to a Virginia company and indicated
Connecticut-based Electric Boat can win the third sub only if it
lowers its price.
   The Newport News Shipbuilding and Drydock Co. won a $612 million
contract on Friday to build two SSN-688 Los Angeles-class
submarines, scheduled to be completed in August 1993.
   Newport News outbid Electric Boat, a division of General
Dynamics Corp., said Navy Lt. Brian Cullin.
   The Navy said it would negotiate with Electric Boat to get a
lower price on the third submarine, Cullin said.
   The announcement is a disappointment for Electric Boat, which
lost out on last year's fast-attack sub competition 4-0 to its
Virginia-based arch rival. Both companies rely heavily on the Navy
contracts.
   Navy officials told Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn., that Electric
Boat raised its bid at the final stage of the contract competition,
a time when companies usually lower their offers, said Gejdenson
aide Chip Partner. It was not known why Electric Boat hiked its
price. Electric Boat spokesman Neil Ruenzel declined comment.
   In a prepared statement, the company said the loss illustrates
that price ``is the acknowledged driver in today's defense industry
environment,'' and that Electric Boat will have to lower labor
costs to compete with Newport News.
   Electric Boat is in negotiations with unionized workers for a
new contract. The current contract expires June 30.
   ``The major cost in our submarine construction is labor. Newport
News, our competitor, has lower labor costs. Today's announcement
is a clear mandate for Electric Boat to hold labor costs in line
and to re-examine all possible options to lowering other key costs
elements,'' said Electric Boat in a prepared statement issued
Friday.
   Ruenzel said it was ``too early'' to assess the potential impact
on employment.
   Union officials could not be reached late Friday for comment.
   The SSN-688 submarine, a 6,900-ton vessel as long as a
professional football field, is designed to hunt down enemy surface
ships and subs. They are armed with Mark 48 anti-submarine
torpedoes, Harpoon missiles and Tomahawk cruise missiles.
   The two sub builders have been competing for the fast-attack sub
contracts since the first award in 1970. Electric Boat has won 31
SSN-688 contracts. Friday's awards brings Newport News' total up to
27.
   Last year, Newport News won all four fast-attack submarines
awarded by the Navy. In 1986, Electric Boat won all four contracts.
   The sub contracts are enormously important to the shipyards.
Electric Boat is the region's largest private employer, with 18,000
workers at its main plant in Groton, Conn., and 6,000 at its yard
in North Kingstown, R.I.
   Newport News has more than 26,000 workers at the Virginia
shipyard.
   In Virginia, Newport News spokesman Jack Schnaedter said: ``A
contract of this size adds a certain degree of long-range stability
to our work force, and it's good news for the yard to get two of
them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
