<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 0911EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-AnotherLook:FarmCredit Adv13   06-11 1181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Another Look: Farm Credit, Adv 13,1210</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, June 13, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Results of Farm Credit Legislation Still Not Clear</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARGARET BAUMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OTIS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agricultural Credit Act of 1987 initially
appeared to be a lifeline for ranchers and farmers drowning in debt
to federal loan programs.
   Yet five months after President Reagan signed the bill and
federal officials hailed it as a critical step toward helping rural
landowners hold onto their acres, ``the jury is still out'' for
thousands of borrowers on billions of dollars in delinquent loans.
   In the first quarter of this year, the act helped 8,500
``distressed'' loans to be restructured so farmers and ranchers
could keep their properties, according to Ruth Ross, spokeswoman
for the Farm Credit Corporation of America.
   But many other farmers owe their money to the Farmers Home
Administration, whose regulations under the act are not yet
settled, and some have been unable to apply for the aid provided by
the landmark legislation.
   The borrower-owned Farm Credit System of banks and lending
cooperatives lost $4.8 billion from 1985 through last year, said H.
Brent Beesley, president of the Farm Credit Corporation of America,
which oversees the Farm Credit System.
   The system's problems, coupled with land devaluation and low
crop prices, were forcing thousands of farms onto the auction
block, Beesley said.
   The act provides up to $4 billion in federal funds to
financially troubled farm credit institutions through 1992,
protecting farmers' stock in those banks and cooperatives.
   It also requires farm loans to be restructured _ changing the
terms in some way so the debt can still be repaid _ if that would
cost less than foreclosure.
   Until the legislation passed, loan restructuring was a voluntary
effort, said Jeff Oates, a spokesman for the Farm Credit
Corporation. ``Now the law says, `You will restructure.'''
   ``I think it's working just fine,'' Beesley said of the
legislation. ``Investors have greater confidence in the system, and
so do borrowers. We're very pleased with the act.''
   But at the office of the Coalition to Save Rural America, based
in this plains town in northeastern Colorado, the hotline rings
steadily.
   ``It's sort of a big question mark,'' said Bill Glover, who
estimated he had fielded hundreds of calls about the act. ``Because
of the complexities in borrowing practices, what happens in one
lending institution could affect them in another federal
institution.''
   The major stumbling block in the process arises from the
structure of the federal lending agencies and the pattern of how
farmers borrow.
   Many farmers have multiple loans spread among the various
lenders. The 37 Farm Land Banks, for example, make long-term land
loans, and the 387 lending cooperatives known as Production Credit
Associations make short-term operating loans.
   Those agencies come under the Farm Credit System. But the
Farmers Home Administration, which makes both types of loans, is
supervised by the U.S. Department of Agriculture, and rules for the
FmHA are still in the public approval process.
   The FmHA has balked at going along with restructuring plans for
borrowers that hold its loans as well as others, fearing
vulnerability.
   ``I had a case over in the Western Slope where the lender at the
Federal Land Bank said they would work anything out with the
farmer, as long as the FmHA would agree to it,'' Glover said.
``FmHA couldn't agree to anything because the rules and regulations
weren't out yet _ and they don't know what they can agree to.''
   Jerry Slaugh, a consultant who helps farmers with restructuring,
predicted it might take until January for the FmHA to be absorbed
into the act.
   ``Until then, anyone with a Farmers Home Administration loan is
just in limbo,'' he said. ``It's just putting a litte bit of a
shadow on our efforts out there because they (FmHA) are not ready
to sit down at the table and negotiate about restructuring.''
   So far this year, Slaugh says he has saved 10 farms by
restructuring loans. He is working on about 50 more with Bill
Byers, a former farmer and his partner in Ag Management
Consultants, based in Grand Junction.
   The company has a contract with the state's rural job training
program to help indebted farmers. It also has clients with loans
from Federal Land Banks in the Wichita, Kan., district.
   Slaugh estimated that those banks hold about 40,000 loans in
Colorado, New Mexico, Kansas and Oklahoma, and that 4,000 of them
are distressed, meaning they are delinquent or potentially
deliquent. That's about half as many as a few years ago.
   ``The new legislation has given us more tools,'' he said. ``At
this point, the jury is still out. We've had some success _ not as
much as we'd like to see. (But) compared to when we started three
years ago, it's a world of difference.''
   Terry Gutschenritter, vice president of special credit for the
Farm Credit System in Wichita, said his agency last year opened a
special credit department for distressed loans and was able to
``bring back'' about 45 percent of 5,000 loans so families could
stay on their farms, he said.
   For farmers and ranchers with distressed loans, the crucial step
is to respond quickly to notices from lenders, warned John Stencel,
president of the Rocky Mountain Farmers Union, a grass-roots
general farm organization with 18,000 members in Colorado, New
Mexico and Wyoming.
   ``Borrowers are currently receiving letters from the Farm Credit
System advising them of their rights to ask for their loans to be
restructured,'' Stencel said. ``If borrowers don't respond within
45 days, Farm Credit can begin foreclosure.
   ``If farmers miss the deadline, they still have the right to
request restructuring, but the cost of foreclosure may diminish
chances of restructuring as (the less expensive) alternative.''
   Agriculture attorneys Judith A. Shively and Joseph Dworkin,
partners with offices near the state Capitol in Denver, see the
1987 legislation as a tool _ particularly because it obligates the
lender to notify the borrower before any foreclosure action is
taken.
   ``We have found ... farmers as a group have always been
hard-working, God-fearing people who have paid their debts, and now
they find they can't pay their debts,'' Dworkin said. ``And when
you have to ask that type of an individual to file bankruptcy, you
get tremendous resistance.
   But farmers today ``have to be aware of every single government
program and use it to the max,'' he said. They also must know what
it takes to grow cattle or crops _ and be good money managers, too,
he said.
   Many farmers in trouble today meet those criteria, but bad
weather and the economy bring them to the Rural Coalition,
consultants like Slaugh and attorneys who are experts in
agricultural law.
   ``The legislation will be beneficial, but it won't eliminate the
farm crisis,'' Gutschenritter said. ``A positive income situation _
better prices _ is what is needed.
   ``I think it's going to be a much wiser farm credit system as a
result of these times. It will make us tougher, better farmers.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, June 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
