<DOCNO> AP880611-0188 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 0641EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv13   06-11 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 13,0564</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Monday June 13</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Long- Vs. Short-Term View</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Over the past two decades U.S. industry has
shucked a lot of its old bad habits, and now is the better for
having done so.
   Looking back, it's evident that the change wasn't motivated so
much by enthusiasm as by fear _ by the fear, for example, that
foreign manufacturers might steal not just foreign markets but U.S.
markets too.
   Old habits are comfortable habits, and many U.S. companies
preferred the old ways and so disappeared from the scene. So did
typically American products, such as television sets and
calculators. Asia took over the business.
   Some industries fought back, cutting their corporate
bureacracies, closing inefficient operations, ending waste,
resolving labor-management battles, updating factories with robots
and electronic controls.
   In short, U.S. industry in the past 15 years or so has become
leaner, smarter, meaner and more competitive. Still, there remains
a gaping weakness that could offset many of the modern improvements.
   That weakness is the inability of many U.S. companies to rapidly
transform new technology, much of it developed in the United
States, into profitable products.
   That in itself would be reason to worry, but there is an added
dimension to the problem: Quick transformation, or exploitation, is
the very skill of some Japanese and other Asian producers of
high-technology products.
   More than half of over 500 U.S. executives, academics and state
officials surveyed recently said that a major barrier to
competitiveness is the excessive time lag in converting technology
to new commercial products.
   That study, sponsored by the Conference Board, the National
Governors' Association and the National Science Foundation, found
that an old bugaboo of U.S. industrial management might be a
primary source of the problem.
   That bugaboo: the seeming inability of American business to
focus on long-term goals, to have a distant vision of the future
rather than a nearsighted fixation on the short term.
   It doesn't take a study to realize two of the reasons why:
   _U.S. corporate executives are paid and promoted for turning out
products today, not tomorrow. Ironically, in focusing on
``today's'' products, they end up turning out those of yesterday.
Competitors beat them.
   A flow of products results from long-term rather than short-term
goals. Yet, according to the survey, American business still
indicates a tendency to become impatient with the long-term view.
   _U.S. industry is under constant pressure to produce profits
now, not tomorrow.
   Executives have a limited time in which to prove themselves.
While they might believe that a corporate shakeup will show results
five years down the road, they must deal with the possibility they
might be fired before then.
   Therefore, they go with what they consider the tried and true
and often old-fashioned products.
   In addition, the U.S. investment climate is such that Wall
Street brokers demand immediate results. In fact, there is pressure
on executives of some companies to show results not in the next
year but in the next quarter or two.
   It creates a baffling paradox, one that American industry must
resolve if it is to keep pace with the often smaller, more agile
entrepreneurs of Southeast Asia.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Monday June 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880611-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 0644EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv11-12   06-11 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 11-12,0702</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 11</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 12</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions June 11-12 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Market Awaits New Junk Bond Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Traders and investors alike are scrounging for
new junk in the credit markets.
   They are eagerly awaiting the high-yield, high-risk junk bonds
that will be issued to help finance many of the mergers and
acquisitions that have taken place recently on the corporate
takeover trail.
   ``There have been a number of deals completed in the last two
months where it is anticipated that (junk bond) financing will be
accomplished,'' said Michael Dahood, a high-yield bond analyst at
Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   He said British industrialist Brian Beazer is likely to use junk
bonds to finance at least some of his $1.7 billion buyout of the
Pittsburgh-based cement company, Koppers Co.
   ``And American Standard Inc. is almost certain to come to market
at some point,'' he added, referring to the $2.5 billion leveraged
buyout of the company that is being led by Kelso & Co.
   It also is anticipated that Toronto retailer Robert Campeau will
raise more than $1 billion through the sale of junk bonds to
facilitate his acquisition of Federated Department Stores Inc.
Campeau also is likely to rely on junk bonds to finance the spinoff
of Ralph's supermarket chain as a subsidiary.
   ``Some of the takeovers do create very large issues, and that
alone is a sudden injection of product into the market,'' said
Robert Waill, a managing director at L.F. Rothschild, Unterberg,
Towbin.
   ``In terms of getting business going, I suppose it's good _ it
does create a certain amount of motion,'' he said.
   A slowdown in mergers and acquisitions since the market crash
resulted in a reduced supply of new junk bond issues. ``That may be
contributing to the richness of the market,'' Dahood said referring
to the high prices at which are selling and trading.
   Conversely, yields on many of these debt issues are not as
handsome as they have been historically. Dahood characterized
current returns as ``rather skimpy.''
   When comparing relative yields, ``the junk bond market is
providing a rather skimpy incremental return to the Treasury market
at the 10-year issuance,'' he said.
   Because high-yield debt securities often are issued for 10-year
terms, they typically are measured against the 10-year Treasury
bill.
   Junk bonds currently are trading about 425 to 475 basis points
above the 10-year Treasury bill, which is hovering just under 9
percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point.
   In the past, however, junk bonds have traded as much as 600
basis points above the government security, and, more recently, 500
to 550 basis points above, Dahood said.
   Putting it another way, ``the premium for accepting the risk
today is somewhat smaller than it has been,'' he noted.
   In addition to the takeover issues that might revive the market,
some analysts say corporations are being driven to lock in
fixed-rate debt as overall interest rates move higher.
   ``Companies that launched leveraged buyouts late last year and
financed them with bank and bridge loans at floating rates are now
getting nervous as interest rates move up,'' noted Gail Hessol,
managing director of industrial rating at Standard and Poor's Corp.
   One attractive option is to sell fixed-rate public debt.
   Despite the high level of risk associated with junk bonds and
allegations of scandal and wrongdoing at Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc., the pioneer in junk-bond underwriting, investor interest
remains keen.
   Some estimate there are some $160 billion in outstanding junk
bonds, with as much as 10 percent held by individuals as opposed to
institutional investors.
   A surge in junk-bond mutual funds is also making the high-yield
instrument more accessible to the average investor. Quoting from a
recent government study, Dahood said there were 23 junk bond mutual
funds in 1981 with assets of $3.1 billion; by Sept. 30, 1987, the
number had mushroomed to 72, and their assets totaled more than $30
billion.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions June 11-12</NOTE>
