<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions June 11-12</NOTE>
<HEAD>Central Bankers, Others Paint Picture Of Economic Stability</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gathering of top-level executives from the
world's biggest banks produced a picture of economic harmony,
supported by improved trade, stable exchange rates and healthy
growth.
   While few economists would dispute those assertions, made this
past week at the 34th annual International Monetary Conference in
Chicago, many agreed the current state of affairs, particularly
involving currencies, was more a product of inertia than
policymaking.
   ``Policy is on hold,'' said Robert A. Brusca, chief economist
for Nikko Securities Co. International in New York. ``The
policymakers are kind of hemmed in. They don't know what to do.''
   Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan made it clear
during the three-day Chicago meeting that he didn't want the dollar
to fall any further, for fear it could harm ongoing attempts to
reduce the huge U.S. trade deficit.
   Greenspan told a separate press briefing the ``adjustment
process,'' by which the dollar has been allowed to depreciate over
the past three years to enhance the U.S. trade picture by making
exports less expensive abroad, ``has made significant progress.''
   But he said since manufacturers already are running at or near
capacity levels due to healthy export growth, further dollar
declines wouldn't help them sell more goods overseas or anywhere
else, facilitating inflationary pressures.
   Bundesbank President Karl Otto Poehl and Bank of France Governor
Jacques de Larosiere publicly agreed with Greenspan. Poehl also
made assurances that his country wasn't trying to drive down the
U.S. currency, discounting recent dollar sales as a routine effort
to trim dollar reserves.
   Other central bankers at the conference included: Bank of
England Governor Robin Leigh-Pemberton, Bank of Mexico Director
General Miguel Mancera and Takeshi Ohta, deputy governor for
international relations for the Bank of Japan.
   Some currency traders and economists remained skeptical about
the underlying motives of West Germany and about how long the major
industrialized nations could maintain stability.
   David H. Resler, chief economist for Nomura Securities Inc. in
New York, said, ``There seems to be an emerging technical reason
for the dollar to be on the firm side in the next month or so,''
partly due to U.S. agricultural sales to the Soviets and Chinese.
   He said the Bundesbank might privately be ``trying to temper the
upward pressure of the dollar that might emerge. A rise in the
dollar, should it occur, would bring instability in the markets
because it's not sustainable.''
   Economists say the upbeat picture publicly presented by the
central bankers this past week amounted to an ``open-mouth policy''
clearly aimed at maintaining the narrow trading range for
currencies that has existed in recent months.
   ``There's PR and hot air involved here ... They want to enhance
the view that they are unified in the open. They prefer the
status,'' said F. Ward McCarthy, chief financial economist for
Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   But there are drawbacks to resisting change, economists say.
   For one thing, ``there's no lure to foreign capital to make
currency gains on their dollar holdings,'' said Brusca.
   ``As long as they hold the dollar in this narrow trading range
you have monetary policy effectively transmitted as though it were
a fixed-rate system,'' said Brusca. ``And even though the rates in
this sytem are `fixed' they're not really fixed and you can't be
sure the floor under the dollar is solid and dependable.''
   The currency markets have been trading on a ``floating rate''
system since early 1973, following about three decades of fixed
rates that grew out of the historic post-World War II Bretton Woods
agreement.
   The stage was set for a drop in the dollar in September 1985,
when the United States and its four major trading partners agreed
to devalue the currency to help reduce the U.S. trade shortfall and
stave off protectionist legislation. Last year, however, that same
group agreed that further decines in the dollar's value would be
``counterproductive.''
   In the last three years, the dollar has lost half its value
against such currencies as the West German mark and Japanese yen.
It has fallen less against the currencies of such major trading
partners as Canada, South Korea, Hong Kong and Taiwan.
</TEXT>
