<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions June 11-12</NOTE>
<HEAD>Glut Of Frozen Pork Bellies Is Good News For BLT Lovers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be followed later in cycle with an ADD containing weekly
price trends</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Lovers of bacon-lettuce-and-tomato sandwiches may be inclined to
add an extra layer of bacon to their BLTs this summer.
   A glut of frozen pork bellies forced futures prices into a
virtual free fall this past week and analysts say retail prices for
bacon, which is made from pork bellies, will likely plummet as well.
   The futures market for frozen pork bellies was created to ensure
adequate supplies of bellies during the summer, when demand for
bacon peaks and supplies of slaughter-ready hogs traditionally
bottoms out. Dealers typically stockpile pork bellies in freezers
during the fall and winter, then thaw them out and slice them into
bacon during the late spring and summer.
   Last year, light hog production resulted in tight supplies of
frozen pork bellies for the summer months and futures prices soared
last summer above 90 cents a pound, a five-year high.
   Dealers compensated by packing away lots of pork bellies during
last fall and winter. They put so many bellies in cold storage that
supplies swelled to nearly 103 million pounds by May 1, more than
double the previous year's May 1 figure and the third largest total
on record for that date, according to the Agriculture Department.
   ``This year they got carried away when they put bellies into
storage,'' said Chuck Levitt, an analyst in Chicago with Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc.
   ``They went from a period of deficit to one of tremendous
surplus in one year because they overcompensated for having run out
last summer,'' he said.
   Because of this abundance, the price on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange for July delivery of frozen pork bellies has plunged 11
percent already this month, from 56.32 cents a pound on May 31 to
50.07 cents on Friday.
   Analysts said they expected the decline to continue until prices
fall low enough to stimulate demand _ possibly as low as 40 cents a
pound.
   And those prices are certain to filter down to the retail level,
analysts said.
   ``They should be able to offer relatively attractive bacon
prices this summer,'' said Dale Durccholz, an analyst with
AgriVisor Services Inc. in Bloomington, Ill.
   In addition to the large supplies of frozen pork bellies, the
market faces good supplies of higher-quality fresh bellies caused
by an unseasonably high number of hog slaughters, analysts said.
   Packers have not cut down on kills because low cash prices for
pork products have narrowed their profit margins, said Tom O'Hare,
an analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. in New York.
   And Durccholz said some hog producers, faced with rising feed
costs due to the spring drought, may be partially liquidating their
herds, thus adding to the number of animals available for slaughter.
   O'Hare said frozen pork belly futures prices may rebound briefly
before sliding lower.
   ``Technically, the bellies have definitely got to be oversold at
this point,'' he said. ``It's low enough that at some point soon,
you've got to get people saying `Hey, this is overdone,' and going
in and buying it.''
</TEXT>
