<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions June 11-12</NOTE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: ... buying it.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are some commodity price trends for the past week:
   Grain and soybean futures moved sharply higher on the Chicago
Board of Trade.
   Wheat for delivery in July settled Friday at $3.73} a bushel
compared with $3.62} a week earlier; July corn advanced to $2.57} a
bushel from $2.34{; July oats soared to $2.60 a bushel from $1.96{;
and July soybeans rallied to $8.84 a bushel from $8.49.
   Livestock and meat futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   June live cattle fell to 72.32 cents a pound from 72.65 cents;
August feeder cattle dropped to 75.25 cents a pound from 75.92
cents; June live hogs slipped to 51.15 cents a pound from 52.45
cents; and July frozen pork bellies plunged to 50.07 cents a pound
from 55.55 cents.
   Precious metals futures fell steeply on the Commodity Exchange
in New York.
   August gold settled Friday at $453.30 a troy ounce compared with
$469.30; July silver dropped to $7.015 a troy ounce from $7.270.
   Energy futures slid lower on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil for July delivery fell to
$16.73 a barrel from $17.50; July heating oil slumped to 44.25
cents a gallon from 47.13 cents; and July heating oil slipped to
49.22 cents a gallon from 50.89 cents.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions June 11-12</NOTE>
